<HEAD>Navy Has Equipment To Recover Stricken Jet's Cargo Door</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 5 grafs after 4th graf, `Investigators suspect ...,
to UPDATE with first lawsuits filed; picks up 5th graf pvs: `Capt. David
...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has equipment capable of recovering the cargo door that sank in 16,800 feet of water after tearing away from a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jumbo jet, an undersea technician said. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> has not decided whether to attempt to recover the door from the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> 85 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>, said member <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON>. He said, however, that examining the front cargo door would be `` very helpful to us in our analysis.'' <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> radar tracked a large object falling into the ocean about 45 seconds after the pilot of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>'s Flight 811 reported an in-flight emergency early Friday soon after taking off for <LOCATION> Auckland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> said Tuesday night. Investigators suspect the cargo door popped open at 22,000 feet, tearing away with a large section of fuselage. Nine passengers seated on the right side of the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 jet were swept to their deaths. The first lawsuits stemming from the accident were filed here Wednesday. <PERSON> Mae </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sapolu </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> flight attendant from <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>, filed a state court lawsuit seeking unspecified damages from <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, maker of the jumbo jet. According to court documents, <PERSON> Sapolu </PERSON> was serving drinks in business class when the hole opened in the right side of the aircraft. <PERSON> Sapolu </PERSON> said she was thrown to the floor and had to cling to the leg of a seat to keep from being swept out of the plane. <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Tudor </PERSON> a passenger from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, also sought unspecified damages in his lawsuit filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, accusing from <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> of neglect in maintaining the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747. <PERSON> Sapolu </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tudor </PERSON> said they suffered physical injuries and emotional distress. Capt. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cronin </PERSON> turned the crippled jet around and flew it 100 miles on two of four engines, landing safely at <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. `` The radar picked up something that could be a large piece of metal, possibly the cargo door,'' <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> said. `` That information is going back to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION><LOCATION> , </LOCATION> <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, to see if we can indeed determine ... that was the cargo door, and its exact location.'' `` We have the location at the surface of the water,'' he said. `` You're talking about three miles -LRB- down -RRB-, one can only guess where that is.'' <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolcott </PERSON>, a technician and submersible launch pilot at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hawaii </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Hawaii </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Undersea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION>, said it would be difficult but probably not impossible to find the cargo door. A search for the door probably would begin with a towed underwater sonar sled to determine possible locations of the door and then the use of a remote operation vehicle equipped with a camera to pinpoint the location, <PERSON> Wolcott </PERSON> said Wednesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has ROVs capable of hooking a line to the door so it could be pulled to the surface, he said. The least likely possibility because of the tremendous expense involved would be the use of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s San Diego-based Sea Cliff, one of the world's few manned submersibles capable of reaching that depth, <PERSON> Wollcott </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION>'s field work was nearly completed and investigators would leave <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> by Thursday. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Guyette </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>'s executive vice president for operations, said the damaged jetliner will be repaired, although there was no estimate on when it will be returned to service. The air frame will be fixed in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> and the engines will be repaired in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Guyette </PERSON> told a news conference here Wednesday. About 10 of the passengers who were on Flight 811 remain in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> as well as a few survivors of the missing and <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> is paying all expenses, <PERSON> Guyette </PERSON> said. Two <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> flight attendants are the only ones on the plane who remain hospitalized.
