<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gaining weight accompanies gaining office for many members of the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. Lunches with lobbyists, snacks during committee meetings and rounds of receptions and late-night dinners at the state capital's leading restaurants make staying thin as tough as _ and sometimes tougher _ than getting re-elected Just talk to Delegates <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Counihan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Elijah </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cummings </PERSON>, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rawlings </PERSON>, and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> McCaffrey </PERSON>. The foursome top the scales at 1,200 pounds collectively and, in a well-publicized weigh-in, they vowed to lose weight by the end of the assembly's 90-day session. `` There are just too many opportunities for too much eating,'' said <PERSON> Counihan </PERSON>, who put on 25 pounds during his first year in <LOCATION> Annapolis </LOCATION> six years ago and has steadily gained since then. Delegate <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Palumbo </PERSON>, who picked up a few pounds each session until he hit 200, said he understood his problem graphically when he started looking at photographs taken during his <LOCATION> Annapolis </LOCATION> career: `` Me getting fatter and fatter and fatter.'' `` It's hard. There is food everywhere,'' <PERSON> Palumbo </PERSON> said. `` You go to a reception and you are talking with someone about something important to them. They have a drink in their hand, you have a drink. They are plucking shrimp off a shrimp tree, so you pluck some, too. ... You end up eating both sides of an issue.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BLACKSBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Wildlife specialist <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bromley </PERSON> has a way to get rid of mosquitoes in the yard: put up a bat house, which is similar to a bird house except it attracts a different type of winged occupant. `` A bat might eat up 2,000 mosquitoes every night,'' said <PERSON> Bromley </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Extension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION>. `` If you have six or seven bats in your house, that's more than 10,000 mosquitoes.'' Besides, a bat house can be entertaining for homeowners, <PERSON> Bromley </PERSON> said. `` On a summer night, you just have to get a lawn chair, sit it outside and wait to see if a bat flits out the bat house,'' <PERSON> Bromley </PERSON> said. `` They're great fliers, so they have aesthetic appeal. Plus, it's fun to have guests look at your bat house and say, ` There's no hole in the front. Then you can say, ` That's a bat house,' and have a lot of fun talking about it around your place.'' <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION> said people can get free plans for a bat house by sending in a self-addressed, stamped envelope. But so far, the <ORGANIZATION> Extension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> has not been going bats answering requests: it has n't received any inquiries yet.
</TEXT>
