<HEAD>Four Young Sisters' Suicide Bid An Attempt To Help Impoverished Parents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four young daughters of a poor factory worker swallowed rat poison in a suicide attempt aimed at easing the family's economic plight and enabling their brother to get an education, police said today. The youngest girl, 6, died. The others, aged 8, 10 and 13, were in serious condition. Their mother, <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Ok-soon </PERSON>, found the girls in the family's rented two-room apartment when she returned from grocery shopping Monday. Their 3-year-old brother was nearby _ unharmed. Police said the eldest daughter, Soon-mi, 13, regained consciousness and told police the sisters decided to kill themselves because it would leave more money for the parents and for education expenses to raise their brother. <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> newspapers quoted the girls' teachers as saying they studied hard and were quiet, model students. But a neighborhood store owner said Soon-mi recently told him she could not afford $ 5.80 worth of notebooks and pencils she needed for school and asked to pay later. The father, <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-bum </PERSON>, 44, supported the family of seven on $ 362 a month in factory wages, police said.
