<HEAD>Walls To Go Up In Warsaw For Uncensored Graffiti</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Graffiti has become such a scourge in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> that city authorities intend to erect walls where people can scrawl whatever they please without fear of censorship, a spokesman for the mayor says. In <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, graffiti usually carries a political message and is most often quickly painted over by authorities with dull hues that accentuate the eyesore. Graffiti and other vandalism cost the city more than $ 1.8 million last year, and slogans scrawled during a `` happening'' Friday near <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>'s main department store caused $ 9,000 in damage, authorities say. Municipal officials decided Monday to build the free-speech graffiti walls at locations still to be decided, said <PERSON> Zbigniew </PERSON> <PERSON> Kopka </PERSON>, the mayor's spokesman. `` Everyone will have a chance to express themselves, if only the paint is no longer sprayed on the walls of our buildings or underground passageways,'' he said Tuesday. Scrawling on walls has a long tradition in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. A cross-and-anchor symboly with the initials `` PW'' for `` <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> is Fighting,'' became a national symbol of resistance during World War II.
