<HEAD>CBS Comes on Strong, But NBC Extends Its Nielsen Streak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Even <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Capone </PERSON> and <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> <PERSON> Smart </PERSON> were no match for <LOCATION> Victoria </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Principal </LOCATION> in a TV movie called `` Naked Lie,'' whose strong performance helped <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> remain out of last place for the fourth time in five weeks. `` The 31st Annual Grammy Awards'' also helped <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> take second place last week. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> has won every week except for one tie with CBS. Never mind that the <ORGANIZATION> Grammys </ORGANIZATION> had its lowest rating ever, 16.0, and ranked 26th. It still did better than <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> usually does on Wednesday nights. Another strong performer for <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> was a special two-hour `` <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>'' that wound up with the highest-rated episode of the durable night-time soap so far this season. It had a 17.9 and was ranked 17th. Principal's thriller `` Naked Lie'' vanquished <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` The Revenge of Al Capone'' and <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s reunion movie `` Get Smart, Again!'' to win Sunday night and finish ninth in the weekly <ORGANIZATION> A.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nielsen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> ratings. Otherwise, the usual suspects rounded up the top 10: `` The Cosby Show,'' <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>; `` A Different World,'' <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>; `` Roseanne,'' <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>; `` 60 Minutes,'' CBS; `` Cheers,'' <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>; `` Murder, She Wrote,'' CBS; `` Golden Girls,'' <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>; `` Who's the Boss?'' <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Dear John'' finished 10th, behind `` Naked Lie.'' <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>, which at 36 straight weeks is creeping up on <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>' record 40-week victory streak from 1962-63, won the week that ended Sunday with an average, prime-time rating of 16.2. <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> had a 14.6. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> had 11.7. Each rating point represents 904,000 households with televisions. The share is a percentage of sets in use. Taking the three network news anchors to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s funeral did n't seem to produce extra ratings. The `` CBS Evening News'' had a rating of 11.7 and a 20 share. `` ABC World News Tonight'' had an 11.5 and 20 share. `` NBC Nightly News'' had an 11.0 and 20 share. The lowest-rated prime-time network shows of the week were: `` Mission Impossible,'' `` Dolphin Cove,'' `` West 57th,'' `` Almost Grown,'' `` <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> 75th Anniversary,'' `` Great Circuses of the World,'' `` TV 101,'' `` HeartBeat,'' `` A Fine Romance'' and `` <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>'s Law.''
