<HEAD>Judge Orders Drug Smuggler To Hand Over Millions or Face An Extra
10 Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>READING, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judge gave a convicted drug smuggler this choice: hand over nearly $ 2.95 million or have another decade added to your 8 -LCB- - year jail sentence <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> French </PERSON>, 37, did not say in court Tuesday whether he would pay up _ the law gives him a year to come up with the cash _ or serve the extra time. The seizure, ordered by Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Murchie </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> Reading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, was the heaviest so far under <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s new Drug Trafficking Act, which allows courts to confiscate the proceeds of illegal drug smuggling. The court convicted French in August of plotting to smuggle 790 pounds of marijuana into <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> with the help of an <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> France </ORGANIZATION> employee. His sentencing was postponed until Tuesday for an inquiry into his assets. During a hearing on the assets, <PERSON> Murchie </PERSON> was told of <LOCATION> French </LOCATION>'s various aliases, his 21 bank accounts in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and his companies or other interests in <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> The judge said Tuesday that he assessed French's assets from drug smuggling at $ 4.3 million, with $ 2.95 million recoverable.
