<HEAD>Dollar Closes Up 0.53 Yen, Stocks Down Marginally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar firmed against the Japanese yen Wednesday, while share prices declined in active trading. The dollar opened at 126.97 yen, the day's low, and moved up to 127.81 yen at one point before closing at 127.68 yen, up 0.53 yen from Tuesday's close. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 300.17-point loser Tuesday, shed another 21.30 points, closing at 31,964.30. Traders attributed the comeback to an 8.03-point gain in the Dow Jones industrial average in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> overnight and to correction of the previous day's loss, which they attributed to technical factors unrelated to economic news. Tuesday's loss in the Nikkei, the market's main barometer, was the biggest since Nov. 28, when it shed 380.27 points. The index had been reaching new highs in recent trading days. In foreign exchange trading, the dollar opened the day at 126.97 yen, down 0.18 yen from Tuesday's 127.15-yen finish. Dealers said the dollar strengthened because of high demand at the start of the new month.
