<HEAD>Postal Service Welcomes Legislation on Government Look-Alike Mail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> wants to zero in on direct-mail groups that try to look like the government and sound like the government in order to get consumers to open their checkbooks. Private fund-raising appeals made to look as if they are from government agencies are among the biggest consumer complaints inadequately addressed by current law, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Swagerty </PERSON>, assistant chief postal inspector for criminal investigations, told a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Governmental Affairs subcommittee Tuesday. <PERSON> Swagerty </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Subcommittee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> at a hearing that he endorsed legislation introduced by <PERSON> Sens </PERSON>. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>, R-Pa., and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ark </LOCATION>., requiring eye-catching `` look-alike'' mail to carry a clear notice on the envelope disclaiming any connection with the federal The bill would deal with ads such as those that appear to come from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mint, from agencies offering surplus property or from the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> offering `` some inside track for obtaining mining rights in public lands,'' <PERSON> Swagerty </PERSON> said. Currently, the Postal Service can do little to stop thousands of pieces of mail it finds deceptive. For example, a private group's fund-raising appeal that said `` important <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> request enclosed'' was not deemed illegal because the contents showed that it was not actually from the government, said <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. Under the proposed legislation, the envelope _ as well as the contents _ would require a notice that it is a private solicitation. Under penalty of fines, the bill would require a similar disclaimer for envelopes with official-looking seals or colors and for organizations with important-sounding names such as the `` Federal Record Service.'' The record service sent letters `` worded to intimidate unsuspecting parents into believing they must obtain a Social Security number for their newborn child,'' Sen. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lieberman </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>., told the panel He said the group charged $ 10, even though anyone can get a number from the government at no charge. An entity called the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> sponsored a $ 50,000 sweepstakes, prompting a confused constituent to ask <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> when the government got into the `` gambling business.''
