<HEAD>Witnesses Receive Federal Protection to Testify</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two witnesses in the hijacking trial of <PERSON> Fawaz </PERSON> <PERSON> Younis </PERSON> said they and their families were uprooted from the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and given new identities to protect against possible terrorist reprisal for their testimony. The Lebanese passenger and Jordanian flight attendant are among four witnesses who have so far identified <PERSON> Younis </PERSON> as the leader of five heavily armed men who stormed aboard a <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jordanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airliner </ORGANIZATION> on June 11, 1985, and held about 70 passengers and crew members hostage for 30 hours. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Aubrey </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> instructed courtroom artists not to sketch the two witnesses as they testified Tuesday. Two American passengers also have identified hijackers, who took control of the airplane in an effort to publicize their efforts to force Palestinian refugees to leave <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Younis </PERSON>, 30, has pleaded innocent to a six-count sky piracy indictment. The trial in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> is a test of a 1984 law in which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> asserts `` long-arm'' jurisdiction over cases involving Americans taken hostage overseas. The protection given the witnesses and their families shows the lengths to which the government has gone to bring <PERSON> Younis </PERSON> to trial, beginning with his dramatic capture on a boat near <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> two years after the hijacking. One of the protected witnesses, <PERSON> Mouin </PERSON> <PERSON> Ajam </PERSON>, 24, said he originally went to jail for five days rather than testify. `` I was concerned about the danger to my parents,'' said <PERSON> Ajam </PERSON>, a Lebanese who was one of the passengers. <PERSON> Ajam </PERSON>, his wife and their infant son are living under new identities at an undisclosed location. Flight attendant <PERSON> Sawson </PERSON> <PERSON> Odetalleh </PERSON>, 22, testified that federal authorities had moved her, her mother, sister, brother-in-law and five nieces and nephews to this country under new names to guard them against revenge. `` If I would come out to testify in the <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION>, I would be sure 100 percent that it would jeopardize my family,'' the Jordanian native said. Miss <PERSON> Odetalleh </PERSON> testified that shortly after the hijackers rushed onto the aircraft, one demanded that she identify plainclothes Jordanian security guards on board and asked a colleague to hand him a knife. `` If you do n't show me the marshals, I will cut your fingers and make your face ugly,'' she testified that the hijacker, not <PERSON> Younis </PERSON>, told her. Later, the same hijacker approached her with two hand grenades, Miss Odetalleh testified. `` This one will kill you, this one will burn you. Which do you want?'' she quoted him saying. At another point, the same hijacker placed her between himself and a window, explaining that he wanted a shield in case snipers started firing, and also wrote his nickname on her leg with a pen. Defense counsel <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> tried to show that <PERSON> Ajam </PERSON> and Miss <PERSON> Odetalleh </PERSON> benefited from their agreements to testify against <PERSON> Younis </PERSON>. But they argued that they had sacrificed important parts of their lives in order to testify. `` We ca n't see my parents, they ca n't visit us. They ca n't know where we are. That's hard for the mothers,'' <PERSON> Ajam </PERSON> testified. `` I left my memories. I left my language,'' said Miss Odetalleh. `` It is hard to be in the witness program ... You start from zero.'' More than two years after the hijacking, <PERSON> Younis </PERSON> was lured on Sept. 13, 1987, to a sailboat and arrested in international waters 13 miles off the coast of <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, testified <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, who led the team of a dozen <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents aboard the boat. <PERSON> Younis </PERSON> was interrogated for four days aboard the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> munitions ship USS Butte and then flown to <ORGANIZATION> Andrews </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> testified. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> sought to convince the jury that the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> coerced a confession from <PERSON> Younis </PERSON>, who was seasick and suffering from two broken wrists after his arrest.
