<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 front cargo door that may have popped open during a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' flight, sending nine passengers to their deaths, had a recent history of problems, federal investigators said. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday that the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> had tracked a falling object it believed to be the cargo door on radar to a point 86 miles south-southwest of <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>, where the ocean is 16,800 feet deep. The cargo door would be `` very helpful to us in our analysis,'' <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> investigator <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> said at a late-night briefing, although he did not know whether an attempt would be made to retrieve it. Meanwhile, a similar <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> jumbo jet scheduled to land Tuesday in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, was delayed 18 hours because of a faulty rear cargo door, the airline said. While the repair took only a short time, it extended the allowable working time for the flight crew beyond the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Adminstration </ORGANIZATION> limit, so the flight was delayed until a rested crew was available, a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said. The forward cargo door on the 18-year-old 747 that ripped open at 22,000 feet after leaving here for <LOCATION> Auckland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, on Friday had electrical problems more than once in December and had to be closed manually, said <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON>, investigator for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. A seal on the same door was repaired in January, he said. At an <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> news briefing Monday night, <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> would not characterize the seriousness of the problems that were found by <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> investigators by checking the aircraft's maintenance records. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Rob </PERSON> <PERSON> Doughty </PERSON> said the electrical problems are not considered serious and were on a list of deferred items that do not affect the airworthiness of the plane. `` That's a list that includes things like a reading light not working,'' he said. As for the faulty door seal, it is something that would be fixed before the plane was allowed to fly, he said. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Bobbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mardis </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, where the maintenance records are kept, said the recent cargo door repairs were not listed on the jet's service difficulty report, possibly because they were minor or were completed recently and had not yet been logged. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> records show that two other airlines reported faulty <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 cargo doors in the past five years. One was on a Pan American 747 that departed <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> in March 1987. The airliner returned to the airport after the crew was unable to pressurize the cabin following takeoff, according to the records. A worn part on a cargo door latch was blamed for the problem. In the other case, the rear cargo door warning light blinked on a <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> 747 during departure from <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> in December 1983. Ice on a master lock pin was the cause, investigators said. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> jet's cockpit voice recorder indicates that the pilot, Capt. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cronin </PERSON>, had no warning before the plane rapidly decompressed, <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> said. On the recording, the cockpit crew discussed only emergency procedures after the accident, not a possible cause or warning, he said. <PERSON> Cronin </PERSON> managed to turn the plane around and land safely in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> on only two of the four engines. For <PERSON> Cronin </PERSON>, 59, the ill-fated Flight 811 was to be his next-to-last before retirement, according to his daughter, <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Twigg-Smith </PERSON>, who lives on the island of <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cronin </PERSON>, a 34-year veteran pilot with <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>, told his daughter that he credits `` the Heavenly Father watching over him.'' `` That's one of the first things he told me when I first talked to him,'' she said. United has refused to allow <PERSON> Cronin </PERSON> and the other 17 crewmembers of Flight 811 to talk publicly about the flight, although he is expected to participate in a news conference in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> on Thursday. Of the 354 people aboard the plane, 27 were treated at hospitals, mostly for minor injuries caused by flying debris. Two remained hospitalized Tuesday, both <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> crewmembers. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, aviation industry and government safety experts recommended Tuesday that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> require $ 800 million worth of mandatory work on older airliners to ensure safety of the nation's aging airliner fleet. The unprecedented program would affect more than 1,300 early <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747, 737 and 727 models at a cost of over $ 600,000 each. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>'s Flight 812 from <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION>, which was delayed because of a rear cargo door problem, was scheduled to arrive in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> at 1:10 a.m. Tuesday, according to <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>'s reservations desk. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> said engineers replaced a safety pin in the cargo door as a precaution in line with a company order to check all of the airline's aircraft. The federal investigation of Flight 811 has focused on the cargo door latching mechanism, and airlines around the world took <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s advice and checked the cargo doors of their 747s. `` What this is from us is by no means interfering or speculating on the probable cause of the accident,'' <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> Spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jiminez </PERSON> said Monday. `` It's more of a prudent act on our part to keep customers appraised of what we know.'' <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>'s headquarters in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> issued a statement that more than 900 cargo doors in a fleet of 399 operational aircraft were inspected, and seven repairs were required. <PERSON> Doughty </PERSON> said no repair was urgent and all would have been performed in normal maintenance.
