<HEAD>Bush Defends not Telling China about Invitation to Dissident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> says he's not bothered by the row over the Chinese dissident who could n't come to dinner and says he wo n't clear such social invitations in advance with the country hosting his visit. Discussing the communist government's decision to bar astrophysicist <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> <PERSON> Lizhi </PERSON> from attending a dinner he hosted in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s capital city last weekend, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he hoped that people would n't make too much over the incident. `` That's not the whole question when it comes to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' commitment to human rights,'' the president said during a photo session while meeting with members of his Cabinet. Asked whether the flap could have been averted if the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government had notified the communist government in advance of those invited to the Texas-style barbecue at the <ORGANIZATION> Sheraton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Great </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> hotel _ as the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> have suggested _ <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` They may have a point, that it might have been avoided.'' But when asked if he would tell a communist host government ahead of time about invitations to dissidents, he replied, `` No, and I think they understand that.'' Presidential spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> defended <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s advocacy of human rights during the two-day visit to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> but acknowledged `` there is some degree of difference'' between <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s handling of the issue and the way former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> dealt with it. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> met with dissidents during his visit to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in 1988, and the former president often gave human rights a high profile during his public statements in foreign settings. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> believes he should push human rights in talks with communist leaders but that it should not be pursued to the exclusion of other concerns. Questions have been raised about how much emphasis <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will devote to human rights in the wake of the flap over <PERSON> Fang </PERSON>. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> chose to voice his complaint _ quietly _ to Chinese Vice Premier <PERSON> Wu </PERSON> <PERSON> Xuequian </PERSON> on Monday, the day after Chinese police barred <PERSON> Fang </PERSON>, 52, from attending the event. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` does feel that there are any number of ways to call attention to our human rights policy, but to make the views known diplomatically in a quiet way that does not disrupt or infringe on many of the other objectives that need to be raised with these countries.'' `` So there is some degree of difference there,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said, `` but I'll let you define'' it. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s invitation to <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> and a handful of other dissidents was intended to make a human rights statement, and said that the president had pushed the issue `` in any number of ways.'' `` I suppose maybe the proof is in the pudding, in the sense that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> today is saying the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is to blame for the diplomatic row,'' he said. `` Which is true. ... Which is to say that the president invited dissidents to this banquet for a reason.'' Four other dissidents attended the banquet, but kept a low profile there.
