CATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Derwinski </PERSON> at the time was a member of a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee investigating the `` Koreagate'' scandal _ bribes by the <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> government for members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to ensure their support. The agent, <PERSON> Sohn </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> <PERSON> Ho </PERSON>, was spirited away from his <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> home by <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents just a half-hour before colleagues from the <ORGANIZATION> Korean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> arrived. After his testimony, he received a new identity in the government's protected witness program. In 1978, <PERSON> Derwinski </PERSON> denied being the source of the tip and declined to testify before a grand jury. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Ethics <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> did not pursue the matter, saying that doing so would compromise intelligence sources and methods. But in 1983, appearing before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> for confirmation as counselor to the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Derwinski </PERSON> admitted being the tipster. <PERSON> Derwinski </PERSON> said he did not realize there was any danger to the agent, whom he did not identify to the embassy. The committee was to cover the same ground in public this afternoon.
