<HEAD>Tough Clean-Air Bill Promised by July 4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Senate clean air supporters have promised to write a tough, new anti-pollution bill by July 4, an announcement made while environmental experts were telling a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel that healthy adults and children are now at risk from dirty air. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> health subcommittee was told Tuesday that the nation faces a health emergency, with 150 million Americans now living in areas with unsafe levels of ozone and carbon monoxide. Dr. <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Landrigan </PERSON>, representing the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pediatrics </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said children are especially vulnerable to air pollution because their airways are more narrow than those of adults, and because of their increased frequency of respiratory infections. He said studies of children in summer camps show those exposed to ozone at concentrations even below current allowable levels developed temporary respiratory problems. `` Children's often high levels of activity put them at risk for acute respiratory effects due to ozone exposure,'' <PERSON> Landrigan </PERSON> said. Dr. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Godar </PERSON>, representing the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lung </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said Americans mistakenly `` accept dirty air as one of the facts of life.'' `` Ozone can cause immediate, short-term changes in lung function and increased respiratory symptoms in healthy adults and children who exercise moderately or heavily during periods of elevated ozone concentrations,'' he said. `` Significant decreases in lung function and symptoms such as coughing and pain ... are experienced by exercising individuals exposed to ozone for one to two hours at levels comparable to those frequently found'' in unsafe air quality areas, he said. Sen. <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Baucus </PERSON>, D-Mont., who will sponsor the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s clean air bill this year, announced that sections of the legislation will be introduced at these time intervals: toxic air pollutants, April 3; new air quality standards, including controls on auto emissions, May 1, and acid rain control, June 1 He said a complete bill should be written before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' July 4 recess. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, sponsor of clean air legislation that died last year, told senators, `` Americans are suffering from a manmade phenomenon that can be controlled. We have developed the technologies of control. We have the resources to apply those technologies. Until now, we have lacked the political will to do so. We must now develop that will.'' Clean air legislation has been stalled for a decade, as supporters of industry and environmental groups _ and different regions of the country _ have fought to a standstill. Only one witness at the House hearing, representing <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION>, said that there was no conclusive evidence that current air quality levels caused lasting health problems. The chief of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION>, Dr. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON>, said the potential health effects from exposure to current levels of ozone and carbon monoxide `` have been the subject of considerable overstatement.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said 62 areas have failed to meet air quality standards for ozone and 59 for carbon monoxide, a list based on readings from 1985 to 1987. The list does not yet include 28 cities that exceeded the safe ozone levels last summer, according to <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> data.
