<HEAD>Bush Must Overcome Nunn's Influence To Win on Tower Nomination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In lobbying senators to support <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON> for secretary of <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION>, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has the difficult task of overcoming the reputation Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> has built over the past 16 years as the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s bipartisan leader on defense issues. `` That's probably the toughest single obstacle the president faces,'' Sen. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Robb </PERSON>, D-Va., said Tuesday <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> Democrat who has been chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> since 1986 and a member of the panel since 1973, led the committee's Democrats in a 11-9 party-line vote last week to reject the Tower nomination. Since then, he has made the case against Tower on national television, in private meetings with other senators and in the written report of the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. But he insisted Tuesday that he has not been `` strong-arming anybody'' to vote against Tower. `` I'm not saying my prestige is on the line,'' said <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, who has been described by <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> as `` one of _ if not the most _ respected'' members of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. `` I give them my views and I do n't make any bones about where I stand,'' <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> said. `` But I'm not asking them to vote on anything other than their conscience.'' <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>'s views are that the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> report on Tower provides evidence of a `` clear pattern of alcohol abuse'' and that the former <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> senator's recent work as a high-paid consultant to defense contractors raises serious conflict-of-interest questions. Those views carry substantial weight, primarily because of <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>'s reputation among both Democrats and Republicans as a senator who does his homework and who speaks with authority on defense issues `` I have never known him to do anything in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that would appear to have self-serving, narrow political implications when dealing with national defense or foreign policy,'' former <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Jeremiah </PERSON> <PERSON> Denton </PERSON> said Tuesday. <PERSON> Denton </PERSON>, a conservative Republican who served on the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> with both <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> and Tower, said he supports Tower for secretary of defense but, unlike some Republicans, does not believe <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>'s opposition is motivated by partisan politics. <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> has resisted Republican efforts to paint the Tower nomination as a partisan fight waged by the Democratic-controlled <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in an effort to weaken the new president. `` The Republicans, if you agree with them, they say you're a patriot, but if you disagree, all of a sudden it's partisan,'' said <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, who during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years consistently ranked as one of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s top Democratic supporters of the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> president. <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> said he realized when Tower was nominated that he would be subjected as committee chairman to a barrage of criticism, regardless of whether he supported or opposed the nomination. `` Either I would be the scapegoat because I was taking on the president, or I would be the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> covering up the alleged transgressions of the nominee,'' he said. The criticism intensified Tuesday when the <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> reprinted a Dec. 4, 1972, article from The <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> detailing an Oct. 31, 1964, automobile accident in which <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> pleaded guilty to leaving the scene of an accident. In an accompanying article, the newspaper said: `` If the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is entitled to pass judgment on <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON>'s personal history, then the public is also entitled to know the salient facts about those who judge Mr. Tower.'' <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> acknowledged that his `` driving and judgment were impaired'' on the evening of the accident because he had too much to drink. But he said an accident 24 years ago is not relevant to the Tower nomination. `` The implication is that if I have an automobile accident in 1964, then I'm not qualified under the Constitution to render advice and consent in 1989,'' <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> said. `` I do n't think that logic holds.''
