<HEAD>Yeutter Says Commodity Programs Likely Budget Target</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> says he is still looking for areas to reduce his budget by $ 1.1 billion, but believes most of the money will come from commodity programs. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has called for the reduction, but not specified which programs should be cut, leaving <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> with only <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration proposals. <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> assured the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday he was not wedded to the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> proposals. For example, he said ground water and food programs cut in the proposed <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> budget will be restored. He said <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> programs and those of the <ORGANIZATION> Rural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electrification </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, however, will be reduced along with commodities. After the hearing, <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> told reporters that cuts in commodities would n't be arbitrary. `` We have to go through a sophisticated analysis to determine the extent of the changes. It may vary from commodity to commodity,'' he said. `` We have to decide the best way to achieve the reduction while still keeping a safety net for farmers. It's not an easy trick,'' he said. He mentioned cutting target prices, but said they may not be cut by the same percentage for every commodity. He also suggested that there may be a reduction in permitted acreage. <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> told committee members who asked specifically about the school lunch program that it was unlikely to see any reduction, though President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had suggested it be cut by $ 950 million. The secretary said he wanted to evaluate it and all nutrition programs run by the department, but he doubted that there would be any cuts in them. Rep. <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Kildee </PERSON>, D-Mich., gave <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> a list of programs for low-income Americans which he said the committee over the years has agreed must never be cut, including school lunch and other child nutrition programs An area <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said should get more money is the Export Enhancement Program. `` Export expansion and long-term market development are of key importance to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agriculture,'' he told the committee. Discussing the ongoing negotiations under the General Agreement on Trade and Tariffs, known as <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is still committed to removing trade barriers worldwide. But he said the difficulty in achieving that end was demonstrated at the midterm review of the <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> Round last December in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> when the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was unable to get other countries to go along with its desire to do away with government subsidies. Following a meeting with <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> on Monday, Australian trade chief <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had softened its position, and `` put the ball very much in the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>'s court.'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said after the hearing Tuesday that <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON> was correct in saying that the ball was in the hands of the <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION>, but said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had not softened. `` We formulated our proposal in a more palatable way,'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said. Trade talks resume in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> in April.
