<TEXT>
 White House press secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> selected an unusual way to announce his engagement. `` The Chinese security dislocated my fiance's jaw,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> complained, thereby confirming what many associates knew but which <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> had never before announced. Chinese security guards, during <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s visit last week to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, engaged in what appeared to be a favorite pastime: pushing, shoving and pummeling <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> news media. At one point, <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Powers </PERSON>, a photographer who works for the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, was slammed into a door. Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> shouted at the security folks to `` calm down.'' `` This girl's job is to take my picture,'' she said. `` She works for my husband.'' Said a blushing Fitzwater of Ms. Powers, his fiancee: `` We have n't really made an official announcement. But we are engaged.'' He said the decision had been made `` the weekend before we left'' for the <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> trip. No date has been set.
