<TEXT>
 When the president went on Chinese television earlier this week, he became the first foreign leader ever to do so. Chinese officials said the live, unedited interview reached between 400 to 600 million Chinese, an audience even <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> would envy. But <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had a hard time making it to the TV studio on time. His meeting with <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> party leader <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyanf </PERSON> dragged on and on. The session went 25 minutes beyond its scheduled close. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s motorcade, racing at speeds up to 60 mph, sped to the TV studio and arrived with less than five minutes to spare before air time <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> sprinted up the outside stairs to the studio. He was rushed in, some makeup quickly applied to his face. The time of the interview was selected by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials: it followed an Italian soccer match and came before <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Mouse </PERSON> and <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Duck </PERSON> cartoons. `` We all agreed it was the best possible time,'' said <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koss </PERSON>, an official at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassy in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. `` The majority of viewers were tuned in to watch <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> and <PERSON> Donald </PERSON>,'' he said.
