<HEAD>Greenspan Defends Interest Rate Hikes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> defends his decision to fight inflation with higher interest rates even though the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration disagrees with the central bank's reading of the economy <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday that the current inflation rate is not `` doing clear, significant, corrosive harm to the economy at the moment.'' `` But it has built into it the seeds of an acceleration that if not dampened ... can become very damaging,'' he said in his first public statement since the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> escalated its anti-inflation fight Friday by increasing a key bank lending rate. He said the central bank expects inflation to increase this year to the 4.5 percent to 5 percent range, up about half a percentage point from last year. However, <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> policy makers are worried that a pickup in wage increases and rising material costs will cause businesses and consumers to include the expectation of inflation in their plans. When that happens, prices will rise faster, he said. `` Our basic goal is to make sure that inflation does not accelerate inordinately and ultimately phases down,'' he said. Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, in testimony before the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, softened previous criticism of <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> tightening, but he did not retract his statement that the administration sees less danger of inflation. `` It's two people looking at the same statistic and coming to a slightly different conclusion,'' <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>, while not explicitly acknowledging the administration's comments, said in response to a question from Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, R-Colo., `` I think I get it from all sides. In the budget committee, Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, R-Colo., and Sen. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Exon </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Neb </LOCATION>., praised the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> for its stance toward inflation, but Sen. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Nickles </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Okla </LOCATION>., told <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>, `` I'm afraid you're laying the seeds for Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.M. </LOCATION>, said he believed the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s strategy of gradual increases in interest rates would not work and that `` far more ratcheting down'' of the economy will be needed to achieve the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s stated goal of zero inflation. `` You've got to almost create a self-fulfilling prophecy and create a recession,'' he said. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> budget director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>, who spoke to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, all said that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the administration can help the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> curb inflation and also permit interest rates to drop by agreeing on a credible plan to cut the budget deficit. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s budget, if adopted, would trigger lower interest rates even if it eventually produced a deficit higher than the $ 100 billion Gramm-Rudman target for 1990. `` I may say I would like to see Gramm-Rudman-Hollings targets met literally -LRB- but -RRB- I do n't think that is required to bring a significant reduction in interest rates,'' he said. `` If, after the fact, the real number is $ 110 billion or $ 120 billion, in that vein, I would think that would be a major improvement which the markets would take very positively,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> chairman said. But, the reduction from the 1989 deficit of about $ 165 billion must not be accomplished with accounting tricks and must hold out the reasonable prospect for further reductions, he said. `` What can not have a positive effect is finding some set of bookkeeping gimmicks which largely meet Gramm-Rudman for fiscal 1990 and then paper over ` 91, ` 92, ` 93,'' he said.
