<FIRST>r w PM-FDA-Aflatoxin     03-01 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FDA-Aflatoxin,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Says Food Supply Safe from Cancer-Causing Fungus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government confirms the drought helped increase the cancer-causing fungus aflatoxin in the 1988 corn crop in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, requiring some corn to be diverted to feed non-dairy cattle. But the government disputed concerns raised in a report by <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> last week that aflatoxin-tainted corn is moving through the nation's food chain because of inadequate sampling and unreliable testing. In a statement Tuesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said the agency `` does not believe such concern is warranted because there is plenty of aflatoxin-free corn available for human consumption, and several layers of protection are in place.'' Aflatoxin is linked to the development of liver cancer in laboratory rats. Last year's heat and drought provided ideal conditions for development of the fungus that produces aflatoxin. Primary concern has centered around possible contamination of the milk and corn supply. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said the agency reaffirmed to state health officials last fall its aflatoxin limit of 0.5 parts per billion for milk. States and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Milk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipments </ORGANIZATION>, which has prime responsibility for testing milk, expanded monitoring and as a result some milk in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and southern <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> had higher levels of aflatoxin than allowed and had to be dumped, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said. The level of aflatoxin allowed in corn is 20 parts per billion, and about 6 percent _ 95 samples out of 1,650 _ of the field corn tested in recent months had higher levels, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said. This corn can not be used for human consumption but can be diverted to feed non-dairy cattle, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said. In addition to <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> testing, which is concentrated in high risk areas, tests are conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the states, manufacturers and millers who buy corn for food products. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> also tested about 100 corn products on store shelves _ including cooked cereal, dry cereal, tortillas, corn chips and popcorn _ and all were negative, agency spokesman <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Grigg </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> tested about 263 samples of corn flour and corn meal and found 2 percent, or six samples, to have more than 20 parts of aflatoxin per billion. <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> policy requires that these products be removed from the market.
