<NOTE>Connaught Laboratories Recalls 46,000 Vials of DTP Vaccine</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Connaught Laboratories of <LOCATION> Swiftwater </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, has recalled 46,000 vials of DTP vaccine as a precautionary measure because of a labeling error, the company and the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said. DTP vaccine is used routinely to immunize infants and children against diphtheria, tetanus and whooping cough. The recall was begun because four vials of equine influenza, found in a plant warehouse, were mislabeled as DTP vaccine. Equine influenza vaccine is used in immunizing horses against several strains of flu. As a safety precaution, the company notified 1,865 customers to return all vials with the lot number 8M91039. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said less than 20,000 of the 46,000 vials in the lot were actually shipped to doctors, pharmacists and distributors nationwide. <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, in a statement, said the labeling error is not believed to constitute a health hazard because Connaught officials believe they have located the only mislabeled vials. `` Parents should not be unduly alarmed, nor should they interrupt their children's immunization schedules, but we feel that the action of the company to recall the marketed vaccine is prudent,'' Dr. <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said.
