<HEAD>Kenya Bans The Satanic Verses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At the request of its Moslem minority, the government of this predominately Christian country has banned the sale and possession in <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> of <PERSON> Salman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>'s novel `` The Satanic Verses.'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Njiru </PERSON>, minister for national guidance and political affairs, said Tuesday that the banning was based on `` a short review'' of the book, which many Moslems consider blasphemous. The review, <PERSON> Njiru </PERSON> said, `` clearly indicates that the content of the book is offensive to Moslems who constitute an important section of the Kenyan community.'' About 6 percent of this African country's 20 million people belong to the Islamic community, which had asked the government to institute the ban. Other countries that have banned the book include <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> has called on Moslems to seek out and kill <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>, who is in hiding, and his government has threatened to break diplomatic relations with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> unless it denounces the author. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> is among more than a dozen European countries that have recalled their ambassadors from <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> over the death threat.
