<HEAD>Andy Timar, AP Representative in Budapest, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Timar </PERSON>, longtime representative of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and a senior correspondent of the national news agency <ORGANIZATION> MTI </ORGANIZATION>, has died after a brief illness. He was 65. <PERSON> Timar </PERSON> died Tuesday at a <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> hospital he had entered Sunday for tests after becoming ill. He died in his sleep after developing respiratory problems. From 1946 to 1947, <PERSON> Timar </PERSON> worked with the English-language section of the Hungarian delegation to the <ORGANIZATION> Allied </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which governed Hungarian affairs immediately after World War II. He then joined the press department of the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Timar </PERSON> first worked for the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> as a stringer in 1957 and was hired as its representative in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> in 1962. He had worked for <ORGANIZATION> MTI </ORGANIZATION> since 1962, first in the agency department that sent news abroad, then as an editor on the English-language Daily News newspaper. <PERSON> Timar </PERSON> was a serious student of languages, art and history and traveled widely throughout the world in his years with <ORGANIZATION> MTI </ORGANIZATION> and the AP. He also had been active for years in the <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> foreign press club. He is survived by his wife, <PERSON> Piroska </PERSON>.
