<FIRST>r a PM-Transplants     03-01 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Transplants,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Network Discourages Using Deformed Babies As Donors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Severely deformed babies facing certain death should not be routinely considered as organ donors, even though hundreds of children desperately need new hearts and livers, the national transplant network said. Directors of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sharing </ORGANIZATION> adopted a policy Tuesday discouraging, at least for now, use of anencephalic infants as organ donors. The board noted, however, `` it is unwise to recommend a moratorium.'' The issue of whether to take organs from anencephalic infants _ babies born without most of their brains _ has troubled experts for some time, but some say it is the only way to save other dying babies and children for whom there are few organs. `` We're certainly not going to take organs from a live person, but in our hearts and in our minds we know these people are not alive,'' said <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Broznick </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transplant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> and a proponent of anencephalic donors. <PERSON> Broznick </PERSON> and many other procurement officials are distressed that they must refuse organs from anencephalic infants until all brain activity ceases. By then, the organs often are not fit for transplantation due to infection. Anencephalic infants are born with only part of a brain stem, which controls respiration. Because they do have slight brain stem activity, they are not legally brain dead, a necessary state before organs can be removed from a human body. Half the 1,000 to 2,000 anencephalic babies delivered each year in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are stillborn. The other half generally die within one week. `` Not all parents would do it -LRB- donate -RRB-,'' said <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON>, director of the Center for Biomedical Ethics at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION>. `` But I'm sure there would be a significant number of donors.'' <PERSON> Broznick </PERSON>, in fact, believes there probably would be enough organs to accommodate the 400 to 500 children awaiting liver transplants in this country. `` We could probably take care of all those kids, and we ca n't do anything about it,'' he said. `` By the same token, we could offer this couple -LRB- with an anencephalic baby -RRB- an opportunity for something positive to come out of this life that they've tried to bring in. It's a real sad situation.'' Only one anencephalic child has ever had its organs removed for transplantation in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. That case occurred on Oct. 16, 1987, at <ORGANIZATION> Loma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Linda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. The heart recipient, a boy who was born the day of the operation, is doing well at home in <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, said <LOCATION> Loma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Linda </LOCATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Anita </PERSON> <PERSON> Rockwell </PERSON>. The hospital has had a moratorium since August on cases involving infants suffering from the incurable birth defect. However, anencephalic infants reportedly have been used as organ donors in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Because of the growing interest in the infants as donors, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sharing </ORGANIZATION>'s ethics committee began studying the matter last year. The panel recently presented its recommendation to the network's 32-member board of directors, which adopted the position during a regular meeting Tuesday in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. The board said further study is needed and could prompt a re-evaluation of its position. `` We must have agreement on how you diagnose death and brain-death in anencephalic infants before we can go any further,'' said <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON>, an ethics committee member. The Virginia-based <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> administers the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Procurement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transplantation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
