<HEAD>Younger Daley Struggling to Escape His Father's Long Shadow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, owner of the most famous last name in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> politics, rarely invoked his father's memory during his Democratic mayoral primary campaign. But with his victory secure, he made sure to pay his dues. `` Today, when I was walking down to vote with my wife ... when I looked up, I know he was looking down on me,'' <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> said Tuesday night of six-term Mayor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>. In unofficial returns, the younger <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> garnered 57 percent of the vote in the primary to oust Mayor <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> and move to the April 4 general election The elder <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> was the boss of big-city machine politics, the purveyor of patronage, the last of a political breed, dying in 1976 three months into his third decade in office. His son, who often sat in the mayor's seat as a youngster, recalled that his father had told him that in politics, `` you're going to have ups and downs You're going to win; you're going to lose.'' And despite the sterling showing Tuesday, the younger <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> has had some of both, in politics and in life. He had to fight to overcome the shadow of his father as he worked his way through his father's old high school and law school. But those difficulties paled compared to the great personal tragedy <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Maggie </PERSON>, endured when their 33-month-old son, <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON>, died in 1981 after a long battle with spina bifida. The couple's three other children, <PERSON> Nora </PERSON>, 15, <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>, 13, and <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON>, 5, stood alongside their 46-year-old father and his wife on the victory platform Tuesday night. In a poignant moment, he thanked each, then added, `` and especially, <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON>, who is always in our hearts. And to the best campaigner in the family, my wife, <PERSON> Maggie </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> also went through a hurtful defeat in a 1983 three-way primary between himself, then-incumbent Democratic Mayor <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>, who won and went on to become the city's first black mayor `` I've been on both sides of these election nights,'' he recalled Tuesday. `` I know what it's like to win, and I know what it's like to pour your heart into a campaign and lose.'' It took <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> three tries to pass the bar exam to become a lawyer, a sore point exploited during the campaign by <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and other opponents. <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> responded with a brusqueness many say is reminiscent of his father. `` I flunked the bar exam. So what? Maybe I should have committed suicide,'' he said. Besides, he added, a passing grade only would have led to charges that `` my father had it fixed for me.'' To be sure, <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> has been helped by his name _ getting elected to the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> at age 29, and as <LOCATION> Cook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> state's attorney three times, including the first win against a party-slated candidate But there's no easy way to say how strong his father's effect has been, said <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Loyola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor and author of a biography of the elder <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> entitled `` Himself.'' `` There's nobody like his father. ... But <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> has acquired a confidence in himself and his judgment that resemble the father in some ways. And he's overcome enough adversity on his own ... to establish a separate identity, to start the long climb out from under his father's shadow,'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. The eldest of seven children, <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> had his first political post as an 18-year-old page for the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> delegation to the 1960 Democratic National Convention. In the state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, he showed more acumen than many gave him credit for, and forged alliances with anti-machine reformers on social-welfare legislation affecting nursing homes and abolishing taxes on certain foods and medicine. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Kruesi </PERSON>, a top aide, said <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> studied hard as a legislator and knew his material. `` Rich has been handicapped by the fact that people have trouble getting past his name,'' <PERSON> Kruesi </PERSON> said. `` If his name were <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON>, he'd be lionized for the work he's done as a legislator and as state's attorney.''
