<HEAD>Measles Hit Some Colleges Hard, But Outbreaks Are Scattered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Measles has hit some colleges this winter, but federal health officials said outbreaks of the disease normally associated with childhood are scattered and no cause for great alarm. Students lined up for measles vaccine last week at the C.W. Post campus of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Long </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, and free inoculations were offered this week at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION>. A measles outbreak caused <ORGANIZATION> Catawba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Salisbury </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, to cancel its basketball season and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Kent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> stopped sending nursing students to local hospitals for fear of giving patients measles. `` We're definitely having measles outbreaks right now, but it is unfortunately nothing new,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>'s immunization division. `` We do get outbreaks on college campuses and high school campuses -LRB- each year -RRB-.'' Most states require children to be inoculated for measles before entering school, but some still reach college without immunity. In some cases, <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> said, the vaccine does n't take; in others, colleges may not have required proof of immunization. At C.W. Post, where 19 cases were reported as of Monday, immunization rules are now being strictly enforced, said spokeswoman <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Ring </PERSON>. Measles cases at <ORGANIZATION> Siena </ORGANIZATI