<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Converge On Capital To Protest Alleged Persecution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IVAN STEFANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 4,000 <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> Slavs and their children converged on <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> today to protest alleged ethnic persecution by the majority Albanians in the impoverished southern region, the state <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> news agency said. The flag-carrying, chanting Serbs and Montenegrins jammed steets and interrupted traffic as they walked from the railroad station to the downtown parliament. Taxi drivers, brandishing pictures of the popular Serbian party chief <PERSON> Slobodan </PERSON> <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>, gave free rides to the elderly. Speaking to a rally in the capital Tuesday that drew an estimated 500,000 people, <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> vowed to arrest the organizers of protests and strikes by ethnic Albanians in <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> _ an autonomous province of the Serbian republic. Serbs who support <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> believe the Albanians in <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, which was ancient <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>'s heartland, want to unite the province with neighboring <LOCATION> Albania </LOCATION>. About 90 percent of <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>'s people are ethnic Albanians. Growing ethnic nationalism has created the greatest threat to <LOCATION> Yugoslav </LOCATION> unity since the 1980 death of President <PERSON> Tito </PERSON>, whose leadership held the disparate nation of 23 million people together. An economic crisis has combined with the resurgence of ethnic and religious rivalries to threaten the loose confederation of six republics and two provinces. The republics of <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Croatia </LOCATION> support demands by ethnic <PERSON> Albanians </PERSON> for guarantees that <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>'s autonomy will not be restricted. The two are <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s most liberal and economically advanced republics. <LOCATION> Macedonia </LOCATION> supports the Serbs, the largest ethnic group in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> was outwardly peaceful Tuesday, except for scattered Serbian protests, under emergency measures imposed Monday after a week of unrest among the province's 1.8 million people. Official Yugoslav media said about 1,000 Slavs had announced plans to leave <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> immediately, alleging harassment by ethnic Albanians. Meanwhile, 500 ethnic Albanians in the <LOCATION> Trepca </LOCATION> lead-zinc mine in <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> continued their strike to protest Serbian plans to change the constitution in a bid to win greater control over their province. On Monday, 1,300 ethnic <PERSON> Albanian </PERSON> miners came out from pits after an eight-day sit-in that forced the resignation of three <ORGANIZATION> Kosovo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leaders they consider pro-Serbian. Doctors from <LOCATION> Croatia </LOCATION> said the exhausted miners would be unable to work for at least a week. <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> said peace prevailed this morning in <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>'s capital of <LOCATION> Pristina </LOCATION>, where additional military vehicles and soldiers had been sent on Monday. But in <LOCATION> Sarajevo </LOCATION>, capital of the republic of <LOCATION> Bosnia-Herzegovina </LOCATION>, 2,000 students lent support to <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>'s drive for more control over <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, and demanded the resignations of the three leaders be rescinded. Thousands of workers in <LOCATION> Macedonia </LOCATION> also sided with <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION> in more protests today and sent messages of support to <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> students saying `` <LOCATION> Sarajevo </LOCATION> Is With You'' and `` <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION> Is Lying,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> said. About 1,000 Slovenian intellectuals held an anti-Serbian protest Tuesday in <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION>'s capital, <LOCATION> Ljubljana </LOCATION>, and about 100,000 Slovenians have signed a petition against the emergency measures in <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>.
