<HEAD>Iraq Denounces Amnesty Report on Child Torture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The official <ORGANIZATION> Iraqi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> today denounced a report by <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> that said the children of political prisoners have been tortured, abused and imprisoned in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> INA </ORGANIZATION> quoted an unidentified editor as calling the report by the international human rights organization `` cheap allegations'' in an `` anti-Iraqi propaganda campaign.'' The editor pointed to the planned political reforms announced by President <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> to dispute the charges. `` These lies aired by enemy circles come at a time when <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> announces its serious efforts through continuous meetings of the political leadership to set the permanent constitution of the country and to permit ... political parties ... and press freedom,'' said the report, which was monitored in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> has said political parties will be permitted and has encouraged the press to be more critical. The new laws have not been announced, but former opposition parties such as the Islamic Call and the communists will not be permitted on the ground they had dealings with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s foe in the eight-year <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> war. The editor said Iraqi children get free education, health care and social security. <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> issued a report on Tuesday saying that `` children and young people have become the innocent victims of a policy of political repression'' in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. It said opponents of <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>'s government have sometimes had to pay for their activities with `` the welfare _ and sometimes the lives _ of their children'' between 1983 and 1988. Children as young as five months old have been imprisoned, and hundreds have disappeared, the report said.
