<HEAD>Likud Takes Labor Strongholds; Kollek Re-elected</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with more comments from Shamir and Peres,
dispute over vote count in mayor's race in Haifa. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> bloc upset the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in nationwide municipal elections, and Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> said today the voting indicates Israelis support <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION>'s anti-PLO policies. <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader and finance minister, insisted Tuesday's balloting had nothing to do with the Palestinian issue and said he was willing to hold a separate referendum on the subject. Other Labor leaders demanded a shakeup to halt a decline in their party's standing since November, when <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> won the premiership in national elections. Political analysts said the results showed Labor's historic dominance of the grass-roots level had eroded. In a key race of Tuesday's election, <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Teddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kollek </PERSON> was re-elected for a sixth term. But he lost control of the city council as religious parties increased their representation to nearly half the city council. The biggest gains were made by such ultra-Orthodox parties as <ORGANIZATION> Shas </ORGANIZATION>, Agudat <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Degel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatorah </PERSON>. Their success will probably give them more power than the traditional, more moderate Orthodox parties. The religious gains also could fuel tensions between secular and observant Jews in the city, because <PERSON> Kollek </PERSON> will need to enlist the support of the ultra-Orthodox to govern, <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> news reports said. But the 77-year-old <PERSON> Kollek </PERSON>, who has been in office since 1965, said he still expected to control the city. `` I will ... give other people an ulcer instead of getting one myself,'' he said. <PERSON> Shlomo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lahat </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> mayor of <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>, also won re-election. The results in <LOCATION> Haifa </LOCATION>, where Labor Mayor <PERSON> Aryeh </PERSON> <PERSON> Gurel </PERSON> was in a tight race with his <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> rival, were uncertain after a dispute developed today over the counting of ballots, <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> reported. <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> appeared to have won several Labor strongholds, including the southern port of <LOCATION> Ashdod </LOCATION> and the town of <LOCATION> Beersheba </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Negev </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Desert </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> also won several communities around <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION> that Labor had held, including Holon, <LOCATION> Petach </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tikvah </LOCATION> and Ramat Gan. Ultra-Orthodox religious parties scored gains throughout the country, repeating their success of the November general elections, according to unofficial results based on 43 percent of the vote. At stake were 147 local councils and mayoralities. In the last national municipal elections in 1983, <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> won in 54 towns, compared to 26 taken by <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION>. The remainder went to local slates or religious parties. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, who had billed the elections as a referendum on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s refusal to negotiate peace with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>, said on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio the results `` will signal to various people in the world, so they know who is dominant in the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> political system, who is the one who determines, who has the stronger voice. `` There is no doubt that the elections ... show <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> is getting stronger and at the same time the majority ... supports its political positions.'' <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> acknowledged in a radio interview that <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> `` has definitely been dealt a blow, and I do n't want to underestimate its force.'' But he disputed claims the results showed wide public support for <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION>'s views on the <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> conflict. Officially both Labor and <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> oppose <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> participation in peace talks, based on a claim that it is a terrorist organization. But there are growing calls inside Labor to reconsider this policy now that <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> has said he renounces terrorism and recognizes <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to exist. Labor leaders, including <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> aides, have met recently with prominent Palestinians in the occupied territories who are known to be <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> supporters. Energy Minister <PERSON> Moshe </PERSON> <PERSON> Shahal </PERSON> of Labor said his party's losses were a further sign of the decline of the party that has failed to win any of the last four general elections. On the national level, <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> have been governing in an uneasy coalition since 1984, with neither party able to score an outright victory in general elections. About 48 percent of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s 2.7 million voters went to the polls on Tuesday, down from 55 percent in 1983. Voters cast two ballots, one for mayor and the second for a party slate for city council. In <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kollek </PERSON> won 64 percent, while his slate received 12 of 31 council seats, down from 17. Religious parties, meanwhile, increased their seats from 10 to 15. <PERSON> Kollek </PERSON> lost his majority in part because of the boycott of east <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>'s 80,000 Arab voters, traditionally <PERSON> Kollek </PERSON> backers. Fewer than 2 percent went to the polls, compared to 18 percent in 1983. The boycott was ordered by the PLO-allied leadership of the 15-month Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. The leaders called a general strike Tuesday to enforce the order and urged Palestinians to punish those who ignored the boycott. In the Arab sector, <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> fundamentalists ousted the communist leadership of the second-largest city, <LOCATION> Umm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> el </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fahem </LOCATION>, causing concern that anti-Israeli sentiment is spreading among Israeli Arabs.
