<FIRST>r i PM-Venezuela-Economy     03-01 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Venezuela-Economy,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Violence Marks End of Oil Dream</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Venezuela-Riots</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAROLD OLMOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For decades, Venezuelans dreamed that oil would cure the economic woes of their petroleum-rich country. That illusion, held even after oil prices began to plummet, appears to have ended with the worst violence in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> in 31 years. Increases of 30 percent to 50 percent in public transport tariffs and price gouging by bus drivers acted as a detonator for an economy in rapid deterioration. The slide in the price of oil, which accounts for 90 percent of Venezuelan export revenue, coupled with a suffocating $ 33 billion foreign debt. The nation pocketed an estimated $ 9 billion in oil revenues last year, compared to $ 19 billion in 1981. Inflation this year is expected to reach 70 percent, up from 35 percent last year. President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>, who took power three weeks ago, announced a sweeping economic reform package intended to breathe life into the stagnant economy and persuade international bankers to increase loans to the country. Some of those reforms included freeing interest rates, doubling gasoline prices, and establishing a free-floating currency with a consequent increase in the price of imports. The violence that erupted across the nation Monday showed the difficulty the government will have implementing the economic reforms. The reforms were backed by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>, from which <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> hopes to obtain a $ 1.5 billion short-term loan. Until now, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> had avoided turning to the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> for a bailout. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> himself called the organization the equivalent of `` economic totalitarianism.'' <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> has 18 million inhabitants and was for years an island of tranquility in a sea of regional violence, political instability and economic recession. Under <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>'s first administration, from 1973 to 1978, oil prices boomed and the country enjoyed an unparalleled prosperity. There was full employment and inflation did not break single digits. Those memories were enough to guarantee <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> a landslide victory in the election Dec. 4, say political experts `` Perez evoked for Venezuelans a bonanza, and now they've had a rude awakening,'' said sociologist and university professor <PERSON> Anibal </PERSON> <PERSON> Romero </PERSON>. <PERSON> Romero </PERSON> said he did not believe the disturbances threatened <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>'s democracy, saying the country had lived through worst crises, including guerrilla movements in the 1960s. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Vicente </PERSON> <PERSON> Rangel </PERSON>, former leftist presidential candidate and congressman, said the riots represented `` the beginnings of an end of an era, of a style of life.'' `` It's the breaking of the illusion that all politicians had that this could never happen here. It did happen indeed, and it's proof of the impoverishment of the country. We're not used to inflation,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Olmos </PERSON> has been the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> bureau chief in <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> for many years and has written extensively on Latin American affairs.
