<HEAD>Tacoma Zoo Needs More Room for Elephants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The elephants of Point Defiance Zoo are getting bigger homes at a $ 1.5 million cost, improvements necessitated largely by a profoundly problematic pachyderm named <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON>, the zoo director says. <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON>, a 24-year-old from <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, is returning after six years on loan to the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> Wild Animal Park. In fact, the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> zoo is pleading with <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION> officials to hasten <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON>'s return, said zoo director <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Otten </PERSON>. It is n't so much that the four-ton <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON> would n't mate with any of the bull elephants in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, but three weeks ago she broke a handler's collarbone with a slap of her trunk. `` From time to time, <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON> has made aggressive motions toward keepers she does n't like, and that's most of our keepers,'' said <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelstein </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> zoo. `` We would n't fight the decision to let her go.'' The return has added urgency to the need to build bigger elephant barns, using money from a prior bond issue. Otherwise, <PERSON> Otten </PERSON> said, `` We'll have to go out of the elephant business.'' <PERSON> Moyo </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thandi </PERSON>, the zoo's 8-year-old female African elephants, also could use larger quarters, <PERSON> Otten </PERSON> said. Part of the plan is for construction this summer of a special yard for <PERSON> Cindy </PERSON> with an elephant `` crush,'' a hydraulic steel device to contain the animal while trainers trim toenails and tusks, administer medication and take blood and fluid samples. The <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> zoo does not have such a device, so trainers must rely on each other to keep elephants still.
