<HEAD>Snow Hauled in By Rail to Battle The Winter that Wasn't</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS one graf for 4th graf pvs, ``Last month ...'' to ADD average
temperature for February. Picks up 5th graf pvs, ``The nice ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG MELLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Trains loaded with snow have been rattling into this usually frozen capital in a costly battle to create the winter that was n't and save an annual tradition. A record warm winter threatened to melt away the <ORGANIZATION> Holmenkollen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ski </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Festival </ORGANIZATION>, which begins Thursday, so organizers hauled in 5,600 tons of snow by rail at about 1.5 cents a pound to rescue the event. `` Snow costs about the same per pound as wholesale sugar,'' said <PERSON> Knut </PERSON> <PERSON> Almquist </PERSON>, secretary general of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Promotion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Skiing </ORGANIZATION>, which has organized the annual festival since 1892. <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION> and southern <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> experienced the mildest January ever recorded. State meteorologist <PERSON> Oernulf </PERSON> <PERSON> Fremming </PERSON> said January was a balmy 28 degrees above normal, and <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION>'s February's average of 36.7 degrees was nearly 12 degrees warmer than the month's normal average temperature of 24.8 degrees. The nice weather has left the <LOCATION> Holmenkollen </LOCATION> ski jump and cross-country trail near <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION> without snow as its annual highpoint approached _ four days of World Cup competitions that begin Thursday. Two of the week's major events, a World Cup 90-meter ski jump and the annual `` Monolith'' cross-country ski race in <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Frogner </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> have already been canceled. The state railroad <ORGANIZATION> NSB </ORGANIZATION> was hired to scoop up mountain snow from the center of the country and ship it 186 miles by flatcar to <LOCATION> Holmenkollen </LOCATION>. Railroaders joked that snow might be a important new cash crop. A giant <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chinook </ORGANIZATION> twin-rotor helicopter had been slated to carry flakes aloft and create its own blizzard above <LOCATION> Holmenkollen </LOCATION>, but was grounded by fog, <PERSON> Almquist </PERSON> said. A lack of snow has not stopped <LOCATION> Holmenkollen </LOCATION> ski jumpers since 1925, and the association will do almost anything to save the event, he said. `` It would cost more to cancel than to ship snow. Our insurance pays for covering the ski area in snow but not for canceling or moving the event,'' he said of the more than $ 150,000 snow purchase. `` We'll take care of the snow if only nature will arrange the cold weather,'' he said. High temperatures and a steady drizzle had threatened to wash away transplanted snow _ but more recent colder weather and snow flurries have raised hopes, he said. Tuesday's high in <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION> was 41 degrees, the low 36. The warm spell has left <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s ski manufacturers, southern resorts and even the ski association strapped for cash but brought the railroad a windfall. `` We would n't mind seeing more ski races like this. It's great for business,'' joked Per <PERSON> Kristian </PERSON> <PERSON> Flaten </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> NSB </ORGANIZATION>. `` We really do hope the jumps and races go as planned after everyone's efforts.'' <ORGANIZATION> NSB </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Olav </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollerud </PERSON>, who engineered the snow lift, said 13 trains have hauled 300 flatcars, each carrying 18.7 tons of snow, from the mountains.
