<HEAD>New Law Would Impose 11 p.m. Weekday Curfew on Youngsters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new law passed by the <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> in an effort to fight the city's soaring crime rate would impose a curfew of 11 p.m. on weekdays and midnight on weekends for people under 18 years of age. The temporary measure passed Tuesday would allow police to detain violators at police stations until a parent or guardian signs for their release. Those not picked up would be held until 6 a.m. the next day. The measure, introduced as emergency legislation by council member <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, calls for fining parents and guardians of repeat offenders $ 100 to $ 500. Mayor <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> has 10 days to sign the bill, which would put it into effect immediately, or veto the measure. He has taken no public position on it. City Corporation Counsel <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooke </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said his office would study the legislation thoroughly before advising the mayor whether or not to sign it. If approved, the curfew would expire after 90 days unless permanent legislation is enacted. It would exempt young people engaged in `` specific business or activity'' related to `` legitimate employment'' after the curfew hours, but they would have to obtain an affadavit signed by a parent or guardian and an employer. Some police officers said the curfew would be difficult to enforce and would add to patrol officers' overburdened workload.
