<HEAD>India Slashes Defense Spending, Pledges to Battle Poverty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s government has slashed defense spending and diverted funds to fight hunger, illiteracy and provide homes for the homeless. The unprecedented reduction in defense spending was contained in the government's budget for 1989-90, introduced in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday by Finance Minister <PERSON> Shankarrao </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>'s government reacted to criticism that it is oriented toward the rich by pledging to reduce official expenditures and slapping new levies on cars, televisions, electronic goods, air travel and hotel tariffs. Analysts said the budget was aimed at wooing the electorate, most of them the rural poor. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> came to power in 1984 after the assassination of his mother and predecessor, <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>. Under Indian law he is required to call national elections by the end of the year. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> will spend 2 billion rupees -LRB- $ 133 million -RRB- less on defense in the 1989-90 fiscal year compared to the previous year's expenses, <PERSON> Chavan </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s armed forces, with the sixth largest army in the world, has 1.3 million soldiers. The budget proposal calls for total spending of 821.6 billion rupees -LRB- $ 54.7 billion -RRB- in the 1989-90 fiscal year, which runs from April 1 through March 31. In 1988-89, the total budget was 735.6 billion rupees -LRB- $ 56.6 billion. -RRB- In February 1988, the exchange rate was an estimated 12 rupees to $ 1. The current rate is 15 rupees to $ 1. <PERSON> Chavan </PERSON> pledged to spend 17 billion rupees -LRB- $ 1.1 billion -RRB- on programs to fight hunger, illiteracy and provide housing for the homeless. The amount is up by 5 billion rupees -LRB- $ 333 million -RRB- from last year. The increased funds for such programs will be raised directly from taxing the upper-middle classes, including an 8 percent surcharge on annual incomes of more than 50,000 rupees or -LRB- $ 3,333 -RRB-. Government estimates for March 1988 indicate that 16.5 million families, defined as a unit of five people, need housing in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, meaning that 82.5 million people are considered homeless. <PERSON> Chavan </PERSON> said the nation was proud of the armed forces for bringing `` credit to our country when called upon to help other countries in their hour of need.'' But he added: `` All of us recognize that there is continuing need for implementing measures for greater cost effectiveness.'' <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> is spending 24 million rupees -LRB- $ 1.6 million -RRB- a day to maintain 40,000 troops in neighboring <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>. They have been stationed there since 1987 to enforce a peace accord aimed at ending the 5-year-old Tamil separatist war. Besides maintaining its armed forces on the frontiers with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> is spending a huge amount to keep its control over a Himalayan glacial ridge on the borders with <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. The 50-mile-long Siachen glacier, the longest in the <LOCATION> Himalayas </LOCATION>, is strategic because it overlooks <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and Indian military concentrations in the valleys nearby. There have been a series of confrontations on the glacier since 1983. But the skirmishes escalated into a major clash in September 1987, followed by several more clashes.
