<HEAD>Black African States Lose: U.N. To Buy Namibia Supplies From South
Africa</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with General Assembly approval.
Picks up 4th graf pvs, ``Britain, France ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The General Assembly today approved $ 416 million for the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping mission to free <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> from 74 years of South African rule. On April 1, the world body plans to begin implementing a one-year plan to create the world's newest independent nation, in the process settling the last major colonial problem in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has ruled <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> since World War I, when it captured the former German colony. In December, <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> finally agreed to cooperate with the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION>'s one-year plan to make the territory a sovereign state. The General Assembly was able to clear the last hurdle to implementing the plan after its budget subcommittee, overriding objections from several African nations, decided Tuesday night that <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeepers in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> may buy goods from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> as long as it continues to be the cheapest supplier. Countries led by <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> had delayed approval of the assessment for the force by trying to make the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> heed its own calls for trade embargoes on South African products. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> opposed the restrictions on purchases for the force, citing the higher cost of buying goods and services elsewhere that are available from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Late Tuesday, the assembly's budget committee adopted language that noted the embargoes but called on the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> to buy from the lowest bidder among the `` widest possible sources of procurement'' in the interest of `` economy and efficiency.'' A dejected Zambian Ambassador <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingiswayo </PERSON> <PERSON> Zuze </PERSON> said he viewed the compromise as the `` best as can be.'' <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> fiscal controller <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Maris </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> pledged that the world body would not buy helicopters from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, as the black African states had feared. He said peacekeeping troops would bring their own military vehicles, but mine-resistant vehicles would be needed in the early stage of the mission, and these would likely be leased from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Other <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials noted that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> is readily able to supply the $ 10.2 million in gasoline and aviation fuel the <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> force will need. The black African states had proposed that fuel be bought from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> or the <LOCATION> Congo </LOCATION> _ a more expensive proposition. In December, the five permanent members of the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> had clashed with the black African states over the size and cost of the mission. The Africans wanted 7,500 peacekeepers sent, at a cost of up to $ 700 million. The <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> instead adopted the Big Five plan of sending just 4,650 personnel, with the rest held in reserve. The Big Five _ the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> _ pay 57 percent of all peacekeeping costs. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> mission in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> is to oversee November parliamentary elections in the territory also known as <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> agreed to grant <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> independence as part of an accords signed in December that also call for the withdrawal from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> of an estimated 50,000 Cuban troops who have aided that country's Marxist government in a 14-year-old war against South African-supported rebels.
