<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION> wildfire moved away from a major interstate power line today after firefighters in a helicopter dropped incendiary bombs the size of ping-pong balls to create a buffer in the drought-parched region. Downpours that drenched parts of the southern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> coast Tuesday brought only a few light showers to the fire zone, but optimism grew today with more rain in the forecast. `` We're probably in better shape than we have been all week,'' forestry division spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitson </PERSON> said. `` It looks like we've got some moisture coming into the state right now, and things have cooled down considerably. Fanned by steady 10 mph winds, the 3-day-old blaze burned an estimated 12,000 acres before stalling at a drainage canal at the <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> line northwest of <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION> early this morning, forestry officials said. Thick smoke from burning resins in sawgrass and melaleuca trees forced the <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrol </ORGANIZATION> to close eight miles of highway for about an hour Tuesday, and prompted complaints from as far as 30 miles away in <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, state forestry spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kern </PERSON> said. Firefighters dropped incendiary bombs from a helicopter to start backfires designed to keep the 10-mile-long wall of flame away from interstate power lines serving more than 3 million <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> residents. <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Light </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> shut off power on the three 500,000-volt lines for four hours during Tuesday's operation. No blackouts were reported. In 1985, a fire that burned more than 100,000 acres engulfed power lines and caused widespread blackouts in southern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. Today, forestry officials on the western side of the <LOCATION> Everglades </LOCATION> contained a 4,050-acre fire that burned through cypress and palmetto-dotted scrubland, duty officer <PERSON> Debra </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said. Officials planned to use incendiary bombs on the blaze later today to burn remaining fuel. That blaze was stalled just south of <LOCATION> Alligator </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alley </LOCATION>, a two-lane highway connecting <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION> to the Gulf coast, said <PERSON> Fort </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> forestry officer <PERSON> Roberta </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>. The two wildfires were the largest of more than 65 fires the forestry division has fought since Monday with about 400 firefighters, said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Maynard </PERSON>, spokesman for the agency in <LOCATION> Tallahassee </LOCATION>. Tuesday's rainfall caused flooding that closed the main runway at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale-Hollywood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> for two hours. The rain also caused a rush-hour mudslide onto Interstate 95 that backed traffic up for six miles. But little of it hit wilderness areas, where rainfall has averaged less than half normal levels since last fall. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> forecast scattered showers in some parts of the state over the next few days, but nothing that would alleviate the growing fire danger, <PERSON> Maynard </PERSON> said.
