<HEAD>Deficit Panel's Final Report Split on Party Lines</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts grafs 6-10, Asked if, with reaction.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A high-level advisory group once seen as the best hope for crafting a bipartisan solution to the nation's budget problems ended up deadlocked, issuing a final report today that splits essentially along party lines. The seven Republicans on the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and the one Democrat appointed by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> endorsed the president's pledge against raising taxes and praised his budget submission to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, calling it a `` workable plan for eliminating the deficit'' by 1993 However, the six Democrats on the panel who were appointed by the congressional leadership signed a minority report calling <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s budget `` neither theoretically sound nor politically realistic. The administration's $ 1.16 trillion spending plan for 1990 `` rules out any discussion of additional revenues and relies heavily on harsh and disproportionate reductions in domestic spending,'' the Democrats said. The sharply divergent reports ended up echoing the current debate between <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and congressional Democrats, where both sides remain far apart on solutions to a budget crisis which is expected to produce a deficit of $ 170 billion this year. Asked if the administration was disappointed that the panel had failed its mission to come up with a bipartisan formula for reducing the budget deficit, <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said: `` They did an excellent job in trying to carry out their mandate. It was a very difficult debate and discussion that they held.'' `` Some of the things in that report are very useful, and we'll have to analyze it for a more detailed respnse,'' he added `` They did the best they could,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON>, D-Calif., called the commission's report `` disappointing,'' but said it was not surprising `` With little support or leadership from the president or the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the commission was unable to face up to the difficult issues,'' he said in a written statement. `` It had no choice but to punt.'' The commission, which now goes out of existence, was a deep disappointment to supporters, who pushed legislation creating the panel through <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in the wake of the October 1987 stock market crash. Their hopes were that a panel of the nation's top business, labor and political leaders would be able to agree on a combination of spending cuts and tax increases to solve a deficit problem which has almost tripled the national debt over the past eight years. But while campaigning for the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was openly critical of the commission, which had the backing of his Republican primary opponent, Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> vowed to reject any final report which called for a tax increase The commission's <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> co-chairman, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON>, said he had `` hoped for a great deal more,'' but that the commission's fate was sealed by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign against tax increases. <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> co-chairman <PERSON> Drew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> had hoped at one time to adopt an ambitious package that would cut $ 50 billion to $ 60 billion from the deficit, in part by raising taxes. But <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON> drew criticism from within his own party last fall when he suggested cuts in government benefit programs, including <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION>, would be needed to balance the government's books. Not everyone was disappointed in the outcome of the panel's work. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Kleckner </PERSON>, a Republican member of the commission who was an outspoken opponent of tax increases, said the majority report reflected the `` will of taxpayers throughout the nation.'' `` Testimony to the commission from 85 witnesses and more than 1,300 responses from private citizens and groups this past 11 months clearly indicated opposition to higher taxes and irresponsible spending,'' <PERSON> Kleckner </PERSON> said. Sen. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, another commission member, said he was pleased that both the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> and Democratic reports criticized continued use of Social Security payroll taxes to mask the extent of the budget deficit. Both reports called for a goal of not simply eliminating the deficit but achieving surpluses to build up the funds necessary to cover the retirement of the `` Baby Boom'' generation. Both reports endorsed the need to reform the congressional budget process with the Republicans offering a detailed list of suggestions, many of them long championed by <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and now <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. They include a constitutional balanced-budget amendment, presidential line-item veto authority in spending bills, a streamlined congressional process for making budget decisions and two-year rather than annual budgets. Commission member Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, D-Pa., a former <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> chairman, blamed partisanship by Republicans for the group's failure to succeed `` The president did n't want a bipartisan deficit reduction plan. He wanted his own plan, the flexible freeze, and he insisted on it from <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> members,'' <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> said in an interview. `` Instead of something bold that could have moved us forward, we end up leaving it to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the administration to continue the fight.'' While <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> criticized the commission during the campaign, he did appoint the final two members in December, former Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Laxalt </PERSON>, R-Nev., and longtime friend <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> `` Lud'' <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> congressman from <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> After taking office, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> decided against extending the panel's March 1 reporting deadline for another six months, a step many on the panel had urged as a way of keeping the commission alive in the hopes that it eventually could reach a consensus That decision basically sealed the panel's fate and with only a few weeks remaining, the panel abandoned efforts for any compromise and began drafting majority and minority reports. In addition to <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON>, <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, the other Democrats on the panel were <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON>; <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> president <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON> and <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Rohatyn </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investment banker In addition to <PERSON> Kleckner </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, who is chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION>, the other Republicans on the panel were Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> of <LOCA