<HEAD>D.C. Tourism Grows Despite Crime Wave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A trade group official says tourism in the nation's capital grew by a `` comfortable rate'' last year despite a drug-related crime wave in the city. `` Fortunately, we have n't found it affecting us,'' said <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Tibor </PERSON>, director of tourism for the <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Visitors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a trade group that encourages tourists to visit the city. `` We've had a nice comfortable rate of growth.'' About 19.6 million visitors came to the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> area last year, up 3 percent from the previous year, according to the association's annual report scheduled for release next month. `` We've done better than some of the previous doom-and-gloom forecasts,'' she said Tuesday. The district had a record 372 homicides last year, and police said 60 percent of them were related to drugs. A total of 91 people were slain in January and February of this year, compared with 54 in the same period last year.
