<HEAD>Ethics Panel Refers Moonlighting Questions To Others</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 7 grafs new with decisions on outside income. Picks up 3rd
graf pvs, The panel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s ethics commission agreed today there should be a uniform limit on the outside income earned by top government officials but called on <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to set the limit and let the President exempt some activities, such as scholarly writing. The eight-member panel completed its fifth and final working day still sharply divided over moonlighting by judges, members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, top executive branch officials and the most senior aides in all three branches. Their compromise recommendation was that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> limit outside earned income to a fixed percentage of an official's federal salary. A majority of the group favored a figure closer to the 15 percent which nows governs the executive branch rather than the higher amounts allowed in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the judiciary. And they asked that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> allow to the president to exempt from the limit income from categories of work that do not raise ethical issues or interfere with the full performance of official duties. They tried but failed to agree on a list of exemptions. Former White House counsel <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Cutler </PERSON> suggested listing teaching by judges, among others. But former Attorney General <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, who wanted to exempt royalties, objected to exempting teaching. `` When you get above 15 percent of salary for teaching, you're not a fulltime government worker,'' <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> said `` You're not in your office when you're teaching and you need to be there so other judges can talk to you.'' With that compromise, the panel completed work on the recommendations due to go to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> by March 9. The issue of moonlighting income was the most divisive it encountered in a review of all federal ethics laws and rules. This issue had consumed more than an hour of debate on Tuesday. The panel was wrestling with questions such as how much money a federal judge should be allowed to make teaching at a law school, and whether federal officials should be allowed to make more money writing novels or songs than from the government. These questions about the proper limits of income earned outside government work have divided the commission more sharply than any others it has confronted in four day-long meetings. The panel could not decide Tuesday whether to recommend a ceiling on all outside earned income or whether certain activities should be exempt from any ceiling because they pose no conflict of interest. At one point, former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> counsel <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Cutler </PERSON> argued, `` Suppose you write a popular song one night; that does n't belong to the government.'' To which former Attorney General <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> replied, `` We do n't want a government of songwriters. Last week, the panel tentatively approved applying the executive branch's outside-income limit _ 15 percent of the government salary, with no exemptions _ to top officials of all three branches. There is no limit now for judges; the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> limits members to 30 percent of salary and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to 40 percent. <PERSON> Cutler </PERSON> argued, `` If the next <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON> is deep in the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, all he can get out of it is 15 percent of a GS-14 salary or he'd have to quit.'' <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bello </PERSON>, general counsel to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> special trade representative, replied that the ceiling would only apply to top officials, at GS-17 and above. <PERSON> Cutler </PERSON>, however, found other examples: `` Suppose you work for the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> on the MX missile and you develop an idea for hybrid corn one night that's worth $ 1 million _ you've got to give it away.'' `` I will dissent from a cap unless there are some totally excepted categories of earned income, such as writing a popular song,'' he said. <PERSON> Cutler </PERSON> said he had been called by a federal judge whose teaching and legal writings bring him income greater than 15 percent of his federal salary. He said the judge said he would quit the bench if the cap were enacted by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` A judge teaching at an accredited law school is a fine activity and there is not the shadow of the possibility of a conflict,'' <PERSON> Cutler </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, who is a former appellate judge, responded, `` If you want to be a judge, you ought to be a full-time judge.'' <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> also said exemptions would send the message that `` we do n't think it's unethical not to give your full-time effort to your government job. <PERSON> Bello </PERSON> also backed the ceiling. `` I would n't want to drive a good judge off the bench, but ... I oppose watering down the current law.'' `` These activities do take time from your work,'' she added. `` And public confidence can be undermined if public servants are taking time from work.'' The panel's chairman, <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkey </PERSON>, a former appellate judge, advocated the exemptions, particularly for judges to teach law. `` This interplay between a live judge and a law school is very vital to our society.'' If there are no exemptions, <PERSON> Wilkey </PERSON> said, `` We'll lose the brightest minds _ people who've got the extra energy to do more work. They're the big contributors to our society and we'll lose them from government.'' <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Fielding </PERSON>, who was <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> counsel for President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, said the panel seemed to be ignoring other kinds of outside earned income, such as breeding race horses or rose-growing. Seeing no reason to discriminate in favor of some outside activities over others, Fielding said he leaned toward a cap.
</TEXT>
