<HEAD>Pentagon Misses Deadlines, Cites Broader Review as Reason</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration missed two more congressional deadlines Wednesday for staking out positions on major defense issues, saying it was n't ready to produce reports dealing with Star Wars and the B-2 stealth bomber. Col. <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Monteverde </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said acting <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Taft </PERSON> <PERSON> IV </PERSON> was notifying <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that the March 1 deadline for the <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wars </ORGANIZATION> report would be missed because the future of the anti-missile defense system is being addressed in a much broader <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> strategic policy review. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, in a brief statement, said the report on the B-2 would not go forward Wednesday because it was `` still in coordination.'' An <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> official who asked not to be named said, however, that that report also was being delayed until the national security review was completed. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, in his budget address to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, announced last month he had ordered the broad policy review and said he expected it to be completed within 90 days. On Feb. 15, the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> cited the same review as the reason it would not meet a deadline for choosing between two mobile nuclear missiles _ the single-warhead Midgetman or a rail-car version of the 10-warhead MX. The missed deadlines come at the same time <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has been unable to win <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> confirmation of his choice as defense secretary, former Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> and other administration officials have insisted that Tower's troubles are not responsible for the failure to meet the congressional deadlines. Rather, they assert that those deadlines were set much too early for a new administration and that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wants to take the time to review the nation's entire strategic posture. Other officials at the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, however, say little in the way of policy formation is being accomplished at the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> because of the lack of leadership. Those officials, holdovers from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, spoke on the condition of anonymity. The first report that had been due Wednesday dealt with one deployment option for a Star Wars system _ the so-called ALPS or Accidental Launch Protection System. First suggested by Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, D-Ga., the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, ALPS would entail the construction of a small missile-defense system capable of stopping a missile fired by accident or by a terrorist group The second report due Wednesday involved the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>'s B-2, a new bomber that is supposed to be almost invisible to radar. The first of the bombers was unveiled in November but has not yet flown. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> wants to build 132 of the planes, but estimated in December that, counting research and development costs, the bombers would cost more than $ 500 million each. Even if research and development expenses are discounted, each plane will cost $ 305 million to build. Faced with that kind of expense, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> said it wanted a report by March 1 `` setting forth the total program cost, in constant and in current dollars, of the <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> B-2 Bomber program.''
