<HEAD>Senate Confirms Watkins as Energy Secretary</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with full Senate approving Watkins; picks up
6th graf, Although he ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted 99-0 today to confirm <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> as energy secretary, handing the retired admiral the `` daunting challenge'' of refurbishing the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s crippled network of nuclear weapons factories The vote came less than four hours after the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> voted 19-0 to recommend that <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>, 61, be made the first career military man to head the department since it was created in 1977. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, D.-La., chairman of the committee, told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> that the job of reviving and cleaning up the nuclear weapons complex was a top priority `` It is perhaps the most daunting challenge that we have ever given to anybody in the Cabinet ... anytime in the history of this country,'' <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> called <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> `` a man of that substance and that reputation,'' echoing the warm praise <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> won during his confirmation hearing last Wednesday. Although he has no experience in the conventional energy field, <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> developed an expertise in nuclear power during a 41-year <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> career that included training in reactor technology as well as the command of a nuclear submarine. Now he's about to enter battle against one of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's biggest challenges: revitalizing the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s nuclear weapons complex and planning a long-range cleanup operation that may cost $ 100 billion. The <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spends about two-thirds of its budget, which this year is $ 14 billion, on developing, building and testing nuclear weapons for the Pentagon. The remaining one-third is spent on conventional energy projects, mainly research. Key parts of the 12-state weapons complex are shut down because of safety, technical and managerial concerns, leaving the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> without the capacity to build nuclear weapons for the first time since the dawn of the nuclear age. `` It's the most daunting management task I think we've ever given to anybody I've seen in government,'' Sen. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, D-La., said during <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>' Feb. 22 hearing Sen. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> McClure </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Idaho </LOCATION>, said that although the weapons plant problems were created by past administrations, `` You, Admiral <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>, will be the man in the limelight or hotseat charged with getting the situation effectively under control as quickly as possible.'' <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> told his confirmation hearing the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s weapons complex was `` antique, out-of-date, desperately in need of change. He also ripped the department's management structure, calling it `` a mess'' and vowing to install the core of a new management team to oversee the plants within six months. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> is a 1949 graduate of the <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Annapolis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, and was hand-picked by the late admiral <PERSON> Hyman </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rickover </PERSON>, father of the modern nuclear <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANI