<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> signed a new agreement to buy the $ 5.4 billion <LOCATION> Shoreham </LOCATION> nuclear plant for $ 1 and dismantle it, and a key lawmaker today said he likes the deal. Under the agreement, the <ORGANIZATION> Long </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lighting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> will let the state tear down the never-used plant, which has had to wage licensing battles since its completion in 1985 and nearly bankrupted the utility with cost overruns and delays. `` It is time to end this matter once and for all and turn our energies to new, productive measures for <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and the state,'' <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> said Tuesday. Unlike a similar agreement last year, which was killed by state legislators, <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> predicted this deal would succeed because it largely bypasses the Legislature. State <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Marino </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> Republican whose support for the plan is crucial to its success, said today that he likes the deal. <PERSON> Shoreham </PERSON> is on <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, 55 miles from <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. `` I think we should get the issue behind us, at least have some kind of direction and this gives us stability,'' <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> said. Other reaction was mixed. <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> business leaders contend the $ 2.5 billion loss that <ORGANIZATION> Lilco </ORGANIZATION> plans to take on the plant during the next three years will be passed to its customers, who already pay among the nation's highest electric bills. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kulka </PERSON>, of the Association for a <LOCATION> Better </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOC