e <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> last week announced a proposed rule change aimed at revitalizing the nation's nuclear power industry by cutting down the licensing process for plants to six years or less, compared with the recent average of 13 years. Many utilities, swamped by debt from nuclear plant construction, contend that long delays in obtaining an <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> license are a main reason why no new plants have been ordered since the mid-1970s. The 800-megawatt <LOCATION> Shoreham </LOCATION> plant, which was proposed in 1966, has thus far been unable to win anything more than a 5 percent testing license from federal officials. That's largely due to the refusal of <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> officials to cooperate in emergency planning for the plant. <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> and the officials long have argued that <PERSON> Shoreham </PERSON> should never be allowed to open because the area around the plant could n't be safely evacuated during a nuclear emergency <ORGANIZATION> Lilco </ORGANIZATION> disputed that. Tuesday's agreement is subject to approval by <ORGANIZATION> Lilco </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors and shareholders, a process that utility spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Lois </PERSON> said would `` take approximately three months.'' `` While the approvals for this agreement are being obtained, the company will continue to vigorously pursue a full power operating license for <LOCATION> Shoreham </LOCATION> before the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>,'' said a <ORGANIZATION> Lilco </ORGANIZATION> statement. However, it said it would operate the plant only if shareholders veto the agreement, which also requires approval by the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, the state <ORGANIZATIO