<HEAD>Cargo Door Believed Found; Officials Not Sure They'll Retrieve It</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 7th graf pvs, `We have ...' with details
on how cargo door could be raised.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Radar has pinpointed an object believed to be the cargo door that tore from a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jumbo jet, but federal investigators say they are n't sure whether it can be retrieved from under 16,800 feet of water. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said late Tuesday that <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> radar tracked a large object 85 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> about 45 seconds after the pilot of Flight 811 reported an in-flight emergency. Nine passengers were swept to their deaths when a 10-by-20 foot section of the fuselage, including the cargo door, tore from the right side of the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 at 22,000 feet on Friday. Twenty-seven others were treated for injuries. `` The radar picked up something that could be a large piece of metal, possibly the cargo door,'' <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> investigator <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> said Tuesday night. `` That information is going back to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION><LOCATION> , </LOCATION> <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, to see if we can indeed determine ... that was the cargo door, and its exact location.'' <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> said the door would be `` very helpful to us in our analysis,'' but added that he did not know whether the object could be salvaged and the decision to try would be up to the full five-member <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> board. `` We have the location at the surface of the water,'' he said. `` You're talking about three miles -LRB- down -RRB-, one can only guess where that is.'' <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolcott </PERSON>, a technician and research submarine pilot at the <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> Undersea Research Lab at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hawaii </ORGANIZATION>, today said the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> is about the only agency with equipment capable of recovering the door. Such a search would probably involve use of an underwater sonar sled and a remote-controlled vehicle equipped with a camera, he said. The vehicle could probably hook a line to the door so it could be lifted to the surface, he said. The least likely possibility because of the tremendous expense _ up to $ 40,000 a day _ would be the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s Sea Cliff, one of the world's few manned research submarines capable of reaching that depth, <PERSON> Wolcott </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION>'s field work was nearly completed and investigators would leave <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> today and tomorrow. Earlier Tuesday, investigators reported that the same front right cargo door had had a recent history of problems, including a seal that was repaired in January. Investigators had not yet determined whether the recent repairs were connected to the accident, said <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Drucella </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>. `` We just do n't know that right now,'' she said. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Rob </PERSON> <PERSON> Doughty </PERSON> said the faulty door seal had to be fixed before the plane could fly again, and other electrical problems did not affect the plane's airworthiness. On Dec. 5, the door's electrical door-closing mechanism worked intermittently, <PERSON> Doughty </PERSON> said. It was repaired, but failed again on Dec. 13 and Dec. 22, he said. It was fixed in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> on Dec. 23 and no further trouble was reported, he said. `` I might add, though, that it is completely proper to close this door manually, and that's what was done,'' he said. <PERSON> Doughty </PERSON> said he did not know the details of the work on the door's seal, but `` I do n't think it was major.'' Meanwhile Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> officials said a safety pin had to be replaced in a rear cargo door of a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 that was to fly from <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. The repair delayed the arrival in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> by 18 hours. Many passengers, however, said they did not mind the delay, including <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hochberg </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` How can you get aggravated at them for trying to save us?'' he asked.
