 The <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> relieved 15 recruiters and their commander of their duties in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> for alleged violations, including fabricating high school diplomas for recruits, a newspaper reported today. The <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> quoted Marine Maj. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> McLean </PERSON>, a corps spokesman at <LOCATION> Parris </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, as saying that six of the recruiters face courts-martial on charges that will be filed within the next few weeks. Punishment for the nine others ranged from forfeiture of pay to letters of reprimand, he said. Investigators found recruiters provided as many as 17 diplomas for recruits who never graduated from high school, the newspaper said. In addition, the criminal records of some recruits were omitted from enlistment papers, as were medical problems that could have disqualified recruits from serving, the Press said. The investigation began in January after a suburban <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> recruit became ill at boot camp on <LOCATION> Parris </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and had to be hospitalized for a severe ulcer his mother says she reported to the recruiter, the newspaper said. Investigators later identified 82 others who may have been recruited improperly. Thirty of the 83 recruits were discharged because of enlistment problems, <PERSON> McLean </PERSON> said. The Corps retained 49 and has yet decided what to do with the others. The head of the <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> recruiting office, Maj. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eberhart </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, was relieved Feb. 14 of duties he had held since 1986. Maj. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Kappel </PERSON>, a corps spokesman in the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> dist