<HEAD>Libya Could Easily Share Chemical Weapons: Webster</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> said Wednesday Libyan strongman <PERSON> Moammar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON>'s chemical weapons plant is so big that he could easily share its output with other radical nations. `` The production capability is far more than Col. <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON> could ever need or use by any stretch of the imagination,'' <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` Is this going to become just another form of currency, ... a brokering capability?'' he asked. <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> also said <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> could have the capacity of targeting such countries as <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> with chemical weapons if <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON>'s forces obtain air-to-air refueling capacity for their bombers. `` It moves it -LRB- the chemical weapons threat -RRB- off the battlefields and puts it into the cities and strategic areas'' of the whole <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, he said. <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> was asked by Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.C. </LOCATION>, if elements of the West German armed forces had aided Libyan efforts to obtain air-to-air refueling capability. <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> said he would prefer to discuss the matter in a closed, non-public session but told <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, `` You're right on target.'' <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> later declined to elaborate on his comment. <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON> has said the plant was built to produce pharmaceuticals, not chemical weapons. <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> said that even if that were true the facility could be converted to manufacture weapons within a day's time The <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> director did say, as he and other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have said before, that West German corporations as well as those from other European and <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> countries have helped <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> acquire a chemical weapons production capability, and that it `` would have been virtually impossible'' for <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> to do that without such help. But he said the West German government _ after a period of hesitation _ has become more willing to address the situation and is moving to tighten export controls on the chemicals and technologies needed to produce chemical weapons. <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> said that while there was an initial `` slowness'' on the part of some countries to accept available intelligence information that a problem of chemical weapons proliferation existed, that is no longer true.
