<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-89 1448EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w BC-DeficitExcerpts 3Takes   03-01 0876</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Deficit Excerpts, 3 Takes,860-up</SECOND>
<HEAD>Excerpts from Deficit Commission Reports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are excerpts from the majority and minority reports of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which were submitted to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and congressional leaders Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MAJORITY REPORT</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 As the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> approaches the 1990s, and with the economy continuing to expand dynamically, economic policy, shaped to some extent by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>, should be designed not only to sustain economic growth in the near term, but to help create the national wealth that will be the basis for future growth. Budget deficits are a direct drain on the national savings pool. To enable investment to grow rapidly, either private savings must increase or the necessary capital must be borrowed from abroad. Nonetheless, the decade of the 1980s has been characterized by high savings and low spending in most industrial countries, contrasted with low savings and high spending in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, including that by the federal government. Such imbalances can not be sustained indefinitely. One result of these spending-savings imbalances has been historically large trade deficits in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and correspondingly large trade surpluses in a number of other countries. Large trade deficits, like budget deficits, drain domestic savings as more and more of the income produced in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> flows abroad. One factor causing trade deficits is that American consumers like to buy foreign goods, including capital equipment. American manufacturers should become more competitive and regain the favor of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> marketplace. Another objective is to increase investment relative to consumption in the economy. One of the best ways to accomplish this is to adopt the recommendation that the capital gains tax be sharply cut. ... Recent data suggests that the industrialized countries are becoming more capital intensive. The country that is the farthest along in this process, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, has a rate of productivity growth that is almost twice that of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> with real income growth also twice as high. Americans must significantly increase savings that, in turn, will be used to finance capital investment. Clearly, one task is to reduce the budget deficits and factors that result in the federal government being a drain on the national saving pool, and to do so without raising taxes. This should reduce the real cost of capital and stimulate even more investment demand. The next step is to set a course for creating government surpluses or at least inhibiting future government deficits while at the same time not inhibiting economic growth. This will be a long term process. Whatever the benefits of deficit reduction, the nation must not expect that a balanced budget, or even government surpluses, will solve all our economic problems. Comparing the economic performance of the key industrial countries over the past 15 years does not suggest that countries with the lowest budget deficits are those that necessarily grow the fastest, have the lowest inflation, have the highest savings rates, have the lowest real interest rates, or the lowest trade deficits. There are many other factors besides balanced budgets that could contribute to economic growth. Rapidly changing technology and products, newly productive economic centers, and increasingly integrated world markets suggest that an economic policy driven by a single goal is not appropriate. Economic policy should not only address the traditional concerns about capital investment and productivity in the industrial sector, but also such hard-to-measure items as productivity in service industries and educated labor forces. The budget should and will be balanced over time. Indeed, the administration's budget lays out one workable plan for eliminating the deficit. There are other alternatives reflecting different priorities, but with equal or greater spending restraint, that could balance the budget by fiscal 1993, as required by Gramm-Rudman-Hollings -LRB- GRH -RRB-, without raising taxes. ... The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has been working on this project for approximately 11 months. We have heard from 85 witnesses and read over 1,300 responses from private citizens and groups. Our mandate was to recommend ways to eliminate the budget deficit while not impeding economic growth. It is clear that the president would prefer to coordinate this activity with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on a one-to-one basis. Indeed, this is the manner in which this process should proceed. We should continue to reduce the deficit as a percentage of GNP. We support the position that the deficit can be resolved through restraints on the growth of federal spending without increasing taxes or affecting low income, means-tested benefits. Therefore, we recommend restraining spending increases while keeping growth strong as the mainstay of budget policy. With an estimated $ 82 billion in additional revenues in fiscal year 1990, it is clear that we do not have to and should not raise taxes but, rather, should restrain the rate of growth in federal spending. The Gramm-Rudman-Hollings deficit targets represent arbitrary but appropriate goals for budget policy over the next several years. These goals, if realized, will be attained without any new tax measures and should result in a federal deficit that continues to decline significantly and consistently. ... We believe budget process reform should be an integral part of any deficit reduction plan. Any agreement on the budget should be accompanied by process reform to rebuild public confidence in national fiscal and monetary policy. ...
</TEXT>
