<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GORMAN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If a guy changing a tire can so fascinate motorists that freeway traffic is backed up for miles, imagine what rubberneckers would make of 1,700 giant yellow roadside umbrellas planted by the artist <PERSON> Christo </PERSON>. If all goes as planned, that's just what drivers traveling the steep, winding section of Interstate 5 known as the Grapevine will see: miles of octagonal umbrellas, each 28 feet in diameter. <PERSON> Christo </PERSON> plans the display as part of a two-nation spectacle for three weeks in October 1991. He wants to set up 1,300 blue umbrellas in rural <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and says he will pay the project's $ 10 million to $ 12 million cost. `` The umbrella is something extremely familiar to everyone around the world,'' the Bulgarian artist said. `` It's so enchanting, so uplifting. It has a fabulous connotation. The umbrella is very much linked to the greatness of kings.'' The <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Highway Patrol is diplomatically embracing the project even while worrying about the effect on <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s major north-south highway a little more than an hour's drive north of downtown <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. `` It will be a traffic nightmare,'' said Capt. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrington </PERSON>, `` but it will be a thing of absolute beauty. ... We're really excited about it. <PERSON> Christo </PERSON> previously gift-wrapped the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> islands dotting <LOCATION> Biscayne </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> in hot pink woven polypropylene, drew a giant curtain across a <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> valley, and shrouded <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>' oldest bridge in champagne-colored fabric.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> celebrated its 122nd birthday Wednesday, the history-minded recalled an incident that could be called the Great Seal Steal. Before <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> became a state on March 1, 1867, <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> was the territorial capital, and a lot of people there opposed the decision to make <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> the state capital. So they kept secreted away the 60-pound state seal. When the new Capitol was ready for occupancy on Dec. 1, 1868, according to previously published reports, then-Secretary of State <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennard </PERSON> declared: `` We'll have to steal the seal! There is no other way.'' <PERSON> Kennard </PERSON> hitched up his horses and set out for <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> on a Sunday. He entered the territorial Capitol, wrapped up the seal and stashed it under the seat of his buggy. He whipped his horses into action and by nightfall had crossed the <LOCATION> Platte </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, the line of demarcation between forces pushing <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> or <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> as the state capital. Early the next morning, he appeared on the steps of the new Capitol. There, on Dec. 3, 1868, he put the impression of the insignia from the state seal to a proclamation declaring the capital of <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> as <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>, County of <LOCATION> Lancaster </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, and that it was `` open for business.'' For 121 years, that same seal has been used almost daily for hundreds of official governmental transactions. The seal depicts a steamboat ascending the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> river </LOCATION>, a smith with hammer and anvil, a settler's cabin, sheaves of wheat and stalks of growing corn, and the <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> in the background.
