<HEAD>Thousands Attend Mass Funeral for Massacre Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of mourners wept openly Wednesday at a funeral for 38 Sinhalese men, women and children who were shot and hacked to death by Tamil rebels this week, police said. The crowd of about 2,500 Sinhalese rice paddy farmers flocked to <LOCATION> Welikande </LOCATION>, a remote jungle village about 100 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, to mourn victims of Monday night's massacre. They dispersed peacefully after the ceremony, a police official said. The government led by President <PERSON> Ranasinghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> was represented at the joint burial by Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ranjan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wijeratne </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary General <PERSON> Sepala </PERSON> <PERSON> Attygalle </PERSON>, according to a police officer who spoke on condition of anonymity. The victims were buried in graves in an abandoned rice paddy. Funeral expenses, including the cost of coffins, were paid by the government. `` Almost every home has hoisted white flags to mourn the deaths. There is tension in the village, but police and soldiers are on alert,'' the police sergeant said. The victims of the massacre were all from Sinhalese rice paddy farming families. Most came to Welikande in the early 1980s as part of a resettlement program after their homes were flooded by the Mahaveli hydroelectric dam and irrigation project. The sergeant said that Tuesday night a child died of wounds suffered in the attack, bringing the death toll to 38 _ 22 men, five women and 11 children. Police Tuesday blamed the attack on the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eelam </ORGANIZATION>, the most powerful of the Tamil guerrilla groups that have been waging a separatist war against the Sinhalese majority since 1983. More than 8,500 people have died since the insurrection began. The <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> denied taking part in the massacre, the third in northeastern <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> in 16 days. At least 81 people died in attacks on Sinhalese civilians. Welikande is in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Province </LOCATION> near the border with <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Province </LOCATION>. North Central Province is predominantly Sinhalese, while <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Province </ORGANIZATION> is about evenly divided among Sinhalese, Tamils and Moslems. Tamil militants say the government has been settling Sinhalese in the area to tilt the ethnic balance. Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, account for 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people and say they are discriminated against by Sinhalese in jobs, education and the use of the Sinhalese language. Sinhalese, who are mostly Buddhists, make up 75 percent of the population and dominate the government and military.
