<HEAD>Supreme Court Asked for Help in Work-on-Sunday Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> was urged Wednesday to grant unemployment benefits to a man who says even though he is not a member of an organized religious group his Christian beliefs dictate he not work Sundays. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> French </PERSON>, a lawyer for <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Frazee </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, said his client's right to freely exercise his religious beliefs was violated by the state's denial of unemployment pay. `` The belief must be sincerely held and it must be rooted in religion,'' said <LOCATION> French </LOCATION>. But he said once state officials accept that a person's refusal to work Sundays fits those conditions it does not matter whether the person belongs to an established religious group or sect. The task for the justices, who are expected to decide the case by July, may have been complicated Wednesday when <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> officials changed the state's approach to the dispute. The <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> previously said <PERSON> Frazee </PERSON>'s basis for not working on Sundays must be more than an individually held religious scruple. The belief must be based `` on some tenets or dogma accepted by the individual of some church, sect or denomination,'' the agency said. But on Wednesday, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> Solicitor General <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruiz </PERSON> argued that <PERSON> Frazee </PERSON> was denied unemployment benefits not because of the absence of affiliation to a religious group but because his belief was `` personal'' rather than religious. `` The sincerity of a personal belief is not the same as a religious belief,'' <PERSON> Ruiz </PERSON> said. `` Just because someone sincerely holds a belief does n't make it religious.'' `` Even if he says that it comes from God?'' asked Justice <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> in a tone of disbelief. `` It seems to me you are just questioning if he was sincere.'' The state's shift in position also was challenged by Justice <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>. `` I do n't understand why you are making this argument,'' she said, adding that the state should have been forthright and `` confessed error.'' Justice <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said the state now seems to be encouraging the court to `` affirm a patently unconstitutional ruling.'' And Justice <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> said the state appeared to be asking the court to decide that <PERSON> Frazee </PERSON>'s beliefs were not sincerely religious even though lower courts and state agencies had not questioned <PERSON> Frazee </PERSON>'s sincerity. <PERSON> Frazee </PERSON> was disqualified from receiving unemployment benefits after he turned down a temporary job assignment in 1984 that would have required him to work Wednesdays through Sundays. He said as a Christian he believed non-emergency work on Sunday is forbidden. A state appeals court ruled against <PERSON> Frazee </PERSON>. It said, `` The injunction against Sunday labor must be found in a tenet or dogma of an established religious sect. -LRB- <PERSON> Frazee </PERSON> -RRB- does not profess to be a member of any such sect.'' <PERSON> Ruiz </PERSON> made no attempt Wednesday to defend that reasoning. Instead, he said <PERSON> Frazee </PERSON> failed to provide enough evidence that his refusal to work Sundays was predicated on a sincerely held religious belief. `` This gentleman may have sincere beliefs,'' <PERSON> Ruiz </PERSON> said. `` But there is not enough evidence to support it.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGAN