<BYLINE>By HAL SPENCER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As you cruise down the freeway and chat on your cellular telephone with your sweetheart, lawyer, bookie or broker, bear in mind that somebody _ anybody _ could be listening. The fact that conversations on cellular telephones can be easily pulled from the airwaves with inexpensive radio scanners upsets a lot of people, including a few state legislators who have proposed a measure to make eavesdropping illegal. Action on the bill has been put off for a year while a legislative committee studies it. At a hearing Tuesday for the <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utilities </ORGANIZATION>, one cellular phone user urged action. `` If there's no prohibition against listening in, why not just go to a CB?'' asked lobbyist <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON>. `` The point for me is that my phone is not like a <ORGANIZATION> CB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION>. I'm paying more to the phone company to use my car phone than to use a phone at my home.'' <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> is one of scores of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> residents who use a cellular phone, for which he pays $ 150 a month in subscriber charges. Attorney <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Senn </PERSON>, a legislative researcher, said either technology must solve the problem or lawmakers must address it. She said the problem will only grow along with the popularity of cellular car phones, which now are estimated to number 1 million in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Senn </PERSON> said legislators have heard from lawyers and physicians who are especially concerned at eavesdropping because some of their conversations are with clients and considered privileged. `` We're talking about a lot of sensitive phone conversations where people might not even be aware that somebody could be listening in,'' she said. <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> acknowledged that a state law might not stop eavesdroppers, especially since a 1986 federal law, which carries a $ 500 fine for eavesdropping, seems to have had little effect. But he said at least `` bragging rights would stop'' among eavesdroppers who have been known to tape conversations and play them on commercial radio stations for entertainment. He said he heard just such a program recently on a <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> station. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> McBride </PERSON>, another researcher for the legislative committee, said radio scanners with a megahertz band of 800 to 900 are capable of picking up cellular telephone conversations. He said the cellular phone industry is working on ways to scramble conversations with relatively affordable technology. European systems already are secure against eavesdroppers, <PERSON> McBride </PERSON> said.
