<HEAD>Government Criticized for Food-Poisoning Scare</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A parliamentary committee criticized the government Wednesday for its handling of a salmonella-in-eggs crisis triggered by a junior minister's remark that most British egg production was infected. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Select </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> said `` the likelihood of an egg being infected with salmonella is very small'' but cautioned that a sharp rise in salmonella poisoning cases from 10,000 in 1981 to 23,000 in the first 10 months of 1988 was `` cause for concern.'' Egg sales fell 60 percent after the junior health minister, <PERSON> Edwina </PERSON> <PERSON> Currie </PERSON>, said Dec. 3 that most egg production was infected with salmonella. Confronted by lawsuits from farmers, Mrs. <PERSON> Currie </PERSON> resigned, but the affair prompted a major public debate about food hygiene. The committee said the government, and not just Mrs. <PERSON> Currie </PERSON>, was to blame from failing to correct her `` wrong'' remark. Critics have accused the government of siding with food producers, neglecting the interests of consumers and issuing conflicting statements that confused the public. Last month, the government ordered an inquiry into food safety after warning pregnant women against eating soft cheeses and ordering farmers to slaughter salmonella-infected chickens. Health Secretary <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON> said Wednesday the government had issued health warnings `` that were very clear.'' `` I accept that we have got to do more to tell people about the safe handling of food,'' he told the <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION>. Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> `` shares the concern of the rest of the government that the health of the public is properly protected and British farming produces high quality food and also that ... we keep things in proportion,'' <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON> said. The committee said `` more should have been done sooner'' by the government to prevent eggs entering the food chain from farms responsible for poisoning outbreaks. It urged the government to spend more on research to counter food poisoning, bring in better procedures for tracing outbreaks to their source and reduce contamination in animal foodstuffs. The government's chief medical officer, Sir <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Acheson </PERSON>, said in January that salmonella in eggs is a serious health problem but `` only a very few eggs are infected.''
