<TEXT>
 A man who set his girlfriend on fire when she told him their relationship was over was convicted of attempted murder and sentenced to 13 years and 10 months in prison, lawyers said Wednesday. <PERSON> Uilson </PERSON> <PERSON> Miyashiro </PERSON> was convicted Tuesday of attempted murder for dousing <PERSON> Cristina </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopes </PERSON> <PERSON> Afonso </PERSON> with alcohol and setting a match to her, defense lawyer <PERSON> Fabiana </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> said by telephone from <LOCATION> Curitiba </LOCATION>, 520 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION>. Miss <PERSON> Afonso </PERSON>, 24, who suffered burns over two-thirds of her body and has extensive scars on her face and arms, testified that <PERSON> Miyashiro </PERSON>, a 42-year-old opthamologist, went berserk when she told him in 1986 their relationship was over, <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Miyashiro </PERSON> broke furnishings in their apartment and poured alcohol over Miss <PERSON> Afonso </PERSON> and asked her to reconsider, the lawyer said. When she refused, he struck a match and set her afire. Miss <PERSON> Afonso </PERSON> spent four months in the hospital. She has had 24 plastic surgery operations and is still in physical therapy. Cheers broke out in court when the sentence was announced. Miss <PERSON> Afonso </PERSON>'s supporters had been worried that <PERSON> Miyashiro </PERSON> would receive a light sentence.
