<HEAD>With AM-Tobacco Exports, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Good News for U.S. Makers in Korean Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Last year's settlement of a trade dispute with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> cleared the way for rapid growth in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sales of cigarettes and leaf tobacco to that thriving Asian market, according to an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report. `` Cigarette manufacturers have clearly won by gaining access to this market, which earned them $ 56.4 million in 1988 and holds promise for even greater annual earnings in the future,'' the department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said. Shipments of `` unmanufactured'' leaf tobacco to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> last year were valued at less than $ 10 million, but that was the most since <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> leaf exports were about $ 40 million in 1981. The $ 56.4 million in cigarette shipments was the most ever. `` <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cigarettes have historically faced stringent trade restrictions in this market,'' the report said. `` Prior to 1986, it was illegal for Korean citizens even to possess foreign cigarettes. This prohibition was lifted in 1986, but <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cigarettes continued to face tought trade restrictions.'' The restrictions led the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cigarette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Export </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> to file a complaint with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade representative on Jan. 1, 1988, charging that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> had violated the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Act. Under the 1974 law, the president can take action, including retaliation, to obtain the removal of any foreign barrier found to be in violation of international agreement or discriminatory. Negotiations produced a `` record of understanding'' signed with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> on May 27, 1988, which eased restrictions on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cigarettes carried out by the <ORGANIZATION> Korean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monopoly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, or KOMOCO. `` Now, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cigarettes are not subject to an import quota,'' the report said. `` Import and domestic taxes have been reduced further; restrictions on advertising and promotion have been reduced; price restrictions have been removed; and cigarettes can be distributed independent of KOMOCO.'' The report added, `` Soon after the agreement was signed, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers began to sign sales agreements with Korean firms, and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cigarette exports began to explode.'' In June 1988, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cigarette shipments to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> increased 30-fold from May. For the entire year, sales totaled 2.4 billion cigarettes, or `` pieces,'' a 670 percent increase from 312 million pieces in 1987. `` In recent years, -LRB- <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> -RRB- cigarette consumption has increased an average of 5 percent annually,'' the report said. `` Increased consumption is attributable to the tremendous growth in personal income and increased consumption by women and students.'' The report also credits KOMOCO with `` an aggressive promotion campaign'' to help boost sales of domestic brands, many of which are using greater amounts of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tobacco leaf.
