<HEAD>Ortega Warns Opposition Against Venezuela-Style Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MGA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> on Wednesday warned critics of his austerity plan not to instigate protests similiar to the unrest in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said the opposition and the `` Yankee empire'' would be the first victims of such an uprising. His speech came the day after the Sandinista government devalued its currency and raised fuel prices for the sixth time this year. It also followed days of front-page stories in Nicaraguan newspapers about violent protests sparked by similar austerity measures. `` If a situation develops here like that of <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, if workers lose their heads and fall into the trap laid by right-wingers, if they lose faith in the revolution, they will rob and raid the establishments of right-wing businessmen,'' <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said. The leftist <PERSON> Sandinistas </PERSON> took power in a 1979 revolution that ended decades of the pro-U.S. <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON> family dictatorship. `` If there is someone trying to sow uncertainty and instability in this country it is the Yankee empire through its spokesmen, -LRB- political -RRB- parties, radio stations, businessmen and newspapers, who clumsily launch that campaign without realizing they would be the first victims of the wave they're trying to stimulate,'' <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said in a speech opening the new semester at a local high school. The president blamed the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other industrialized nations for the economic crises in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>. He said: `` In <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, right-wing groups, politicians and radio stations speak against the economic measures, of the disaster of the Nicaraguan situation,'' <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said. He called it the tolling of `` a bell calling the people to insurrection.'' `` They fail to understand that with these attitudes they are playing with fire, which could end up burning them,'' he said. The riots in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> came after the month-old government of Venezuelan President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> announced a sweeping economic reform package under pressure from internatonal creditors. Although <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> does not face the same pressure from creditors, it is suffering from inflation that hit 20,000 percent last year and <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>'s harsh austerity program resembles <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>'s in many ways The Sandinista program, announced Jan. 30, includes devaluations, cuts in public spending, higher fuel prices, massive layoffs of public employees, restricting credit and slashing capital investment. `` Our country demands effort, sacrifice and productivity from all Nicaraguans,'' <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said Wednesday. He said his economic program is working and that inflation, which hit 97 percent in January alone was `` only 40 or 41 percent'' in February. `` We were expecting a much higher inflation rate, but our measures are showing results, thanks to the efforts of the popular sectors and of responsible businessmen,'' he said. <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s currency, the cordoba, has been devalued six times so far this year. Each time the cost of food and fuel has risen, in part because food has to be trucked into the city from the countryside. The latest devaluation was announced Wednesday, with the official exchange rate now 4,200 cordobas to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar, up from 3,800 cordobas. Fuel prices also rose 1,000 cordobas, with a gallon of gasoline now selling for 8,900 cordobas. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said that fuel prices will rise in the future but not by as much as over the last two months.
