<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Dance Halls,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Hears Arguments in Texas Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Communities should be allowed to protect younger teen-agers by banning anyone over 18 from dance halls that cater to minors, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> was told Wednesday. `` <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> is attacking the juvenile crime problem ... and the influence older people can have on juveniles,'' <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> argued in urging reinstatement of the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> city's age limits for patronizing certain types of dance halls. <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> said local governments do not infringe on people's right to associate with whom they please by imposing such bans. There is `` no constitutional right of association reaching a dance hall,'' he said. Even if there were such a right, <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> added, the <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> ordinance still served the compelling interest of protecting younger teen-agers. But lawyer <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, representing a <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> dance hall owner, said, `` We are asking the court to recognize the right ... to associate even if the purpose is social.'' Although the word `` association'' does not appear in the Constitution, a long series of <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decisions have recognized such a right _ including political and familial associations. But the court has never said that such constitutional protection extends to `` social'' or recreational associations as well. A <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> appeals court recognized such a right in 1987, when it struck down the <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> ordinance that licensed certain dance halls on the condition only teens aged 14 to 18 be admitted as patrons. The ordinance made exceptions for parents, legal guardians and dance hall employees. The city appealed to the nation's highest court; a decision is expected by July. All nine justices asked questions during a lively, hour-long argument session Wednesday. Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> and Justices <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> seemed most impressed by <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>' arguments that, even if 14-year-olds have a right to associate with people older than 18, the city may create a `` safe harbor'' by inhibiting that right in dance halls. At one point, a seemingly dubious <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON> why the dance hall age limits are any less constitutional than statutory rape laws making it a crime to have sex with a minor. The <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> ordinance was challenged successfully in state courts by <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanglin </PERSON>, who operates the Twilight Skating Rink. <PERSON> Stanglin </PERSON> has a `` Class E'' dance hall license, issued to those dance halls catering to minors. He divided the floor of his skating rink so that patrons dance or skate to the same music in full view of one another. People over 18 can be admitted to the skating rink but not to the dance hall. Contending that the ordinance may betray many <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> residents' religiously based bias against dancing, <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON> asked, `` If the problem is older teens corrupting younger teens, why -LRB- are they only barred -RRB- on a dance floor? <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON>, smiling broadly, suggested that the city `` may be moving on roller rinks next _ one evil at a time.'' Justice <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> voiced surprise when the city's lawyer said about 500 dance halls hold licenses. `` Do they do anything else in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>?'' <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> asked. The case is <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Stanglin </PERSON>, 87-1848.
</TEXT>
