<HEAD>Commission Members Defend Base Closing Plans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Members of a presidential panel Wednesday defended their plan to close <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military bases, telling lawmakers the decisions were based on `` military value.'' The commission's co-chairs, former Sen. <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Ribicoff </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>., and former Rep. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ala </LOCATION>., also disputed lawmakers' claims that the decisions were based on faulty data or <PERSON> Ribicoff </PERSON> and <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, testifying before the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Subcommittee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Installations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Facilities </ORGANIZATION>, defended the Dec. 30 report of the <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Base Realignment and Closure. `` We did not just pluck these recommendations out of midair,'' <PERSON> Ribicoff </PERSON> said. Disputing charges that the commission played politics, <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> added, `` Military value is really the touchstone of the process.'' <PERSON> Ribicoff </PERSON> and <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> were supported by a top congressional investigator, who said he has yet to find `` glaring errors'' in the commission's data. <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ribicoff </PERSON> were on Capitol Hill to fend off criticism of their report, which was proposed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in an attempt to solve the politically difficult problem of closing military bases. The base-closing panel, planning to close some 86 installations and partially shut five others, expects its recommendations to save $ 5.6 billion over 20 years. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is scheduled to vote within weeks on the recommendations, which must be either endorsed in whole or refused in whole. Most criticism has come from lawmakers facing base closings in their areas. Some lawmakers say the decisions are based on bad conclusions, and that transfer of some doomed bases' functions will cost as much or more money than they will save. Rep. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>, R-Ky., said he orginally supported the legislation calling for the commission's report But <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> said he has been concerned by calculations that show the closures might not save money. `` If we're not, I'm not going to support it,'' he said. For example, the commission estimates reductions at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dix </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, will save $ 84.5 million a year. A report by the Secretary of <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION>'s office predicts the change will cost $ 190 million in new military construction, and $ 182 million in other `` implementation'' costs. Deputy Assistant <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stone </PERSON>, who provided the cost estimates, defended them. `` There is an old adage that it takes money to make money. For base closures, it takes money to save money,'' <PERSON> Stone </PERSON> told the subcommittee. <PERSON> Ribicoff </PERSON> said the commission made its recommendations `` after serious consideration.'' Criticism was expected, he said. `` Change is not always welcomed. In fact, it can be threatening.'' `` We were heartened by the substantial evidence showing that communities do recover from the temporary dislocations that result from a base closing. Many end up much better off,'' <PERSON> Ribicoff </PERSON> said. Rep. <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON>, D-Colo., the subcommittee chairwoman, asked <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> about speculation some of the decisions may have been motivated by politics `` We were not only bipartisan. We were non-partisan,'' <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> replied. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Conahan </PERSON>, a ranking official of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, said his agency has yet to find fault with the commission's overall recommendations `` We have not found any glaring errors,'' said <PERSON> Conahan </PERSON>, adding the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>'s review will continue.
</TEXT>
