<FIRST>r i AM-Chile-Pinochet     03-01 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile-Pinochet,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Formed To Promote Pinochet's Re-Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVA VERGARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Politicians and right-wing activists have formed an organization promoting the re-election of military President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, who was lost a referendum last year on whether he should remain in office. <PERSON> Claudio </PERSON> <PERSON> Morales </PERSON>, a former councilman in <LOCATION> Valparaiso </LOCATION>, said the group is made up of social leaders, independent politicians and members of various right-wing parties who are `` convinced that the best candidate we may have'' is <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>. The group was organized Tuesday night in <LOCATION> Valparaiso </LOCATION>, 75 miles north west of <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>. Several right-wing politicians and parties have also indicated they would like <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> to run, but the <ORGANIZATION> Valparaiso </ORGANIZATION> group is the first one especially organized to promote his candidacy. The 1980 constitution bars Pinochet from seeking re-election, but in recent weeks the growing divisions among right-wing forces prompted calls to find a way for him to run in the Dec. 14 election. The election was made mandatory by an Oct. 5 referendum, in which voters overwhelmingly rejected a military proposal to extend <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s term until 1997. Supporters of a Pinochet candidacy say the constitution may be changed to allow him to run, and the general's wife, <PERSON> Lucia </PERSON> <PERSON> Hiriart </PERSON>, publicly supported such a constitutional amendment. Others say the constitutional restriction on re-election does not apply to the 73-year-old president and army commander because he was not elected in the first place. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> seized power in a bloody 1973 coup. The government announced last week that it is considering a plebiscite as early as June to approve unspecified constitutional changes. There has been no indication, however, that the changes would include one to allow <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> to run in December. <PERSON> Pablo </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>, one of two right-wing politicians who have formally announced their presidential candidacies, says he would only withdraw from the race if <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> can run. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> has admitted he can not be a candidate under the present constitutional terms. He told his supporters, however, that he will tell them who to support in the presidential race.
</TEXT>
