<FIRST>r w AM-StealthCruise 580   03-01 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stealth Cruise, 580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Picture Released of Another Secret Weapon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, continuing a selective relaxation of the security shrouding its newest weapons, released a photograph Wednesday providing a limited view of its new stealth cruise missile. The black-and-white photo shows a B-52 bomber flying with four of the new missiles tucked under each wing. The picture shows the missile has flattened sides instead of a perfectly rounded shape; that the engine air inlet is cut into the top of the missile instead of sticking up on a pylon from the fuselage, and the wings and tail fins are folded up against the missile body until it is fired. But the angle from which the photograph was taken does not allow any other details of the weapon's design to be discerned, and the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday it is not prepared to say more. Production schedules, budget figures and tentative dates for fielding all remain classified, said Lt. Col. <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Oborn </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. The release of the photo of the stealth cruise, known formally as the Advanced Cruise Missile, or AGM-129A, is the third such move in 10 months. Last April, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> released an artist's sketch that revealed the `` flying wing'' design of the new B-2 stealth bomber. Then last November, the service released a photograph _ albeit a poor one _ of the super-secret F-117A stealth jet fighter. Wednesday's release appeared to be tied in part to an upcoming test of the new missile over <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> announced Feb. 1 that <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> had agreed to let the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> test the Advanced Cruise Missile in arctic conditions. According to <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> officials, who asked not to be named, the first such test was scheduled Wednesday but had to be postponed due to weather conditions. The standard cruise missile is a jet-powered flying bomb that looks like a torpedo with stubby wings and a tail fin. The missile carries a sophisticated guidance system that allows it to hug the ground to escape detection. The stealth version of the cruise missile is supposed to be even more impervious to detection, while also offering greater range. The term stealth is applied to a variety of techniques used to foil radar. By employing unusual aircraft designs and new types of manufacturing materials, a plane or missile can absorb or deflect radar signals without bouncing them back to an enemy tracking system. Although most of the publicity about stealth technology has centered on the B-2 bomber, the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has been under contract since 1983 to develop and build a stealth version of the standard cruise missile. The <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> received a separate contract in 1987 to become a second producer of the missile. Congressional officials disclosed almost two years ago, in April 1987, the stealth missile program was suffering from serious production quality problems and cost overruns. Although denied by the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> has quoted sources as saying the program is three years behind schedule and will cost $ 7 billion instead of $ 5 billion. Acting Air Force Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON>, in a written statement released Wednesday with the picture, said the stealth cruise missile `` will improve the long-term effectiveness of the -LRB- bomber -RRB- leg of the -LRB- nuclear -RRB- triad.'' `` Incorporation of advances in propulsion and guidance technology, along with low-observable -LRB- stealth -RRB- design features, results in a system with improvements in range, accuracy and flexibility.''
</TEXT>
