<HEAD>General Assembly Approves Namibia Independence Financing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday approved $ 416 million for the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping mission that will oversee <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s passage to freedom after 74 years of South African rule. `` The show is on the road,'' declared <PERSON> Marrack </PERSON> <PERSON> Goulding </PERSON>, the ndersecretary-general in charge of all <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping operations. The one-year <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> plan for <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s independence begins April 1. The 159-member assembly adopted by consensus a funding resolution for a <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> force that will consist of 4,650 peacekeepers, 500 police, and about 2,200 civilian staff and election monitors. The mission will oversee elections for a constituent assembly in November that will organize a black majority-ruled government _ creating the world's newest independent nation and in the process settling the last major colonial problem in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials confirmed publicly that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> will receive a generous share of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> funds as the force makes purchases in the region, including $ 10.2 million in gasoline and aviation fuel. Some black African nations, led by <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, fought to make the world body heed its own calls for trade embargoes on South African products. `` We do n't have any oil distribution in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, so we have to use the oil that is there,'' said <PERSON> Martti </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahtisaari </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> undersecretary-general in charge of the civilian phase of the <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> transition plan. `` For the military component, the maximum tasks come in the first few weeks of the transition period,'' said <PERSON> Goulding </PERSON>. He said the military `` has to ensure that the South African forces are confined to barracks; ... to start supervising the withdrawal of South African forces down to 1,500; ... to start the process of dismantling the command structures and taking into custody the arms of the various local forces that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has set up in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>.'' White-dominated <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has ruled <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> since it captured the colony from <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> during World War I. In December, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> signed accords with <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> agreeing to free <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> if 50,000 Cuban troops stationed in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> are sent home by mid-1991. Marxist <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> adjoins <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> is one of the world's most sparsely populated areas, with an estimated 1.3 million people occupying territory as large as <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> combined. The Ovambo people inhabit the relatively fertile northern region and make up about half the population. There are 75,000 white residents. The economy is dominated by mining, with diamonds, uranium and copper the principal minerals.
