<FIRST>r w AM-Aflatoxin     03-01 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aflatoxin,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeutter Says Amount of Aflatoxin in Food Supply Unlikely to Hurt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said Wednesday that cancer-causing aflatoxin is unlikely to get into the food supply in amounts great enough to hurt anyone. `` Anytime we have a drought, we are going to see more aflatoxin problems,'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Appropriations subcommittee on rural development, agriculture and related agencies. `` That does n't mean we're going to have more in the food supply ... or any that slips in is going to hurt anyone. <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> criticized a recent article in The Wall Street Journal that said aflatoxin-tainted corn is moving through the nation's food chain because of inadequate sampling and unreliable testing. He said the article implied that people are being cavalier about the existence of the toxin. `` Everyone is going to do their best to minimize the risk of letting aflatoxin into the food supply,'' he said. `` Nobody in the food chain wants it.'' Last year's heat and drought were ideal for development of the fungus that produces aflatoxin, which researchers have linked to the development of liver cancer in laboratory rats. The level of aflatoxin allowed in corn is 20 parts per billion. On Tuesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said about 6 percent _ 95 samples out of 1,650 _ of the field corn tested in recent months had higher levels. That corn can not be used for human consumption, but can be diverted to feed non-dairy cattle, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> tested about 263 samples of corn flour and corn meal and found 2 percent, or six samples, to have more than 20 parts of aflatoxin per billion. <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> policy requires that these products be removed from the market. In answer to another question from the subcommittee, <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said he considers the chance of international trade reform to be better than it has been in a decade. He said that there are some hurdles the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> must work out before talks in the <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> Round resume next month in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. `` I'm cautiously optimistic we'll get that worked out between now and April,'' he told the committee. `` What happens in the <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> Round will determine what we should have in farm legislation,'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said. He said he does n't anticipate any significant changes from the 1985 farm bill that is due to expire in 1990. He said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> could extend the 1985 law until the <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> talks are complete, or pass a new bill and amend it as necessary after the negotiations.
</TEXT>
