<HEAD>Peru Rekindles Austerity Plan As Inflation Continues Surge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government Wednesday installed the second in a series of four monthly austerity measures aimed at reducing record inflation by cutting subsidies on basic foods and transportation. Consumer prices rose 42.5 percent in February, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> reported Wednesday, despite the austerity plan launched Feb. 1. The measures Wednesday included a devaluation of 23.3 percent, bringing the value of the official Peruvian currency, the inti, from 920 to 1,200 to the dollar. In addition, the prices of products subsidized by the government were increased. Consumer prices for basic foods, such as wheat, cooking oil and milk, were increased between 33 percent and 50 percent, and gasoline was increased 28 percent, according to the government. The minimum monthly wage rose from 42,000 intis to 55,000, equivalent to $ 46 at the official rate, and salaries for all state employees and non-unionized private workers rose a similar percentage. Analysts say <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s working class and poor have been hit hardest by rocketing inflation, which ran a record 1,722 percent last year as a result of subsidy-fueled deficit spending under President <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, and a dramatic shrinkage of the economy last year estimated at 8.4 percent. <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>'s subsidy-cutting plan that raised prices on gasoline prices and bus tickets this week set off widespread rioting that left at least 100 dead. <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>'s administration has acknowledged inflation will continue to grow in the short term due to the price and wage increases but eventually decline with a decrease in government spending for subsidies. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said inflation so far this year has reached 109.9 percent. Consumer prices rose 47.3 percent in January. Prior to the program of austerity installments, which concludes in May, the government over the past year has been steadily cutting back on the types of products its subsidizes. Now most imported products now must be purchased at the floating free market exchange rate, which was 1,300 intis to the dollar and unchanged by Wednesday's measures.
