estment, reaping for the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> more than it costs. However, the idea has generated fierce opposition in the Democratic-controlled <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, where leaders have sought to portray it as a new tax break for the rich. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Wednesday insisted the tax break will increase revenues $ 4.8 billion annually. Private economists are divided on whether lowering capital gains taxes would increase or decrease revenues. While in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> cautioned the South Korean National Assembly to do more in opening markets and avoiding protectionism. He made reference to that in Wednesday's address, claiming he had stressed to Asian trading partners `` at every stop ... the need for keeping these markets open.''
