<HEAD>Crew Member Recalls Horror and Heroism Of Flight 811</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Plane Emergency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Heroism by both passengers and crew saved countless lives during the `` unbelievable horror'' when a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jet ripped open over the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>, spilling nine passengers to their deaths, a crew member said. `` I felt like <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> in the Wizard of Oz when her house gets picked up and everything gets blown away,'' purser <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Shanahan </PERSON> said in an interview in Wednesday's editions of the Honolulu Star-Bulletin. `` We had some flight attendants who had to hang on to the first class stairwell when it actually happened. And, by golly, it held. It helped to protect the lives of at least three people that I know of,'' said <PERSON> Shanahan </PERSON>, 42, who has worked for <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> for 21 years. Federal investigators suspect the forward cargo door on the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 jet, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>'s Flight 811 bound for <LOCATION> Auckland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, popped open during the flight Friday, tearing a 10-by-20-foot hole in the plane's fuselage. The plane carried 354 people, including 18 crew members. `` I instantly knew that we had a hole in the airplane,'' said <PERSON> Shanahan </PERSON>. She said her first reaction was to find oxygen to keep from passing out. Because of the damage, the plane's emergency oxygen system did not activate, investigators said. <PERSON> Shanahan </PERSON> said she searched desperately for an oxygen bottle, finally finding one and taking `` a few real strong inhalations'' to regain her strength. `` Then I stopped and I collected my thoughts for just a second. I realized that the plane was flying. It was not in an uncontrolled rapid descent.'' Capt. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cronin </PERSON> flew the crippled jet 100 miles on two of four engines, landing safely at <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> International Airport 25 minutes later. Twenty-seven people were injured, with only two still hospitalized Wednesday. <PERSON> Shanahan </PERSON> said it was `` truly a miracle that there were not more injuries to people from things flying around in the cabin. There were ice buckets, racks of glasses, cartons of juice and bins of things around.'' The decompression of the plane took only a few seconds, and during that time `` anything that was n't nailed down moved,'' she said. <PERSON> Shanahan </PERSON> said she inched her way forward and saw `` an incredible amount of structural damage'' and that two or three crew members were helping passengers. `` They were reassuring people. I could see them physically touching arms. I do n't know what they were saying because the noise was so incredible you could n't hear yourself think,'' <PERSON> Sanahan </PERSON> said. She started walking back through the cabin, telling passengers to put on life vests and inflate one chamber. She said she tried using the public address system but it was too noisy for it to be heard, so she found a megaphone. <PERSON> Shanahan </PERSON> said she instructed the passengers to tighten their seat belts, grab their ankles and `` stay down until you know we're back on earth and we've stopped.'' She said she found three young men and assigned them to help with the evacuation upon landing, instructing them on how to open the emergency exit and deploy the inflatable slide, making them repeat the instructions back to her. She said she told them, `` This is a critical job. They will pile up at the bottom of the slide. They will get badly injured. It is vital that you stay there.'' `` And they did. God bless them. They did,'' <PERSON> Shanahan </PERSON> said. When the captain announced that the plane was two minutes from the end of the runway, `` people kept unfastening their seat belts and standing up to look out the windows,'' she said. `` I'm sure that they wanted the reassurance. They wanted to see those <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> city lights. `` That's why I'm hoarse. I screamed for two minutes: ` Grab your ankles. Stay down, stay down, stay down,''' <PERSON> Shanahan </PERSON> said. `` It was the best landing. It was just perfect. It was smooth. It was wonderful,'' she said. Once the plane stopped, <PERSON> Shanhan </PERSON> said she whipped open the door and began ordering the passengers to form double lines and leap onto the slide. <PERSON> Shanahan </PERSON> said she did n't know until she was off the plane that passengers had been lost. It was only then that she saw the size of the hole.
