<HEAD>New South African Law Will Allow Some Integrated Neighborhoods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After 39 years of mandatory residential segregation, a new law took effect Wednesday that will allow a few carefully selected multiracial neighborhoods. In a separate development, the government announced it has commuted the death sentences of 16 prisoners, including an activist who was the subject of clemency appeals from the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. The government also agreed to release 50 detainees held without charge, anti-apartheid church leaders said Wednesday following a meeting with the Minister of Law and Order <PERSON> Adriaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON>. The churchmen said that will bring to 279 the number of releases <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> has authorized in the past two weeks. The government has hailed the legalization of integrated neighborhoods as a milestone, but an opposition newspaper called it a `` half-baked'' plan that will create a few overcrowded multiracial areas while segregation prevails elsewhere. Most observers expect that multiracial neighborhoods will be limited to a handful of new housing developments and to inner-city neighborhoods that already have become integrated despite segregation laws. Decisions on establishing integrated neighborhoods will be made by an eight-member board dominated by government supporters. One member is black. The board is supposed to take community sentiment into consideration, and the government has made clear that no white neighborhoods will be integrated if there is significant opposition. `` This act does not change the present living and residential patterns of our communities,'' Acting President <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Heunis </PERSON> said last week. `` But it gives those people who wish to associate freely with one another the democratic choice to do so.'' Heunis is filling in for President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>, who is recuperating from a stroke. The Star, a liberal <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> newspaper with the country's largest daily circulation, acknowledged that the act will allow people of different races to live together legally for the first time since residential segregation was mandated by the Group Areas Act in 1950 `` Yet it does this in such a half-baked and limited way that it is likely to aggravate, not alleviate, slum conditions,'' said The Star in an editorial Tuesday. It predicted that a handful of `` free settlement'' areas will rapidly become overcrowded, leading to problems that the government will blame on integration. The 16 prisoners who had their death sentences commuted included one man of mixed-race and 15 blacks, among them <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Setlaba </PERSON>, convicted of committing murder during a 1985 black consumer boycott. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> gave no explanation for the action, merely listing the prisoners granted clemency. In each case, the death sentence was commuted to a prison term, ranging from 10 years to life. <PERSON> Setlaba </PERSON>'s planned execution was stayed by Justice Minister <PERSON> Kobie </PERSON> <PERSON> Coetsee </PERSON> in November, hours before he was to be hanged. The stay followed appeals for clemency by human rights groups in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and by the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, which depicted <PERSON> Setlaba </PERSON> as an anti-apartheid activist caught up in political unrest. Details of the other reprieved prisoners' cases were not disclosed. The release of 50 prisoners held without charge came in response to a series of hunger strikes by up to 400 inmates in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> `` gave the delegation his assurance that ... the process of releasing detainees would continue,'' church leaders said in a statement.
