<SECOND>AM-Trade Report,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Says Industrial Nations Must Pursue Non-Inflationary
Growth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Industrial nations must pursue non-inflationary economic growth to stimulate world trade and provide growing markets for their own exports and those of less-developed countries, the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration said Wednesday in a report to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The report from the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the Office of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its major trading partners were committed to making the changes needed to reduce imbalances in world trade. <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, both countries with large trade surpluses, need to take steps to ensure open and growing domestic markets, the report said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, meanwhile, `` is committed to substantial federal budget deficit reductions, improving its international competitiveness, and bolstering its savings rate,'' it said. The report noted that most economies are structured in ways that can hinder international efforts to coordinate monetary, fiscal and exchange rate policies to promote world trade. It said the industrial nations agreed at the <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> economic summit last year to pursue specific reforms that would reduce such barriers through steps such as cutting subsidies that impede the international flow of resources, reforming tax systems that discourage innovation, and reducing burdensome regulations. Such a course `` is well suited to producing medium-term solutions to what are, after all, medium-term problems,'' the report said. The report projected that without policy changes, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade surplus in goods and services would drop `` significantly'' in the next two years from about $ 80 billion this year, while <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, with export growth rebounding, would see its overall surplus largely unchanged. <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s ballooning of its trade deficit in 1988 is unlikely to be reversed, and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> should collectively have about the same deficit in 1990 that they did in 1988, it said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, meanwhile, expects to see increases in exports exceed growth in imports, although rising payments on the national debt will hold back the overall reductions in the trade deficit. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit in 1988 posted its first improvement since 1980, narrowing to $ 137.34 billion from an all-time high of $ 170.32 billion in 1987. The report said less-developed countries also must move to promote world trade. These countries, especially those that are heavily in debt, must adopt policies that support domestic growth, reduce inflation, and encourage support from banks and international financial institutions, it said. The trade projection report was required under the Omnibus Trade Act of 1988.
