 Thousands of people demonstrating against ethnic Albanians massed outside <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday while a senior official inside told lawmakers ethnic violence threatens to tear <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> apart. <PERSON> Lazar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mojsov </PERSON>, a member of the ruling 12-man state presidency, also charged that an illegal group of ethnic Albanians has detailed plans to disrupt southern <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> province, the state-run news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The integrity of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> is jeopardized to the extreme degree,'' <PERSON> Mojsov </PERSON> said in comments carried on <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> radio. The government indefinitely extended a ban on all public gatherings in <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> said, following more than a week of widespread unrest in the province. Outside Parliament, about 4,000 members of the <LOCATION> Serb </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Montenegrin </LOCATION> minority from <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> blocked streets and chanted songs to protest alleged persecution in the province by Albanians, who make up 90 percent of <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>'s estimated 2 million people. <PERSON> Mojsov </PERSON> told the assembly 50,000 Slavs emigrated from <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> since 1981 because of harassment. The flag-carrying protesters were joined by at least 10,000 <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> sympathizers. On Tuesday, a <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> rally led by <ORGANIZATION> Serbian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> boss <PERSON> Slobodan </PERSON> <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> drew an estimated 500,000 people. Taxi drivers, carrying large portraits of <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> on their cars, provided free transportation for the elderly. The mainly Christian Serbs believe the predominantly Moslem Al