<HEAD>Search For DEA Agent Killer Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A unarmed federal drug agent shot to death in an undercover operation was wearing a radio transmitter and had five backup men, but they lost contact as he drove off with the man suspected of killing him, officials said Wednesday. The murder of undercover Special Agent <PERSON> Everette </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatcher </PERSON> on Tuesday was the first killing of a <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> officer in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> area since 1972, said <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Strang </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and police issued an all-points bulletin for Constible `` Gus'' <PERSON> Farace </PERSON>, 28, of <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Farace </PERSON> was released from the <ORGANIZATION> Elmira </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Correction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Facility </ORGANIZATION> in June 1988 after serving eight years for the 1979 kidnapping and murder of a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> teen-ager, said police sources who spoke on the condition of anonymity. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Maloney </PERSON> said he would seek the death penalty under the new federal drug bill when <PERSON> Hatcher </PERSON>'s killer is caught. Investigators do not believe <PERSON> Hatcher </PERSON>'s `` cover was blown or that he was known to be a law enforcement officer,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Y. </PERSON> <PERSON> Doran </PERSON>, special agent in charge of the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>'s Criminal Division. `` This was not a ` buy and bust' situation. There were no drugs present. There was no money present,'' <PERSON> Doran </PERSON> said. `` The killing was out of cold-bloodedness as far as we can determine.'' He said <PERSON> Hatcher </PERSON>'s wire had not been disturbed. <PERSON> Hatcher </PERSON> was found slumped over the wheel of an unmarked car on a dead-end street on <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> at 10:15 p.m. Tuesday, shot four times in the head and upper body, apparently from outside the car, authorities said. Shortly after 9 p.m., <PERSON> Hatcher </PERSON> notified his back-up team that he and <PERSON> Farace </PERSON> were going to drive their cars to a diner, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stutman </PERSON>, special agent in charge of the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> bureau. `` Shortly after that they -LRB- the agents -RRB- lost contact with the transmitter,'' <PERSON> Stutman </PERSON> said. He said they had dropped back so as not to be spotted and there was considerable traffic. The back-up team lost sight of <PERSON> Hatcher </PERSON> and began looking for the agent, without success, at various diners on the boulevard until returning to the original meeting area and finding <PERSON> Hatcher </PERSON>'s car. <PERSON> Hatcher </PERSON>, 46, had worked at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> office since joining the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> in 1972. At the time of his death, the agent was part of a joint DEA-FBI Task Force engaged in a long-term drug investigation, officials said. Two other <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> agents have been shot and wounded in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> in the last six months, but none has been killed in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> area since October 12, 1972, when Special Agent <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Tummillo </PERSON> was shot in a midtown hotel. Tummillo's partner, Supervisory Agent <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Devine </PERSON>, died Sept. 25, 1982, of wounds he suffered during the 1972 shooting, <PERSON> Strang </PERSON> said.
