<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It is n't easy adopting smoking restrictions in the heart of tobacco country, as the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louisville </ORGANIZATION> discovered when it tried to put a stringent smoking policy into effect last fall. But it is possible, and new regulations went into effect Wednesday that try to give campus smokers and non-smokers equal rights to puff and not be puffed upon. `` I hope that this is an issue that we can put behind us,'' said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, a university official who met twice with the <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> to iron out details that did n't set well with lawmakers representing <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> burley producers. `` It's a hard issue for anybody who lives in a tobacco state,'' said <PERSON> Justine </PERSON> <PERSON> Speer </PERSON>, dean of the university's School of Nursing. The revised regulations, approved by <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Swain </PERSON> last month, did away with an especially controversial provision in the original regulations that would have favored non-smokers in disputes with smokers. After the first draft drew fire last November, some lawmakers threatened to cut the university's budget. But in December, the university agreed to rewrite portions of the policy to make sure smokers and non-smokers would be treated evenhandedly. Under the revision, department heads will discuss and settle conflicts over smoking with employees and their supervisors. `` The university feels that it's been responsive to the concerns of many of the legislators in those two meetings, and my hope is that it will be received as such,'' <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> said. The new policy bans smoking in classrooms and elevators, as did the early proposal, but calls for more modest restrictions in hallways, lounges and other public areas, where smoking will be allowed in designated areas. <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> said the rules would be introduced gradually as signs are printed and posted designating the smoking and non-smoking areas. Ms. <PERSON> Speer </PERSON> said nursing students and faculty worked out their own smoking policy several months ago, before the issue surfaced campus-wide. Nursing faculty members _ none of whom smoke _ and students voted not to smoke in halls outside classrooms, Ms. <PERSON> Speer </PERSON> said. Smoking is also prohibited inside classrooms. The nursing students' lounge is divided for smokers and non-smokers, and staff members have separate lounges, she said. Although the school is sensitive to the issues of tobacco farmers, it also wants to provide a `` healthful environment'' to non-smokers, she said. `` There are very few people in our area who smoke anymore,'' she said. `` It's just like people have learned.''
