graf `Last month's...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> met at the border on Thursday and resumed talks on a possible meeting between their prime ministers. Delegates from the two sides exchanged greetings at the <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION> truce site and chatted for about 10 minutes before beginning formal deliberations. Last month's talks bogged down after <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> demanded a halt to joint U.S.-South Korean military exercises. The <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION> government repeated that demand Wednesday. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has said the talks can not progress unless the `` Team Spirit'' exercises, an annual event since 1976, are canceled. `` The South Koran authorities should, first of all, have a corrrect fundamental stand and attitude toward the dialogue and take a determined stand of discontinuing the ` Team Spirit' joint military exercises at once,'' <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s official <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said in a report monitored in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. Another factor that may affect the dialogue would be <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>'s blocking of dissidents from meeting with North Korean officials on national unification Wednesday South Korean dissidents, defying a government ban, scheduled the meeting at the truce village of <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION>, but police overpowered and arrested 28 dissidents heading to the site. Before the Feb. 8 meeting at the border village of <LOCATION> Panmunjom </LOCATION>, hopes were high the countries would be able to agree on terms for the prime ministers' meeting. It would be the highest-ranking meeting ever between communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and capitalist <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. Despite the North Korean demand, military officials of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> have made it clear they will not halt this year's exercises. <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> observers believe the hardened <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> stand also is expected to affect a scheduled meeting March 9 between sports officials of the two nations to form a single delegation to the 1990 Asian Games in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. It's also believed <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> may be displeased with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s recent visit to <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> and last week's defection to <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> of two North Korean students. While in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> reaffirmed <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s security commitment to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would continue its military presence. About 42,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops are stationed in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> under a mutual defense treaty.
