<HEAD>Army Chief Says Beating Policy Open to Soldiers' Judgment</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with new developments, move up
background on trial. Pick up 9th pvs, ``Earlier testimony...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KIRYAT MALACHI, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s army chief of staff on Wednesday defended the policy of beating Palestinian rioters but acknowledged that in many cases the individual soldier decides how much force to use. Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Shomron </PERSON> made the comments as he testified in the trial of four soldiers charged with manslaughter in the beating death of a 42-year-old Arab refugee last August. It was the army chief's most comprehensive explanation to date of a policy that prompted harsh foreign criticism after pictures of soldiers clubbing Palestinians were seen on worldwide television. He said beating as punishment was prohibited and force should not be used once a riot is over. `` Deterrence is not the goal, overcoming violence is,'' <PERSON> Shomron </PERSON> said, `` but when someone stops resisting, that's a matter of opinion.'' In another development Wednesday, soldiers arrested two Palestinians who tried to stab and kidnap a Jewish settler in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, the army reported. An army spokeswoman said a car `` approached in a suspicious manner'' when a settler left his vehicle, then two men jumped out and one tried to stab the settler while the other pushed him into the car. The settler escaped and alerted soldiers, who closed the area and erected roadblocks, the spokeswoman said. The Palestinians abandoned their vehicle and fled on foot. Also Wednesday, anonymous telephone callers to a news agency and to an Arab lawyer demanded the release of all Palestinian prisoners held by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> in exchange for the release of an Israeli paratrooper. <PERSON> Avi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sassportas </PERSON>, 21, has been missing since Feb. 16, when he disappeared on his way home to <LOCATION> Ashdod </LOCATION>, south of <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Shomron </PERSON>, testifying before a three-judge military court, said orders issued to commanders on Feb. 23, 1988 regarding beatings outlined proper procedures. The army has contended that beatings are necessary to subdue riots which have raged in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> since the Palestinian uprising broke out Dec. 8, 1987. `` Dispersing a violent demonstration must be done with force,'' <PERSON> Shomron </PERSON> said. `` Let us be clear these are not demonstrations over food subsidies, but violent demonstrations that endanger the lives of our soldiers.'' `` You can beat someone to prevent an incident, disperse a violent demonstration or to stop someone who is resisting an arrest,'' he said. The three privates and a first sergeant are charged in the beating death Aug. 22 of <PERSON> Hani </PERSON> <PERSON> Shami </PERSON>, 42, at the <LOCATION> Jabaliya </LOCATION> refugee camp in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. They face maximum prison terms of 20 years if convicted. Earlier testimony said a stone-thrower the soldiers were pursuing ran into <PERSON> Shami </PERSON>'s house and, when <PERSON> Shami </PERSON> tried to keep them out, the soldiers broke the door down, threw him to the ground, beat him with a broom and kicked him. An autopsy determined he died of a punctured lung, and at least 12 of his ribs were broken. The courtroom's 50 seats were full Wednesday and relatives of the defendants, who served in the elite <ORGANIZATION> Givati </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brigade </ORGANIZATION>, were seated behind them. Final statements in the case are expected next week. Defense lawyer <PERSON> Uziel </PERSON> <PERSON> Atzmon </PERSON> repeatedly asked <PERSON> Shomron </PERSON> precisely when beatings were legal and when they were not. `` You are asking me about gray areas and asking for clear answers,'' said <PERSON> Shomron </PERSON>, who spent 2 -LCB- hours on the stand. `` Soldiers are told to use their own judgment _ how severe the situation is and how much force is necessary. `` It is possible that these events will be seen as a deviation. It shows how difficult the situation is.'' `` I am responsible for the orders given but not for the actions of every soldier,'' he testified. `` I expect the soldiers will fulfill their legal orders. `` If officers give orders to troops that are not legal, it is no doubt proper to investigate these orders.'' At least 387 Palestinians have been killed in the uprising, most shot to death in confrontations with soldiers, and 17 Israelis have been killed. Thousands of Palestinians have been wounded or beaten. Six Palestinians were reported wounded by <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers Wednesday, three in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Nablus </LOCATION> and three at the Khan Yunis refugee camp in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. Those wounded at the camp included an 8-year-old boy shot in the chest, <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> doctors said.
