<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, fresh from his <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> primary triumph over Mayor <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, rallied his forces Wednesday for a three-way general election battle against a black alderman and a Republican nominee still to be crowned. <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, son of the late, six-term political boss, Mayor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, drew overwhelming white support Tuesday and benefited from low voter turnout, especially among blacks, to oust <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, a black former alderman. The victory made <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> first among the biggest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cities to have a black incumbent mayor defeated by a white in an election. <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, a three-term <LOCATION> Cook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> state's attorney, now faces a third-party challenge in the April 4 general election from <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, a popular black alderman who has the support of <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, and who also hit the campaign trail Wednesday. The outcome of the Republican primary, normally barely noticed in this heavily Democratic city, remained in doubt Wednesday. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Vrdolyak </PERSON>, a white former Democratic alderman and <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> foe who launched a write-in candidacy only a week ago, claimed a victory that if upheld could cut into <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>'s core constituency. With five weeks of campaigning ahead, <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> was up at dawn to greet commuters and tape a television appearance. `` I think my father's looking down upon me, on a beautiful, warm day in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> ... very proud of me, and most importantly, proud of the type of campaign that I ran in the last three months _ reaching out to every community,'' <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> said on `` CBS This Morning.'' At a commuter rail station, <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> pledged to avoid racial divisiveness in the campaign's next phase: `` I'm going to be vying for votes of everybody throughout this city and this is a city made up of the black community, the white commmunity, the <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION>, the Hispanic community.'' He predicted `` a good clean election.'' <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> said his political career was n't over but suggested he would not back <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> or <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>. `` My general sense is that I will not endorse anyone,'' he said. `` I am thinking it through and I've got a lot of people to talk to before I decide.'' With 2,843 of 2,911 precincts, or 98 percent, reporting, <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> had 481,370 votes, or 56 percent, to 367,919 votes, or 43 percent, for <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>. Three other candidates shared the remaining Democratic votes, while the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> race between <PERSON> Vrdolyak </PERSON> and Dr. <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Sohn </PERSON> was considered too close to call Wednesday. <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, 45, previously <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>'s chief black rival, maintained a low profile during the primary campaign. But he began campaigning Wednesday at 6:45 a.m., shaking hands with voters at an elevated train station and promising to crush the `` Daley machine.'' <PERSON> Vrdolyak </PERSON>, 51, had no formal appearances scheduled Wednesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commissioners </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday's official canvass would determine the Republican outcome With 96 percent of 2,911 percincts reporting, unofficial results gave <PERSON> Vrdolyak </PERSON> 10,711 votes, or 45 percent, to 10,234 votes, or 43 percent for <PERSON> Sohn </PERSON>. Two other candidates each had 5 percent. The elections board estimated that 64.5 percent of the city's nearly 1.55 million voters went to the polls Tuesday <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>'s primary triumph gave him an advantage in the general election, a contest Democrats have won without fail since 1931. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> congratulated <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> and offered his full support to the party nominee. In doing so, the first black chairman of a national political party broke with <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, whom he had served as convention manager last summer. `` Tough contests and hard-fought politics are nothing new to Democrats and certainly not to Democrats in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said in a statement. `` The emphasis for all Democrats now must be on unity and conciliation.'' <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> proved his effectiveness as a political organizer, winning broad-based support among white ethnics and Hispanics in the primary. But he must work to gain support in the black community, analysts said. If <PERSON> Vrdolyak </PERSON>, a slick campaigner and nemesis of the late Mayor <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>, is declared the winner over <PERSON> Sohn </PERSON>, observers said the white vote in the general election could be split between <PERSON> Vrdolyak </PERSON> and <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, giving <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> the edge. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> became the city's first black mayor after winning the 1983 Democratic primary, in which the younger <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> and incumbent <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> split the white vote. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> gained support from liberal whites and Hispanics to repeat in 1987, becoming the first mayor since the elder <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> to win re-election. But he died in office without having annointed a successor, touching off a war between <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> that caused a deep rift in the black community.
