<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>New Riots in Caracas; 200 Reported Killed in Caracas in Three Days</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with higher deaths, injury tolls, latest
government measures; no pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CAR3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY CAPLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Riots broke out Wednesday in the western slums despite martial law, and a newspaper said more than 200 people were killed in the <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> area alone in three days of violence over price increases. At least nine people were reported killed on Wednesday. The newspaper <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nacional </ORGANIZATION> said in its early Thursday edition that more than 1,000 people were injured and 2,000 were arrested in <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> since riots _ triggered by a wide-ranging government austerity program _ began on Monday. The newspaper listed the names of 159 persons whose bodies were in the <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> morgue, which it said was `` congested with corpses.'' It said there was a `` high number of corpses in other <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> morgues.'' The independent newspaper quoted unidentified police sources and gave no details. Government ministers maintained that calm had been largely restored to <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, but they censored international TV broadcasts from <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION>. The army began to airlift food from the interior of the country to supply <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> residents running low on supplies as a result of rioting and looting. Sporadic gunfire could be heard just blocks from the <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> office as a 6 p.m. curfew fell over the city. <PERSON> Nicole </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendoza </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> resident, said soldiers were piling people into jeeps and taking them away outside her building to enforce the curfew, which was announced Tuesday night. Fighting continued in <LOCATION> Petare </LOCATION>, a shantytown east of the capital, and local hospitals were full of injured, a parish priest said. Officials refused comment on numbers of dead or injured. A witness reported that an army unit shot mobs sacking a food store in <LOCATION> Petare </LOCATION> after loudspeaker appeals failed to stop the looting, a doctor who lives in <LOCATION> Palo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Verde </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Petare </LOCATION>, told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. The doctor said four people were shot to death. There was no independent confirmation. The government called on workers to return to their workplaces on Thursday, saying violence was `` practically controlled.'' Most businesses were closed on Wednesday. Before the curfew, Venezuelans jammed the few remaining open food stores, which were guarded by soldiers. Police battled with snipers in <LOCATION> Nueva </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tacagua </LOCATION>, a shantytown in the hills west of <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION>, and broke up mobs of looters in <LOCATION> Catia </LOCATION>, also a slum to the west of <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION>, according to <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rumbo </ORGANIZATION>, a local station. An AP photographer said he saw at least four bodies of people who had been shot Wednesday in <LOCATION> Catia </LOCATION>. In the <LOCATION> Chapellin </LOCATION> neighborhood of <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION>, an elderly woman died in her apartment from a wild bullet fired during gunbattles between army units and residents of a nearby slum, said eyewitnesses. Radio reporters said delinquents were trying to break into homes in <LOCATION> Guarenas </LOCATION>, about 30 miles west of <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION>, while homeowners were defending themselves with gunfire. Interior Minister <PERSON> Alejandro </PERSON> <PERSON> Izaguirre </PERSON> acknowledged there had been fighting in the capital but said `` calm has been restored to the rest of the country.'' President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> declared martial law late Tuesday, saying the `` incredible tragedy'' of the violence threatened <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>'s `` consolidation of democracy. `` I blame the authorities, because we warned them we would need protection way in advance,'' said Spanish-born businessmen <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Taboada </PERSON>, whose four shoe stores were sacked by the looters. He estimated his losses and damages at $ 2.6 million. Bus fare increases of 30 percent to 50 percent, and price gouging by drivers were the immediate cause of the riots, but oil accounts for 90 percent of <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>'s export income and the economy never recovered from the plunge in world prices several years ago. Inflation is expected to reach 70 percent this year, double the 1988 level, and the foreign debt is $ 33 billion. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>, in office only four weeks, announced a sweeping reform package under pressure from international creditors. It includes freeing interest rates, doubling gasoline prices and letting the currency float, which means higher prices for imports. Correspondents from Spanish and West German television said state-owned television and telephone companies refused to transmit images of the violence overseas. A government spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said there had been restrictions imposed because televised reports of the disturbances were `` too crude.'' It was unclear whether the censorship was connected to the imposition of martial law, which prohibits public gatherings, suspends the right to privacy and freedom of the press and permits detention without charge. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> said industrialists and the Venezuelan Confederation of <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>, the most powerful labor group, agreed to an across-the-board raise of 2,000 bolivars a month, or about $ 52. That would mean a raise of more than 50 percent for people on the minimum wage.
