<HEAD>For Release Thursday PMs, March 2, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>David Copperfield Defends Illusion of Collapsing Building</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA2 of Feb. 28</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A building falls on magician <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Copperfield </PERSON> during his latest special, but who's worried? The building collapse is the highlight of `` The Magic of <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Copperfield </PERSON> XI: The Explosive Encounter,'' a special airing on <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> Friday. <PERSON> Copperfield </PERSON> is handcuffed and sealed inside a safe on the fourth floor of the White House Hotel in <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C </LOCATION>. The 13-story landmark, built in 1924, is to be demolished by means of strategically placed explosives and wire cables that will cause it to collapse inward. As a Mozart melody plays, the crew shuts <PERSON> Copperfield </PERSON> in the safe, sets the explosive timer and runs out of the building. The building collapses and moments later <PERSON> Copperfield </PERSON> appears from beneath a blanket on a steel plate. Magic or camera trickery? <PERSON> Copperfield </PERSON> was asked about suggestions that his spectacular TV feats, such as making the Statue of Liberty or a jet airplane disappear, are not true illusions but use camera tricks. `` That's not true,'' said <PERSON> Copperfield </PERSON> as he watched a tape of the building collapse on a monitor in an editing room. He had just arrived a few minutes before from <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>, where he had been performing on stage. `` I think a lot of magicians are jealous. When I hear that, it's a compliment People ask me to, say, cure a headache. I say I'm only an illusionist. I always work in front of an audience. There were 40,000 people watching when the building came down. It was all done in one unedited camera shot. `` Besides, the network is very strict. They would never permit me to take advantage of the audience. There are people who are funnier than me, people who are better looking. If you could do it with a camera, they could use anybody.'' It is the 11th special <PERSON> Copperfield </PERSON> has done for <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>. It features such new illusions as dancing ties and an origami box. His guest is <PERSON> Emma </PERSON> <PERSON> Samms </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Dynasty,'' who participates in a levitation illusion. `` I combine magic with a story and romantic music,'' he said. `` We use a lot of contemporary rock' n' roll, from the Pet Shop Boys to <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> to Sting. ... `` It's very important for me to keep my magic current. It's an art form that keeps growing. If more of us were doing it you'd see more transition in magic. Since I'm one of the few who gets exposure I feel a responsibility to guide magic into new areas.'' As he talked the monitor in the screening room showed his various illusions. He borrowed a necktie from a man in the audience and made it dance and drink milk through a straw while <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Belafonte </PERSON> sang `` Angelina.'' The illusion using origami, the Japanese art of folding paper into figures, begins with a small box penetrated by three swords. <PERSON> Copperfield </PERSON> pulls out the swords and unfolds the box until it becomes a large box. A woman then steps into it. <PERSON> Copperfield </PERSON> folds it until it is small again. He then re-inserts the swords. Finally, he opens the box again, and when the woman emerges she is wearing different clothing. `` <PERSON> Emma </PERSON> <PERSON> Samms </PERSON> and anyone who appears on my show must sign a secrecy agreement,'' <PERSON> Copperfield </PERSON> said. `` Even when I build the equipment for my illusions, I give sections of it to different builders. Members of my crew have different tasks. I do have illusion designers, but I work out most of my own illusions. They may suggest a different way to do it.'' <PERSON> Copperfield </PERSON> said he also has a project in which magic is used as therapy in hospitals around the world. `` We teach magic to patients to help them regain dexterity,'' he said. `` For me for a long time magic was just a job. I was in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> for the illusion of walking through the Great Wall. Someone said, ` Look, you're doing what you want to do and here you are in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>.' I slapped myself on the face and I've been enjoying magic ever since.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Elsewhere in television: JOINS `` DYNASTY'' _ <PERSON> Tracy </PERSON> <PERSON> Scoggins </PERSON> joins <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Dynasty'' as <PERSON> Monica </PERSON> <PERSON> Colby </PERSON>, the role she created for `` The Colbys'' several years ago. She plays the daughter of Sable Colby -LRB- <PERSON> Stephanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Beacham </PERSON> -RRB-... ANOTHER MILESTONE _ `` The New Leave It to Beaver'' on SuperStation <ORGANIZATION> TBS </ORGANIZATION> celebrates its 100th episode with a special story about <PERSON> Wally </PERSON> <PERSON> Cleaver </PERSON> and <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Haskell </PERSON>. It's the only television show in history to complete 100 episodes in its original incarnation, as `` Leave It to Beaver,'' and 100 more in its reborn form, with the original cast.
</TEXT>
