<SECOND>BC-Weekly Farm, Adv 05,0904</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 5, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Yeutter Says Federal Farm Policy Needs Steady Hand at Wheel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> makes it plain that he intends running a tight ship through the stormy seas where trade barriers, drought, poverty and foreclosure lurk as monsters of the deep. But <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> also says he is not ready to keelhaul farmers and the rest of rural <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> at the first sign of a budget knife. Some things are done simply because it's right to do so, within limits. `` We still have to have compassion for folks who get into economic difficulties in agriculture, often through no fault of their own _ weather conditions, for example, like last year's drought,'' he says `` And we will probably want to continue special privileges to help out young farmers so that they can gain entry in this business.'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> had been asked to respond Feb. 24 at his first news conference at the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> since joining President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s Cabinet. The question was whether he agreed with a report by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which recommended, among other things, that cuts be made in federal subsidies for agricultural credit. Farming, the commission said, is a business and not a `` way of life'' that should include government props for those who ca n't make it on their own. `` I agree with the basic conclusion ... that farming is a business that ought to be handled in a business-like way by everyone, including the federal government, and that we ought not to be running long-term welfare-like programs in agriculture,'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said. `` At the same time, however, we have to recognize that we can achieve that laudable objective only in a gradual way,'' he added, `` and only through cooperation of our trading partners.'' Thus, <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> shifted into the mode that he knows intimately after 3 -LCB- years as President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s trade representative. He led the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> charge against foreign barriers to free trade and still is a key player in the on-going <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> Round of negotiations under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. For many years, since a wheat-hungry <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> blew the lid off <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grain exports in the early 1970s, many economists, commodity groups, farmers and politicians have held doggedly to the idea that foreign markets offer the potential for prying American agriculture out of its old ruts and dependence on federal programs. One of the reason for federal subsidies is `` because our farmers and our marketers have to compete with subsidized products elsewhere in the world,'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said. If other countries agree to reduce their levels of subsidization, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> can do likewise and eventually `` trade distorting subsidies'' can be eliminated. `` I put particular emphasis on the term ` trade distorting' because lots of people here and abroad have misquoted me as seeking to eliminate all agricultural subsidies, and I never said that,'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said `` We can continue to provide income support to farmers as we deem appropriate, and I suspect that we will be doing so for a long period of time, simply because farming is a volatile business and it is going to be very difficult to reach a utopian situation where no assistance of any kind from the government level is required for American agriculture,'' he said. After his confirmation hearing on Feb. 2, <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> provided the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> with 147 pages of answers to questions that he and the panel did n't have time to cover during the formal proceeding. Those will be hauled out regularly as debate unfolds in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on various farm programs and proposed legislation. For example, Sen. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Harkin </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Iowa </LOCATION>, asked <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> about the future of agriculture and where full-time commercial family farms are heading. <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> replied that `` the economic structure of agriculture is likely to continue evolving much as it has in the past'' with fewer and larger farm units. <PERSON> Harkin </PERSON> then asked about the federal role. `` Federal policies should provide assistance and support to the farm sector in a structurally neutral manner,'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said. `` In other words, agricultural policies should be evaluated based upon their benefits and costs to the nation, but their implementation should not be slanted to favor one economic structure over another.'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> added: `` Attempting to freeze a particular structure in place would inevitably reduce the efficiency of the sector over time. The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> experience in agriculture is a classic example of this.'' The indications now show that `` a family farm structure will continue to dominate <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> agriculture, and I see no reason to tilt farm policies away from that,'' he said. <PERSON> Harkin </PERSON> also asked about <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> policies to help young and beginning farmers, and whether small and medium-sized farmers should be helped to start and stay in business. <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said policies `` should assure there are no artificial barriers'' to prevent entry to farming but care should be observed. `` Helping these folks to start farming is one thing,'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said. `` Helping them to stay, no matter what kind of managers they are, is another. The latter can be enormously costly to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> taxpayers. Successful farmers are not enthusiastic about paying more taxes in order to assist unsuccessful farmers to hang on.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 5</NOTE>
