<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, March 17-19, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lynn Whitfield Stars in ABC Miniseries `The Women of Brewster Place'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Jackee and Mary Alice are full names in 3rd graf</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitfield </PERSON>'s role as a successful doctor helps create the positive black family image in <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` HeartBeat,'' and yet she's eager to range from the mainstream to do controversial material. She's one of the stars of the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> miniseries `` The Women of <LOCATION> Brewster </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Place </LOCATION>,'' the story of a group of poor black women, which presents an unabashedly feminist view of the troubles they have with the men in their lives. The four-hour miniseries, which airs Sunday and Monday, is based on a novel by <PERSON> Gloria </PERSON> <PERSON> Naylor </PERSON> and also stars <PERSON> Oprah </PERSON> <PERSON> Winfrey </PERSON>, <PERSON> Olivia </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON>, <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Givens </PERSON>, Jackee, <PERSON> Paula </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, <PERSON> Lonette </PERSON> <PERSON> McKee </PERSON>, <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Yvonne </PERSON> <PERSON> Stickney </PERSON>, <PERSON> Cicely </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Alice </PERSON>, <PERSON> Moses </PERSON> <PERSON> Gunn </PERSON>, <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Winfield </PERSON>. <PERSON> Winfrey </PERSON>, as <PERSON> Mattie </PERSON> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>, is the central character, but the story of each woman is told. The film is interesting and well-made. But it is anti-male, and black men in particular take their lumps. With few exceptions, the men are ne'er - do-wells who shirk responsibility and desert their <PERSON> Mattie </PERSON> is an unwed mother whose teen-age son betrays her and causes her to lose her home. <PERSON> Ceil </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Whitfield </PERSON> -RRB- is abandoned by her husband after their child dies in an accident. <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> and <PERSON> McKee </PERSON> play lesbians, and when <PERSON> McKee </PERSON>'s character is raped by a street punk she takes out her rage on the nearest man, the kind-hearted building superintendent who befriended her. `` I'm an actress who occasionally does material written by feminist black writers who give their impressions of black men,'' <PERSON> Whitfield </PERSON>. `` When I did ` for colored girls who have considered suicide @ when the rainbow is enuf,' I was attacked outside the theater. ... `` It's a writer's prerogative to write it as she sees it. But I know for myself, I'm ready to reinforce other ideas about the family. I think it's a tragic flaw in black literature and drama that so much responsibility is put upon the artist to present images that are positive. It's unfair to dump all the responsibility onto the artist. `` On the other hand,'' she said. `` It's not fair that there are n't enough projects being done that cover a wide span of black life. So any one project done takes on so much responsibility to present good images of our race.'' She said now that she has begun writing she `` can assume responsibility for what I present.'' She has written a treatment for a romantic mystery movie, called `` Passant Blanc,'' set in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> in 1929, and a presentation for a situation comedy. <PERSON> Whitfield </PERSON>'s role on `` HeartBeat'' as Dr. <PERSON> Cory </PERSON> <PERSON> Banks </PERSON> would seem to come naturally. She is the granddaughter of a doctor and the daughter of a dentist. She grew up in <LOCATION> Baton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rouge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, where the <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> Community Center is named after her grandfather. `` I feel so good when I play this doctor representing my family profession,'' she said. She recently helped select actor <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gossett </PERSON>, a cousin of <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Gossett </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, to play her husband in the series. `` I'm very proud of what we're doing,'' she said. `` We're not presenting a couple that is totally perfect. We deal with our sexuality and our inner conflicts. We do n't make comment about what it's like to be black in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. I am a black person. Being there is enough. I think we need to look forward and enforce the concept that we are equal. `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is a competitive society. You elbow your way through. As a black artist I ca n't think of a better time to be around.'' <PERSON> Ceil </PERSON> is not that different from <PERSON> Cory </PERSON>, <PERSON> Whitfield </PERSON> says, even though the only obvious similarities between the two would seem to be that each has a husband and child. `` <PERSON> Ceil </PERSON> is a woman who has the same desires -LRB- as <PERSON> Cory </PERSON> -RRB-, but without the education or the finances to manage it,'' <PERSON> Whitfield </PERSON> says. `` She just was n't programmed to move up in the system. <PERSON> Lucillia </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Ceil </PERSON> -RRB- Turner is a classic case of coming from a broken home. She was raised by her grandmother. `` The most important thing for her was what she never had, the solidity of a real home. She was married to a man who had no viable trade or profession and was n't equipped to make a good living. She herself was not prepared to earn a living. It's a classic case of our social-political system and how it works.''
</TEXT>
