<HEAD>Japan Threatens U.S. Lead In Markets, Merc Chief Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> threatens <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dominance in finance just as it has in cars and computer chips, the president of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> says. The threat of competition from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> was the driving force behind the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to institute 24-hour, worldwide electronic trading through its <ORGANIZATION> Globex </ORGANIZATION> system, <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Brodsky </PERSON> said at a conference Tuesday. `` The Japanese are something that no one ignores in the world of industry or finance,'' he said in an interview. The Japanese, who once scorned innovative U.S.-invented securities products such as stock-index futures, have begun electronic trading in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION> of stock and yen bond futures and soon will begin trading yen currency futures in competition with <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. The desire to keep business executed through <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> was behind the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION>'s development of <ORGANIZATION> Globex </ORGANIZATION> in conjunction with <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>. The system, in which investments are traded on a computer screen, is scheduled to begin in October. An Australian exchange and the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, which handles oil futures, have said they also will list contracts on <ORGANIZATION> Globex </ORGANIZATION>. `` Innovation of this type is essential if the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> is to maintain its leading competitive edge and remain a leading provider of financial services to the world community,'' <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON>, chairwoman of the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, said when the federal agency approved <ORGANIZATION> Globex </ORGANIZATION> on Feb. 2. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON>, the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, has called <ORGANIZATION> Globex </ORGANIZATION> `` the wave of the future.'' The race to round-the-clock trading, faster computers and instantaneous global communication poses a challenge to regulators such as the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> as well as to an older generation of traders. One eventual victim of modernization could be the local traders on the floor of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, some of whom are being investigated for allegedly cheating their customers. Some outsiders have predicted that <ORGANIZATION> Globex </ORGANIZATION> will undermine the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION>'s chaotic but time-honored `` open outcry'' trading system. <PERSON> Brodsky </PERSON> denied that Tuesday, saying face-to-face trading in the pits has advantages over faceless electronic trading, which will be prohibited during the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION>'s regular hours. `` Why are we here today in a room when we could all be on speaker phones in our offices?'' he asked at the conference. <PERSON> Brodsky </PERSON>'s comments came on the second and final day of a conference on technology and the financial markets sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> Annenberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Kellogg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Graduate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>. In another session, <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> economist <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Summers </PERSON> spelled out a proposal for a tax on stock trading to discourage socially wasteful market speculation. A half-percent tax could raise $ 10 billion a year without doing any damage to the stock market's basic functions, said <PERSON> Summers </PERSON>, who was the chief economic adviser to <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the losing Democratic presidential candidate. Summers was disputed by <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Margolis </PERSON>, a managing director of <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, and by <PERSON> Sanford </PERSON> <PERSON> Grossman </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> economist. <PERSON> Grossman </PERSON> said it was unfair to single out the securities industry for a tax.
