<BYLINE>Smokeless Cigarette Flawed, But Won't End Innovations, Analysts
Say</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Premier, <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabicso </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s `` smokeless'' cigarette, was dead on arrival because of its unpleasant taste, industry analysts said. But they predicted the failure wo n't forestall other cigarette innovations designed to counter complaints about smoke `` Everyone I know who tried it thought it was really horrible,'' said <PERSON> Pavlos </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexandrakis </PERSON>, who follows tobacco companies for <ORGANIZATION> Argus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> R.J. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION>'s cigarette subsidiary, announced Tuesday that it was withdrawing Premier from the market after five months of testing in two states. `` While smokers are very interested in the concept, the current product has not achieved adequate consumer acceptance,'' the company said in a statement from its <LOCATION> Winston-Salem </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, headquarters. `` This is no surprise,'' said industry analyst <PERSON> Emanuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON>. `` It was brought out stillborn.'' <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON>, who works for <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said Premier suffered from two fatal problems: unacceptable taste and aroma. `` What the company was saying was consumers will get used to it, they'll give it an extra try,'' he said. `` That's inconsistent with the fact that we are a nation of channel-hoppers, and if you do n't like it the first time, you're not going to try it a second time. Smokers also found Premier hard to keep lit, and were n't sure what to do with the cigarettes when they were finished since Premiers do n't burn down like ordinary butts, said analyst <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Adelman </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` I thought the project initially was revolutionary in concept,'' he said. `` I think <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> was very bold. But the technology was n't there yet to satisfy consumer requirements.'' Premier differed from ordinary cigarettes in that it did n't actually burn tobacco Instead, smokers lit a carbon heat source at the tip. During inhalation, hot air passed passed over an aluminum-encased flavor capsule and dried tobacco. Despite its innovations, Premier did n't eliminate health concerns. Several health organizations, including the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, last year asked the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Admininstration </ORGANIZATION> to ban sales of the cigarette. Several analysts speculated that the timing of Premier's demise was due to the buyout of <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> earlier in February by <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investment firm needs to cut costs at <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> to pay off the debt it took on in the record $ 24.53 billion takeover. But others said Premier was doomed no matter what. `` I think the consumer reaction was so negative that it pretty much was a foregone conclusion,'' <PERSON> Adelman </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> KKR </ORGANIZATION> did not make the decision to drop Premier, said <PERSON> Betsy </PERSON> <PERSON> Annese </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman. It was a decision by the tobacco company's management, she said, `` and they just agreed with us.'' <PERSON> Adelman </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> spent about $ 200 million developing Premier, and an additional $ 125 million to launch the product in the test markets. <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> had said it expected it would cost $ 1 billion to roll out Premier nationwide. <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> said it had no plans to reintroduce Premier or a similar product `` unless we have fully addressed the issues raised in the test markets.'' Ms. <PERSON> Annese </PERSON> said research on Premier led to much spinoff technology, including some aspects of two brands recently put in test markets, Vantage Excel and <LOCATION> Chelsea </LOCATION>. Vantage Excel has a new tobacco blend and special, high-porosity paper that give off less lit-end smoke than ordinary cigarettes. <PERSON> Chelsea </PERSON> has a distinctive aroma that is being marketed as being less objectionable to non-smokers. `` We have learned an awful lot that will be helpful,'' Ms. <PERSON> Annese </PERSON> said. `` We do not consider this to be a failure.'' Analysts said <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> and other tobacco companies have other projects in the works to reduce the smoke cigarettes emit _ the primary cause of smoking restrictions and complaints from non-smokers. <PERSON> Adelman </PERSON> said some companies are looking at a change in the way tobacco is packed into cigarette casings. <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON> said the biggest innovation may come from biotechnology, which may provide new strains of tobacco lacking many of its undesirable characteristics. `` The 1990s are likely to be a period of technological breakthroughs -LRB- in cigarettes -RRB-, providing you do n't have an advertising ban,'' <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON> said. He said a ban on cigarettes advertising would prevent companies from successfully launching new products.
