<HEAD>Study Says Gay Men Are `Dream' Consumers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Madison Avenue ad agencies long have ignored the gay community in their marketing plans, but a new nationwide study portrays homosexuals as dream consumers. The report by <ORGANIZATION> Simmons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Market </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, commissioned by a marketing firm that represents 125 gay publications, found gay men in general have higher than average incomes, higher education levels, fewer dependents and a large amount of discretionary income that can be spent on luxury goods. `` The survey basically validates what we've known all along, and puts quantitative figures on it,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Di </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabato </PERSON>, president of New York-based <ORGANIZATION> Rivendell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which paid for the survey. `` The gay market is economically a dream market.'' The report questioned 4,000 readers, mostly male, of gay newspapers in eight of the nation's top urban markets. It asked them about their lifestyle and spending habits, including buying patterns in travel, liquor, electronic equipment and apparel. <PERSON> Di </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabato </PERSON>, who says marketing companies have largely ignored the possibility of targeting gay consumers, said Monday he plans to use the survey's findings to urge national advertisers to place their messages in more gay publications. The Simmons survey, completed in October and released this week by <PERSON> Rivedell </PERSON>, found gay men had an average annual income of $ 36,800, more than triple the national average of $ 12,287 as reported in March 1988 Census figures. It also found the annual income of a gay household was $ 55,400, compared with a national average of $ 36,500. Sixty percent of gay men are college graduates, compared with the average of 18 percent for consumers in general. About 35 percent of homosexuals also have some type of post-graduate education. Forty-nine percent of gay men hold `` professional or managerial'' posts, compared with about 16 percent of the population at large. While gay men are 50 percent less likely than the population at large to own their primary residence, they are twice as likely to own vacation homes. Gay men also are twice as likely to travel than those in the general consumer market, and seven times more likely to go to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> than the rest of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> population. <PERSON> Di </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabato </PERSON> said the buying habits of lesbians are not as easy to calculate because of the relatively few major publications expressly addressed to them. `` We have been selling the legend of -LRB- gay -RRB- high income, high education, the low number of dependents, and the large amount of discretionary and disposable income spent on high-ticket items _ like travel and imported alcohol,'' <PERSON> Di </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabato </PERSON> said. `` But other than the legend, there was very little to back it up.'' <PERSON> Di </PERSON> <PERSON> Sibato </PERSON> said the few national companies that have tried targeting gay consumers have been rewarded. `` <PERSON> Remy </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> -LRB- cognac -RRB- has done ad campaigns -LRB- in the gay press -RRB- six weeks prior to Christmas, and in June, prior to Gay Pride Week -LRB- nationwide -RRB-, and it has paid off for them,'' <PERSON> Di </PERSON> <PERSON> Sibato </PERSON> said.
