<HEAD>Zenith, AT&amp;T Partners On HDTV Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLENVIEW, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A partnership between <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> could give the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> an edge in the global race to dominate the high-definition television market, <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman says. <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T announced Tuesday they were joining forces on a $ 24 million effort to develop a processor-receiver and other hardware needed to bring high-definition TV, which produces clearer, brighter pictures, to the mass market. Separately, <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> announced a $ 21.5 million program to develop picture tubes for high-definition TV sets. <PERSON> Pearlman </PERSON> said the successful completion of the two projects would yield `` real winning American technology ... that will allow the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> to leapfrog the Japanese and Europeans'' in the mass-market development of high-definition TV. <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION>, based in this <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> suburb, and <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T said they would spend $ 11 million and were seeking a $ 13 million federal grant from the government to finance the research-and-development project. They said it was the first time two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies have combined on a major high-definition TV research project. Last month, 16 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> electronics companies said they were considering banding together to compete in the high-definition TV market, but they have not yet announced such an agreement. The Pentagon has indicated it wants to help finance the development of high-definition television because of its potential military applications, and is seeking grant proposals. By combining <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION>'s integrated-circuit technology with <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION>'s television expertise, the companies hope to develop equipment for evaluating and demonstrating <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION>'s prototype high-definition TV transmission system The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> high-definition television transmission standard prescribes 1,125 horizontal lines per screen, more than twice as many as the 525 lines per screen on today's televisions, permitting superior pictures. <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> also announced a $ 21.5 million program to develop large-screen versions of its `` flat tension mask'' high-resolution picture tubes for military and consumer high-definition TV displays. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said the company has used the tubes, which currently measure 14 inches diagonally, in its computers for the last two years. <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION>, the only major U.S.-owned producer of television sets and picture tubes, said it was seeking $ 10 million from the government to complement its $ 11.5 million commitment to the picture-tube research program. Industry analyst <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Magid </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Needham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, called the <ORGANIZATION> Zenith-AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T partnership `` fantastic.'' `` They should have a lot more partners than that,'' <PERSON> Magid </PERSON> said. `` This is a very big and important project.'' <ORGANIZATION> Zenith </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Zenith-AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T arrangement `` certainly would n't preclude us from teaming with others.'' The market for high-definition television, including production equipment and receivers, is expected to reach tens of billions of dollars a year by the early years of the 21st century.
