<FIRST>r f PM-AdCosts     03-01 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ad Costs,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Ad Study Puts Average Ad Production Cost at $145,600</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The average original television commercial aired in 1987 cost $ 145,600 to produce, according to a benchmark study by an advertising agency group. The backers of the study say the methods developed for its report will give the ad industry a recognized standard against which it can measure from year to year what is driving commercial production costs. In the past, advertiser, agency and media groups often have come up with widely differing estimates of production costs. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advertising </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agencies </ORGANIZATION> said its latest report was based on a computerized study of production costs for 2,042 commercials submitted by 22 ad agencies. The average production cost is 27.8 percent more than the $ 113,940 average that the same group reported 1986, although people involved with both surveys said no comparisons between the reports should be drawn because of the changes in how the latest data were compiled. They said the new report also should give advertisers more comparative information than they have ever had on how their commercial production costs compare with the average for companies in the same business or doing the same types of ads. It found, for instance, that commercials for fast food, snacks, beer and soft drinks were on average nearly twice as expensive to make as ads for toys and recreation, $ 229,800 compared with $ 117,500. Commercials produced for national advertisers averaged $ 156,600 to produce, while those for regional advertisers averaged $ 102,000 and local ads cost an average of $ 56,900, the study said. The report said commercials that featured interviews or testimonials were the cheapest to produce, at an average cost of $ 76,300, while those using song and dance productions were the most expensive, at $ 277,700. Commercials using special effects averged about $ 188,000, those with animation cost $ 113,400 and those featuring a simple shot of a product while an unseen narrator spoke cost $ 101,900. The average industrywide production company costs were $ 97,400 per commercial, accounting for the bulk of the total costs, the survey said. The rest of the costs came from items such as performing talent, editorial and post-production work, music and travel for the admakers. `` The big news here is that we finally have a way from 1987 on to use the same critieria in measuring commercial costs,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bragg </PERSON>, the Lintas: <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> ad agency executive who headed the study team. Over the past few years, several trade groups, including the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advertisers </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advertising </ORGANIZATION>, have attempted to estimate average production costs, but the results have varied widely. The advertiser group, for instance, estimated production costs averaged $ 124,930 in 1985, but the television bureau said its survey showed costs averaged less than 40 percent of that amount. Even the figures that the ad agency group came up with in recent years are no longer comparable with the latest survey findings, <PERSON> Bragg </PERSON> said. `` We are using an entirely different data base and different criteria for gathering information,'' he said. He said the 1986 study included information from a number of smaller agencies that were not included this year. But he said he expects to have figures for 1988 ads that are comparable to the 1987 figures by mid-summer.
</TEXT>
