<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar rose against nearly all major currencies in moderate European trading early today. Gold prices were slightly lower. Dealers said market participants sold British pounds for dollars in <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> markets before today's release of British trade figures for January. The pound fell to a three-week low against the dollar on market expectations that the British trade deficit will widen to $ 3.2 billion from $ 2.9 billion in December. The pound fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to $ 1.7350 from $ 1.7430 late Tuesday. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar rose 0.53 Japanese yen to a closing 127.68 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it edged up further to 127.80 yen. Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Tuesday's rates, included: 1.8360 West German marks, up from 1.8230; 1.5685 Swiss francs, up from 1.5535; 6.2485 French francs, up from 6.1975; 2.0730 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0555; 1,351.95 Italian lire, up from 1,341.50; 1.1975 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2005 Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 386.50 a troy ounce, down from $ 386.75 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 386.10 In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the noon bid price was $ 386.10, down from $ 387.15 bid late Tuesday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell 59 cents to close at a bid $ 388.26. Silver bullion fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a bid price of $ 5.84 a troy ounce from $ 5.86 late Tuesday.
