<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Trade     03-01 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Trade,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Trade Deficit Widens Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s merchandise trade deficit widened to 2.09 billion pounds, or $ 3.63 billion, in January from a revised deficit of 1.76 billion pounds in December, the government said Wednesday. January's trade gap compared with a deficit of 1.45 billion pounds in January 1988, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> said. The financial markets had been expecting a deficit of about 1.85 million pounds and the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> moved quickly to say they `` should n't put too much emphasis'' on the figures. Monthly trade figures can be `` very erratic'' and `` among the last indicators to respond to a tightening of monetary policy,'' said a <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, speaking anonymously in keeping with British custom. The pound fell slightly on the news, from $ 1.7350 to $ 1.7300. <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> <PERSON> Gould </PERSON>, trade spokesman for the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said the figures show `` <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> is now an economy which can not pay its way and which is falling further and further behind in the competitive race.'' The figures showed exports totaled a record 7.37 billion pounds in January, up from 6.9 billion pounds in December and up from 6.4 billion pounds in January 1988. Imports totalled a record 9.47 billion pounds in January, up from 8.66 billion pounds in December and up from 7.8 billion pounds in January 1988. The December merchandise trade deficit was previously reported as 1.66 billion pounds. The government said the upward revision in the December figures was due mainly to a revision in the seasonal adjustments for 1988. With January's trade in invisible items, which covers services, overseas investment earnings and official transfer payments, estimated to be in surplus by 400 million pounds <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s current account showed a deficit of 1.69 billion pounds, compared with a revised deficit of 1.36 billion pounds in December.
