<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> today rejected a senator's request to delay a controversial overhaul of <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T's rate structure despite widespread congressional criticism of the proposed action. <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> told Sen. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Exon </PERSON>, D-Neb., he will press ahead at a March 16 commission meeting with the plan to change the way <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> charges customers He said the part of the proposal covering interstate service could go into effect July 1. <PERSON> Exon </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> at the hearing of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on communications if he would postpone consideration of the `` rate cap'' plan until two vacancies on the five-member <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> are filled by the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. The commission has been two members short since the beginning of last year and President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has yet to announce choices for the open slots. `` It is extraordinarily important to restructure the incentives that we give this industry,'' <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> told <PERSON> Exon </PERSON> today. `` We have to begin to send a message. The sooner we start on that, the better.'' <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> on Tuesday told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> telecommunications and finance subcommittee the plan could save residential customers $ 700 million in the next four years while giving <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T the incentive to streamline and modernize. But subcommittee Chairman <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass., asked <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> `` why all the people who are purported to benefit from this plan still oppose it and why all those who are supposed to be regulated by it are clamoring for its immediate implementation? The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> proposal would change the two decades-old `` rate of return'' regulation that allows <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T certain specified profits beyond its costs. The new plan _ what <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> called `` incentive regulation'' _ would place a cap on what <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T could charge customers but would allow the company to keep any funds after costs as profit. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> let the plan die last year because of concerns that windfall profits could result at the expense of consumers, but <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> is moving ahead with it after making changes he says meet congressional concerns. `` We've made several changes to satisfy their concerns and we'll continue to discuss them,'' said <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> `` But the commission will consider the pricing matter on the 16th.'' <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>'s July 1 target leaves congressional critics little time to pass an alternative that precludes the FCC. `` At this point, we do n't have a concensus,'' said <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>. Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.M. </LOCATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has left a vacuum that <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> is filling with his action. He urged his colleagues to `` preserve our role in the regulatory process.'' And Rep. <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON>, D-Va., told reporters that <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> should postpone an <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> vote for a second time `` in new of the bipartisan nature of the concerns expressed'' at Tuesday's hearing <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON> was one of several lawmakers from rural areas who said <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> has n't provided real safeguards to prevent <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T raising rates unfairly for sparsely populated regions while giving discounts to businesses and residents of cities. `` Talk may still be cheap in urban areas but it's about to get very expensive in rural areas,'' an absent Rep. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, D-Tenn., said in a statement read at the hearing <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON> told reporters <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> `` is making movement in the right direction, but I think it's not enough. `` I'd say we would have price caps in due course,'' he said. `` But under this plan, <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T could be an enormous profit machine.'' <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> outlined provisions that would limit <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T's ability to raise or lower rates for various customers and said he would look at other safeguards to ensure price changes for less populated regions `` remain within the zone of reasonableness.'' He said <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T would have to cut overall prices by 3 percent over four years under the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> plan. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> also sought to mollify <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> by proposing to divide <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T's services into three `` baskets'' _ one group including residential and small business customers, for example _ and allowing only limited price increases or decreases for each service.
