<HEAD>Xerox Introduces Three New Copiers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEBSTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> introduced three new copiers today, including two low-volume models and a copier with a beveled edge that can make copies from books without ruining bindings. The machines were displayed at a news conference at the company's major manufacturing center in the <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION> suburb of <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> is based in <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn </LOCATION>. The low-volume copiers, the 5012 and the 5014, make 12 copies a minute and come with <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION>'s unique three-year warranty on parts and labor and a copy cartridge guarantee. <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> has always enjoyed a strong position in the mid - and high-volume copier segments, but has not fared as well in the highly competitive low-volume and personal copier markets These new machines represent the company's attempt to increase its presence in the low-volume market, which includes machines that make up to 30 copies a minute, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Cahn </PERSON>, vice president of reprographics product support for <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. `` We're aiming to set the industry benchmark for quality and value in the low-volume range,'' <PERSON> Cahn </PERSON> said. The 5012 costs $ 2,325. The 5014, which has reduction and enlargement capabilities, costs $ 2,850. The company's other new copier, the 5042, was designed for book copying, mostly with the library industry in mind, <PERSON> Cahn </PERSON> said. It has a 35-degree slanted copying surface and a hinged cover that will follow the shape of a book or other bound material instead of squashing it down. It makes 35 copies a minute. <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> officials said their studies found that in 1985 libraries spent about $ 40 million to repair broken book bindings and they believe the 5042 machine will help save bindings. The machine also features a versatile vending attachment that will accept coins, bills and special vending cards. `` We have offered vending before, but it was just coins,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION>'s manager of decentralized product marketing. `` And librarians told us they were tired of spending their whole day making change for people.'' The 5042 costs $ 9,470. All of the machines are available to buy or rent immediately.
