<SECOND>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spending By Consumers and Builders Weakens</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Grafs 1-6 new with Commerce Department reports today, picks
up 5th graf pvs, Consumer spending...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The government issued two reports today suggesting economic growth is weakening, contrary to a fourth-quarter 1988 assessment issued Tuesday that signaled rising inflation and an unabated <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> appetite for foreign goods. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Americans' personal income shot up 1.8 percent in January, the biggest increase in more than a year, but that the pace of consumer spending was nearly unchanged after a strong gain in December. A slowdown in consumer spending would be welcome news to some because of worries that demand has been outstripping the production capabilities of factories already coping with high operating rates and tight labor markets. In another report, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said construction spending rose 0.4 percent in January, the weakest performance since October. Rising interest rates have dampened activity in most areas of the construction business, with fixed-rate mortgages averaging nearly 11 percent. The reports came a day after the department released figures on fourth-quarter growth that worried economists because it suggested pickup in inflation, partly because of the summer drought. While the overall growth figure of 2 percent was unchanged from an initial report a month ago, the report also showed that the country's trade imbalance worsened even more than previously estimated. Imports grew at an annual rate of 13 percent, swamping a 7 percent gain in exports. Consumer spending rose at a robust 3.5 percent annual rate, too fast given constraints on production resulting from tight labor markets and high factory operating rates, economists said. The jump in consumer spending, which went primarily to big-ticket items such as cars, also showed Americans are still spending and borrowing to buy foreign goods. In other economic news Tuesday, a real estate trade group reported sales of existing homes fell 7.4 percent in January, the biggest decline in two years. But housing industry experts said the drop reflected a return to more normal buying patterns following a December sales spurt. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION> said that existing single-family homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 3.63 million units in January after 5.7 percent rise in December to a rate of 3.92 million. None of the reports had much impact on the financial markets. On Wall Street, stock prices rose slightly in what analysts called a reflex response to its sharp declines of the previous week. Bond prices, a sensitive barometer of the economy, fell sightly, and the dollar finished mixed against foreign currencies.
</TEXT>
