<HEAD>New England Monthly Sale Expected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Telemedia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s largest publisher of consumer magazines, said Wednesday it has reached a tentative agreement to buy <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monthly </ORGANIZATION>, a 5-year-old regional magazine that has been struggling toward profitability. Terms of the sale were not disclosed pending ratification of the agreement by the magazine's 59 shareholders. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Nylen </PERSON>, the publisher, said the legal papers will be completed this week and the shareholders probably will vote before the end of March. <ORGANIZATION> Telemedia </ORGANIZATION> said both <PERSON> Nylen </PERSON>, 44, and the magazine's editor, <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Okrent </PERSON>, 40, will continue in their jobs. Despite winning national awards for journalism and tripling its circulation to more than 116,000, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> Monthly's costs continue to exceed its revenues, <PERSON> Nylen </PERSON> said. `` We started in 1984 and we've made progress in each subsequent year _ each year we've shaved our losses by several hundred thousand dollars _ and now we're within striking distance of profitability,'' <PERSON> Nylen </PERSON> said. The magazine, based in <LOCATION> Haydenville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, has a staff of 40 and annual revenues of more than $ 4 million. It won National Magazine Awards for general excellence in 1985 and 1986. A literate, breezy, often irreverent publication, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> Monthly frequently profiles small companies or craftsmen and devotes one issue a year to `` local heroes.'' But it has been harshly critical of some of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s most powerful institutions and individuals. Recent issues, for example, have cast <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>'s leading families and <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>' <ORGANIZATION> Lotus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in an unflattering light Approximately $ 6 million has been invested in the magazine since 1984, and <PERSON> Nylen </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Telemedia </ORGANIZATION> will inject `` a few million dollars'' more to keep it going. `` I expect that the magazine will operate much as it has. But it is not immutable,'' <PERSON> Nylen </PERSON> said. `` What we really want is their advice and counsel, and that may mean changes in marketing, advertising or other areas.'' <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weir </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Telemedia </ORGANIZATION>'s vice president for finance, said stockholders of the magazine will not receive any payment up front, but will be paid over a period of years under a formula tied to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> Monthly's future earnings. He declined to comment on the potential size of the payments. The shareholders include private investors, venture capitalists and two British merchant banks. <ORGANIZATION> Telemedia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s other holdings include Canadian television and radio stations, the Canadian edition of <ORGANIZATION> TV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guide </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Harrowsmith </PERSON> magazine.
