<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Higher Despite Widening Trade Gap</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock investors virtually overlooked news of a wider-than-expected British trade deficit Wednesday and bid shares higher on newly found hopes that the government might be able to avoid raising interest rates. Equities were marked broadly lower immediately after the trade figures were announced before midday, but there was n't any selling pressure to justify the markdown and prices soon recovered to their best levels of the day. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s merchandise trade deficit widened sharply to 2.09 billion pounds, or $ 3.63 billion, in January from a revised deficit of 1.76 billion pounds in December, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> said. `` There was relief that we did n't get a trade figure that implied an immediate interest-rate rise,'' an analyst said. `` It is still felt the authorities will avoid a rate rise if they can hope to do so.'' At the close, the <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times-Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> 100-share index was up 18.9 points, or 0.9 percent, at 2,021.3. Volume was moderate, with 535.4 million shares changing hands, but most of this business came on a spurt of buying interest in the morning, dealers said. On Tuesday, turnover was a meager 357.8 million shares.
