<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>' 824 stores across the nation began reopening today after a 42-hour facelift to complete price reductions on 1.5 billion pieces of merchandise. `` People are backed up as far as we can see. It's wall-to-wall people, said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dumas </PERSON>, manager of the <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Northland Mall store in <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> `` We have Christmas-quantity people, and we have better than Christmas traffic,'' said <PERSON> Dumas </PERSON>, who estimated that more than 1,000 people waited outside for the doors to open. Workers changed prices Tuesday on everything _ including light bulbs, toasters and polished door knobs _ as <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> prepared for a new retailing strategy it hopes will win customers. Employees also had to change signs and displays, take inventory and clean up before the openings, which occurred at noon local time. `` The worst was the screwdrivers,'' said <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON>, a high school freshman who spent much of the day at the Northland Mall store in <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, repricing baby booties and toddlers' dresses `` You had to take them all down, clean each one by hand, then put them all back.'' <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> intends to keep its prices low year-round, instead of marking them up and down periodically for sales. This marks a major change for the retailer, which helped to pioneer the concept of the sale. Last year, <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> sold 55 percent of its goods at `` sale'' prices. The company said it still will run some sales, but for reasons like simply clearing out lawn mowers in the fall. Otherwise, it will use the strategy that retailers call `` everyday low pricing.'' <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, in adopting the strategy, joins a growing list, that includes <ORGANIZATION> K </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> mart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Dayton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hudson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s Target discount chain and <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> and Co.. At the Columbus store, 700 workers scrambled to the tune of `` Do n't Worry, Be Happy,'' as they marked down items such as twin canopy beds from $ 269.99 to $ 99.00, a Diehard automobile battery from $ 72 to $ 64, and a Craftsman power drill from $ 59.99 to $ 32.62 <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>' new strategy meant reductions on 75 percent of its own brands and the 1,000 other brand names it carries. `` I do n't think they had any choice. They lost their customer base,'' said <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sacks </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` I think Wednesday will be a madhouse at <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>. But will they be able to re-educate their customers not to come in just for a sale?'' <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenstein </PERSON>, an analyst with the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said the strategy paid off in <LOCATION> Wichita </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>, where sales rose 15 percent when <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> tested the idea last fall. `` And <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> will invest in an advertising campaign that, to not hear about it, you would practically have to be comatose,'' <PERSON> Greenstein </PERSON> said. The cash register rings about 3,000 times a day in the 100,000-square-foot <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> store, but the only sound in the last couple of days was the clicking of pricing guns and muffled sounds of store officials keeping in touch with walkie-talkies. About 100 high school students worked for $ 5 an hour to help company officials in shirt-sleeves and scores of others with the makeover. `` It's the most exciting thing I've ever been involved in in <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dumas </PERSON>, manager of the Northland Mall store and a 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> employee. `` It's no longer that old sea of yellow,'' he said, referring to <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>' old yellow-with-black-lettering sale signs. The new signs, touting new, lower prices, are in vibrant red and blue. In apparel, the signs are magenta and gray. `` They really needed to do something dramatic like that,'' Ms. <PERSON> Sacks </PERSON> said. `` We'll just have to wait a year or two to see if it works.''
