 Soybean futures prices closed sharply lower Wednesday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> amid forecasts for rain in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s soybean fields and signs that supplies may not be as tight as previously feared. Wheat futures advanced modestly due to an increase in export business while corn futures finished mixed. Soybean futures plunged in the session's final 10 minutes following forecasts for rain in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> later today and over the weekend. The selling also reflected an increase Wednesday in the number of notices of intent to deliver soybeans against the March contract. A greater number of notices indicates a greater willingness among commercial traders to sell physical soybeans, which suggests an easing of supply fears. Soybean delivery notices posted Wednesday morning totaled 9.2 million bushels compared with 4.4 million bushels on Tuesday, the first notice day for the March contract. Wheat gained strength from the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to target <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> for sales of 1 million metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat at subsidized prices, and from reports that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> was bidding for 500,000 metric tons of subsidized <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat. At the close, wheat was 1 cent to 4 cents higher with the contract for delivery in March at $ 4.39 -LCB- a bushel; corn was -RCB- cent lower to -RCB- cent higher with March at $ 2.71 -RCB- a bushel; oats were 1 -RCB- cents to 2 -LCB- cents lower with March at $ 2.03 a bushel; soybeans were 3 -LCB- cents to 12 -LCB- cents lower with March at $ 7.50 -LCB- a bushel.
