<HEAD>Xerox Introduces Three Copiers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEBSTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> hopes a copier introduced Wednesday will save the encyclopedias, dictionaries and other books in libraries around the country from broken-binding syndrome. The Xerox 5042 has a slanted edge and a hinged cover that allow a book or other bound material to be laid flat without squashing or stretching the binding. `` We've responded very directly to a market need,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Cahn </PERSON>, vice president of reprographics product support for <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> officials said their studies found that libraries spent about $ 40 million in 1985 to repair broken book bindings. `` This is very much of a niche kind of product, but it's the kind of thing that will give <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> a presence in places it wants to be, like universities and libraries, where a lot of people will see their name,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Sostilio </PERSON>, a copier-industry analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Dataquest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. The 5042 makes 35 copies a minute and can make reductions and enlargements. It sells for $ 9,470. The machine also features a vending attachment that accepts coins, bills and magnetic cards. `` We have offered vending before, but it was just coins,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION>'s manager of decentralized product marketing. `` And librarians told us they were tired of spending their whole day making change for people.'' The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> asked copier companies to come up with a copier that would n't damage books and would make better copies of bound materials. <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> is one of two companies to offer a machine built with libraries in mind. The other manufacturer, Oce Business Systems of <LOCATION> Venlo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, introduced two library copiers in January, said company spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON>. Also on Wednesday, <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> introduced two new low-volume copiers that are designed to keep the company ahead in that highly competitive segment of the market, which includes copiers that make up to 30 copies a minute. All three machines were displayed at a news conference at the company's major manufacturing center in the <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION> suburb of <PERSON> Webster </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> is based in <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn </LOCATION>.
