<HEAD>Agents Say Travelers Fleeing Eastern Bookings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK REYNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Would-be travelers to and from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> were steering away from <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> as the carrier's Saturday strike deadline neared, travel agents said Wednesday Agents said most customers were asking to change reservations or turn in Eastern tickets. Eastern's largest union, the Machinists, is poised for a strike if no contract settlement is reached by Friday midnight. There has been a surge in ticket sales at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s competitors, said several agents interviewed Wednesday. Agents said participants in <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s OnePass frequent flier program were for the most part sticking with <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, but the agents were reluctant to book other customers on the carrier. Eastern says anybody with a ticket for an <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> flight that is canceled will get a refund or a seat on another airline. Besides confusing travelers in <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s major markets _ <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> _ the looming strike has also raised the specter of disruption of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s lucrative ocean cruise business. At <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Happy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holidays </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION>, which does about 30 percent of its business in Eastern tickets, `` Most of them -LRB- customers -RRB- phone up and say right away: ` Please try and get me another airline,''' said manager <PERSON> Beatrix </PERSON> <PERSON> Mompoint </PERSON>. `` A lot of people -LRB- are -RRB- calling up asking not to be put on Eastern,'' said a travel agent at <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Barry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> who identified herself only as <PERSON> Agnes </PERSON>. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> DiPietro </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Esplanade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> reported that his company remained `` hesitant'' about booking with <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> `` until we learn more about what is going to happen.'' He said his agency is only booking Eastern if clients specifically request the troubled airline. Even travel agents actively booking seats on <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> said they only do so with a warning to customers. Agent <PERSON> Galen </PERSON> <PERSON> Wightman </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Capitol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> said his Washington-based company was advising customers of the possibility of a strike, and warning that alternative arrangements might have to be made at the last minute. <PERSON> Mompoint </PERSON> said agents at Happy Holidays inform customers that Eastrern tickets ` usually get accepted'' by other airlines in the event of a strike. At <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, airline spokeswoman <PERSON> Cori </PERSON> <PERSON> Zywotow </PERSON> pledged disruption caused by a strike would be kept to a minimum. `` Eastern will refund tickets on canceled flights,'' she said. `` If you want your money back, you'll receive a full refund.'' According to <PERSON> Zywotow </PERSON>, agreements between <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and other major airlines stipulate that tickets which are endorsed by Eastern for travel on another airline will be honored by other carriers at no additional cost. That accord, she said, also covers discount-fare tickets purchased from Eastern. The effectiveness of the inter-line agreement, however, was being called into question by several other airlines _ including <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, all of which have reportedly withheld unconditional acceptance of Eastern tickets pending their own reviews of the situation. Some airline analysts have said Eastern might seek protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code, which would make it difficult for other carriers to be compensated. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s cruise lines, which carry each year nearly 4 million passengers _ most of them flown in from around the country and abroad _ could also be adversely affected by a strike at Eastern.
