<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar rose broadly Wednesday, benefiting from weakness in the British pound. Gold prices pulled back in domestic and overseas dealings. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted a bid of $ 383.80 for a troy ounce of gold bullion at 4 p.m. EST, down from $ 387 late Tuesday. `` The weakness of the pound pushed the dollar and the deutsche mark higher,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>, chief dealer at the <ORGANIZATION> Amsterdam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rotterdam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Sterling suffered due to unexpectedly bad figures on <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s trade performance during January and persistent doubts about <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s overall economic health Currency dealers dumped pounds after release of the trade report. In an effort to counter the sell-off, the Bank of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, the country's central bank, intervened in the market, buying pounds. One pound cost $ 1.7243 in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> late Wednesday, nearly 2 cents cheaper for buyers than Tuesday's late $ 1.7430. It was the pound's lowest level since Oct. 11, when sterling stood at $ 1.7175 Later, the pound ended in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> at $ 1.72325, down from $ 1.7430 Tuesday. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, dealers bid up the value of the mark on the grounds that West German monetary authorities soon might raise interest rates to reduce economic activity and relieve inflationary pressures. European dealers had earlier sold marks amid speculation there that prospects for higher West German interests have diminished, due partly to the currency's strength. In <LOCATION> Tokyo