<HEAD>Copper Futures Leap On Peruvian Strike, Supply Fears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Copper futures prices soared Wednesday amid supply concerns prompted by labor unrest in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> and underlined by the small number of copper delivery notices posted on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Commodity Exchange. On other exchanges, precious-metals futures prices plummeted; soybean futures dropped sharply; and grain, energy, and livestock and meat futures were mixed. Copper settled 3.9 cents to 8.8 cents higher on the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> with the contract for delivery in March at $ 1.455 a pound, the highest settlement price for the March contract since Jan. 27 but still well below the record high for spot copper of $ 1.6475 a pound reached Dec. 8 on the exchange. The rally was sparked by news that miners in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, the world's sixth-largest copper producer, would consider extending a planned 3-day strike if conditions warrant The strike is scheduled to begin on March 26. The reports stirred memories of last fall's 57-day Peruvian mining strike, which was a major factor in copper's rise to record price levels. Demand for copper remains strong and supplies continue to be tight, a situation reflected in the slim number of delivery notices posted Tuesday and Wednesday on the exchange. The delivery notices signify the intent of commercial traders to deliver copper against the March contract, which expires on March 29. A small number of delivery notices would indicate a reluctance or inability among copper processors to deliver the metal, suggesting that their own supplies are limited. Only three delivery notices were issued Tuesday, the first notice day, and none were posted on Wednesday. Analysts said the market's bullish supply-and-demand factors and strong chart signals could lead to another run at record price levels. `` It's starting to look like a replay of 1987 and 1988,'' when copper prices reached their last two peaks, said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Demler </PERSON>, metals economist with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Platinum led a steep sell-off in precious-metals futures as the strengthening dollar and rising interest rates spurred a further retreat of investors from precious metals, a traditional hedge against inflation. Platinum settled $ 9.30 to $ 9.80 lower on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> with April at $ 531.10 a troy ounce. On the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, gold settled $ 3.30 to $ 3.70 lower with April at $ 387.10 a troy ounce; silver was 8 cents to 10.1 cents lower with March at $ 5.744 a troy ounce. Soybean futures dropped sharply on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> amid forecasts for rain in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s soybean fields. Wheat futures advanced modestly due to an increase in export business while corn futures finished mixed. The soybean sell-off also reflected a steep increase Wednesday in the number of delivery notices posted against the March contract. Wheat settled 1 -RCB- cents to 4 cents higher with March at $ 4.39 \ a bushel; corn was -RCB- cent lower to -RCB- cent higher with March at $ 2.71 -RCB- a bushel; oats were 2 cents to 2 -LCB- cents lower with March at $ 2.02 -RCB- a bushel; soybeans were 4 -LCB- cents to 12 -LCB- cents lower with March at $ 7.50 -LCB- a bushel Crude oil futures posted modest gains on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> but prices for refined products ended narrowly mixed. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 10 cents to 13 cents higher with April at $ 18.28 a barrel; heating oil was .29 cent lower to .30 cent higher with April at 50.49 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .08 cent lower to .30 cent higher with April at 51.56 cents a gallon. Expectations of a demand slump weighed on the cattle futures market at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> while pork futures gained in a technically inspired rally. Live cattle settled .20 cent to .78 cent lower with April at 77.27 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .28 cent lower with March at 82.52 cents a pound; live hogs were .20 cent to .65 cent lower with April at 44.35 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .20 cent to .50 cent lower with March at 38.67 cents a pound.
