<SECOND>AM-Smokeless Cigarette,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analysts: Premier May Pave Way For Cigarette Revolution, Despite
Failure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s high-tech, smokeless cigarette may have been pulled from test markets, but some analysts said Wednesday the experimental smokes could start the same sort of product revolution that Tab did for diet soft drinks 20 years ago. `` I think down the road it will do real well,'' said <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Garner </PERSON>, a vice president in the <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION> office of <ORGANIZATION> Carolinas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's a little rough, but I think the concept is good and in the next 25 years we're going to see more companies go to this.'' <ORGANIZATION> R.J. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> announced Tuesday it was withdrawing its Premier brand after five months of test marketing in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>. Smokers complained that the cigarette, which used a carbon heat source to pull warm air over a flavor capsule and dried tobacco, had a bad taste and smell. `` Everyone I know who tried it thought it was really horrible,'' said <PERSON> Pavlos </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexandrakis </PERSON>, who follows tobacco companies for <ORGANIZATION> Argus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Garner </PERSON>, himself a smoker, said he had tried one of the cigarettes when <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> made a presentation to investment groups. The flavor, he said, `` was less than thrilling, that's about all I can say.'' `` It was a very strange thing, if you're a smoker,'' <PERSON> Garner </PERSON> said. `` There were no ashes, but you kept flicking it out of habit. It had a strange taste because you were n't burning any tobacco, just drawing air through it.'' Despite his own experience with Premiers, <PERSON> Garner </PERSON> said he expects to see similar innovations in the future. `` I remember the first Tabs, how terrible they were,'' <PERSON> Garner </PERSON> said. `` They tasted just awful, but now you have diet <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION>, diet <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION>, all these diet drinks. It really was a revolutionary product. `` More new products fail than succeed, so Premier's failure _ and I'm not sure it's a total failure _ is not really surprising,'' he said. `` You try to find out what's wrong with a product in your test marketing and they've obviously been given some things to work on. `` I'm sure they'll take it back to the lab and keep tampering with it and monkeying around with it and they'll come up with something pretty good,'' he said. `` The consumer will tell them if they've worked it out somewhere down the road.'' `` This is no surprise,'' said industry analyst <PERSON> Emanuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON>. `` It was brought out stillborn.'' <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON>, who works for <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said Premier suffered from two fatal problems: unacceptable taste and aroma. `` What the company was saying was consumers will get used to it, they'll give it an extra try,'' he said. `` That's inconsistent with the fact that we are a nation of channel-hoppers, and if you do n't like it the first time, you're not going to try it a second time. Tobacco growers initially were uneasy with Premiers because they used significantly less tobacco than regular cigarettes, but <PERSON> Carlton </PERSON> <PERSON> Blalock </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Growers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION>, said he doubts farmers will be jumping up and down with joy over Premier's demise. `` Everybody said from the start it would have been better had it been a product that used more tobacco than a regular cigarette,'' <PERSON> Blalock </PERSON> said. `` But I felt like on balance it might have worked out. `` The cigarette had potential had it proven to be acceptable by the public because of some of the features that it offered, especially on sidestream smoke and the fire safety issue,'' he said. `` Had that ... been accepted as fully as it potentially might have been, it could have more than offset the amount of tobacco used in the cigarette. `` Anytime somebody in the industry tries something new and it does n't work out, you're a little disappointed because it well could have a positive impact on tobacco growers down the road,'' he said. `` My guess is that they -LRB- RJR -RRB- will continue working on it. It certainly would not make sense for them just to shelve it after all the investment that's been put into it.''
