<HEAD>Pipeline to Tap Oklahoma Natural Gas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Coastal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Arkla </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Shreveport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, announced a major pipeline expansion Wednesday that will open up markets in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> to the prolific <LOCATION> Arkoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION> in eastern <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>. Officials said the the project will ultimately mean an extra 450 million cubic feet per day of natural gas can be moved to the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and Northeast. They estimated that would increase the sales of <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> gas by $ 300 million. Officials said most of the capacity expansion will come from a new 200-mile pipeline originating in <LOCATION> Latimer </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> in eastern <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> and terminating in <LOCATION> Jefferson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ark </LOCATION>. They said the 30-inch diameter pipeline will provide substantial additional capacity across <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> to the Southeast Mainline of <ORGANIZATION> ANR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pipeline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a Coastal subsidiary. Estimated cost of the new pipeline was set at $ 120 million. Officials said it could be in service by as early as mid-1990. The announcement was made at a news conference attended by <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Bellmon </PERSON>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordes </PERSON>, executive vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Coastal </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Bracy </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Arkla </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Pipeline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Cordes </PERSON> said officials believe the new pipeline will allow <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> gas to be sold at a competitive price with natural gas from <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bracy </PERSON> said the first phase of the project will kick off next month. `` From Coastal's prospective, these agreements have three major benefits,'' <PERSON> Cordes </PERSON> said. `` First, we will substantially improve our ability to move gas out of <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> by providing greatly expanded transportation and pipeline links between our <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> and Southeast pipeline facilities. `` Second, by using our newly proposed connections in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> to the major pipelines serving the Northeast, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> producers will gain direct access to this major growing gas market. `` Third, our <ORGANIZATION> ANR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pipeline </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary will gain access to the increasingly important gas supplies in the <LOCATION> Arkoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basis </LOCATION> to meet the requirements of its customers in the future.'' <PERSON> Bracy </PERSON> said the project allows <ORGANIZATION> Arkla </ORGANIZATION> to strengthen its access to new markets `` while at the same time increasing the efficiency of our existing pipeline system, which will benefit our current customers and producers.'' The extra sales of <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> gas will mean an additional $ 21 million in gross production taxes for the state, officials said. Those taxes go principally to the state teacher retirement program.
