<HEAD>Board of Trade Computer System Will Improve Audit Trail, Chairman
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> is moving to employ a computerized, off-hours trading system for competitive reasons, but its proposed new system will provide a `` significantly improved audit trail'' for regulating its members, the market's chairman said Wednesday. In a 20-minute speech to the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> division of the <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Karsten </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> within weeks would publicly unveil its proposed electronic auction-market system. <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> said the new computerized trading method would be more than a system for matching orders and claimed it would surpass the <ORGANIZATION> Globex </ORGANIZATION> trading system being developed by the rival <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. `` The system to the greatest extent possible replicates the trading pit as we all know it today,'' <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> said. The Board of Trade informed its members 2 -LCB- weeks ago that it was planning to implement the computerized system for trading during hours when the market's trading floor is closed. Its purpose then was described as primarily to give foreign investors easier access to the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>'s increasing market for <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond futures, members said. Industry observers have said the move into computerized trading by the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> appearently was prompted by a widespread federal investigation of suspected fraud at the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> indicated Wednesday that market pressures were the primary motivation. `` Knowing that our competitors were developing a computerized trading system, we privately proceeded to develop our own,'' he said. `` If I were president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> ... and I knew that my neighbor competitor had a nuclear bomb, I would have no alternative but to also develop such a weapon,'' he said. `` I may prefer other strategies to nuclear weapons, and I may not necessarily use them, but I simply can not afford to have the weapon not in my arsenal,'' he said. But <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> also said `` a significantly improved audit trail'' would result from a new electronic order-entry system to allow greater regulation with minimal increased costs to members. Like <ORGANIZATION> Globex </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>'s system is to use a computer to match orders to buy and sell contracts for future deliveries of financial instruments. Also, like <ORGANIZATION> Globex </ORGANIZATION>, the system will be open to other futures exchanges that wish to list their products for trading. But unlike <ORGANIZATION> Globex </ORGANIZATION>, which the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> is developing in partnership with London-based <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, the Board of Trade system is to be developed and owned entirely by the exchange and its members. <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> emphasized the differences Wednesday, saying, `` It has become obvious to me, at least, and to the exchange, that the technology used in <ORGANIZATION> Globex </ORGANIZATION> is outdated, and as that, extremely costly ... to market users.''
