<HEAD>Defense Opens Case in Stock Manipulation Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-GAF-Impact, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge Wednesday refused to dismiss charges or grant a mistrial in the <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> stock manipulation case and defense lawyers called their first witnesses. <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> and its vice chairman, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherwin </PERSON>, are charged with securities fraud and other criminal counts in an alleged scheme to manipulate the price of <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> stock in October 1986. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> denied defense motions to dismiss the charges made Tuesday, finding that `` the government has offered sufficient evidence.'' The judge also denied a defense request to declare a mistrial for the second time. <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> declared a mistrial Jan. 10, four weeks into the case, because a prosecutor failed to disclose a report that concluded a major piece of evidence had been altered. After a new jury was selected, the second trial began Feb. 1 with opening arguments at federal court in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. Legal and business observers consider the <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> trial significant because it is the first courtroom test of information stemming from the insider trading scandals that rocked Wall Street in the mid-1980s. <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION>, a <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON>, N.J.-based chemicials and building materials manufacturer, two subsidiaries and <PERSON> Sherwin </PERSON> were accused of orchestrating a scheme to drive up the price of <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> before unloading 5 million shares acquired during an unsuccessful takeover attempt. The main prosecution witness was <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jefferies </PERSON>, former