<HEAD>Freeze May Result In Short Potato Chip Shortage</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts lead, adds new graf after 7th graf pvs, `In Putnam ...,'
to CLARIFY that officials not predicting potato chip shortage. Version
moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPUDS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The cold snap that heavily damaged <LOCATION> northeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s potatoes and blighted other crops could drive up local vegetable prices and put a crimp in the nation's potato chip supply this spring, officials said Tuesday. The potato chip industry had been counting on an early and abundant supply of potatoes from this area this spring to replinish dwindling stocks, said <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Willingham </PERSON>, southeastern area field manager for <ORGANIZATION> Frito-Lay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. But now the freeze has turned what was expected to be a bonanza into a season of gloom for potato farmers. `` As good as the crop was looking it would work out about right. It was as much as three weeks early,'' <PERSON> Willingham </PERSON> said Monday from his office in nearby <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON>. The 26,000 acres of potatoes St. <PERSON> Johns </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Putnam </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Flagler </LOCATION> counties in northeast <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> fill a niche in the supply of chip potatoes for a few weeks each spring because they come in earlier than other areas. Emergency boards in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Johns </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Flagler </LOCATION> counties estimated that 10 percent of the potato fields had 100 percent loss, 10 percent had no loss and 80 percent had from 10 to 50 percent loss. In <LOCATION> Putnam </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, the loss was 50 percent. However, <PERSON> Willingham </PERSON> said he could n't `` envision there not being enough potato chips on the shelves for consumers.'' <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Zant </PERSON> of the Agricultural Stablization and <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Gainesville </LOCATION> said the counties have been asked to submit reports that will be sent to the governor's office for a decision on whether damage is sufficient to request federal disaster assistance. `` There is some severe damage. I think the percentage of loss will go higher,'' said <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> ASCS </ORGANIZATION> director for <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johns </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Flagler </LOCATION> counties. The attitude among potato farmers has gone `` from optimism to gloom,'' said <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> <PERSON> Tilton </PERSON>, <PERSON> Putnam </PERSON> <PERSON> Countky </PERSON> extension director. The 5,000 acres of potato plants in <LOCATION> Putnam </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> sustained heavy losses because they had been planted early and were too big to cover with dirt to protect them from the cold, <PERSON> Tilton </PERSON> said.
